<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--PostPoll     08-17 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Post Poll,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post Poll: 49 Dukakis, 46 Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis had 49 percent to 46
percent for Vice President George Bush in a Washington Post poll in
Thursday's editions, a dead heat given the imprecision of public
opinion polling.
   It was the third poll released since Friday to find a
statistical tie in the presidential race, following a string of
earlier polls that found the contest tightening from Dukakis' big
post-Democratic convention lead.
   One poll, conducted by ABC News on Sunday, ran counter to the
trend of a tightening race, finding a 15-point Dukakis lead. It had
a small sample, 383 likely registered voters, and a six-point
margin of error.
   The new Washington Post poll was conducted from July 11 through
Tuesday among 1,119 likely voters nationwide, and had a margin of
error of plus or minus three percentage points.
   The day it was completed was the day Bush selected Sen. Dan
Quayle of Indiana as his running mate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
