<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     08-17 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fox Breaks into the Top 50</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC had six shows in the top 10 last week _ so
what else is new? Fox had one show in the top 50. Now that's news.
   The new Fox network's leader in the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings
last week was ``America's Most Wanted,'' which finished 47th. Its
rating of 7.9 was the highest ever for a Fox series, and led the
way to the network's best Sunday night.
   Fox's ``Married with Children'' had a 7.4 rating on Sunday for
54th place, ``21 Jump Street'' had a 5.8 and 65th place, ``The
Garry Shandling Show'' had a 5.2 and 66th place, ``The Tracey
Ullman Show'' placed 69th with a 4.2 and ``Duet'' was 71st at 2.8.
   NBC won the week _ its eighth week in a row and 41st time this
season _ by placing five of its Thursday night shows in the top 10.
NBC had an average rating of 11.5, followed by CBS at 10.5 and ABC
at 9.4.
   For the 47 weeks of the season, NBC leads with a 14.7 average,
followed by CBS at 12.4 and ABC at 12.3.
   Each rating point represents 886,000 homes with television.
   ``Cheers'' on NBC was the top-rated show, followed by ``The
Cosby Show,'' ``A Different World'' and ``Night Court'' on NBC,
CBS' ``60 Minutes'' and ``Murder, She Wrote,'' ``L.A. Law'' on NBC,
a special Tuesday night showing of ``Full House'' on ABC, and a tie
between ``Circus of the Stars'' on CBS and ``Blood Vows: The Story
of a Mafia Wife'' on the NBC Monday Night Movie.
   Fox said its Sunday night lineup was No. 1 among women ages
18-34.
   Unfortunately for Fox, it is now little more than a Sunday night
network, and a money-losing network at that. In June, owner Rupert
Murdoch he was committed indefinitely to supporting the network,
despite losses of $80 million last year.
   Fox has an automatic liability in the ratings wars: it now has
122 affiliates, compared to 207 for NBC, so its potential viewing
audience is smaller.
</TEXT>
