<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PolicemanKilled     08-17 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Policeman Killed,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Narcotics Officer Shot In Brooklyn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An undercover narcotics officer making an arrest
was fatally shot in the face Tuesday by the gun of his sergeant,
whose arm was bumped by a suspect, police said.
   The officer, Joe Galapo, 30, was shot about 6 p.m. in Brooklyn,
and died at 8:49 p.m. at Bellevue Hospital Center in Manhattan,
authorities said.
   Galapo and Sgt. William Martin, who worked on the same Brooklyn
narcotics squad, were conducting a buy-and-bust raid and making two
arrests when a scuffle broke out, Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward
said.
   One of the suspects turned, bumping the arm of Martin and
causing the gun Martin was holding to fire, Ward said.
   Although police had not confirmed that the shot that struck
Galapo was from the sergeant's gun, there were no other shots
heard, Ward said at a news conference.
   ``The sergeant's recollection is that something struck his arm.
He says it's quite possible it was his bullet that hit the officer.
He's devastated about it. The sergeant said he did not see a gun in
the hands of the person being arrested or any place else,'' Ward
said.
   Galapo, who joined the police force in July 1983, was married
with three children.
   He was the fourth New York City police officer killed in the
line of duty this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
