<DOCNO> AP880817-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Clowns     08-17 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Clowns,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Drought-Stricken Farmer Plays the Clown with `Raindrops'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Heat Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRI COLBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While other farmers wring their hands
in despair and pray for rain, Gene Trimble dresses like a clown and
plays ``Raindrops Keep Falling on My Head'' on his trumpet.
   It may not make the rain come, but it helps Trimble and the
other farmers in his clown band forget their troubles as they make
music strolling through the Illinois State Fair.
   ``This is a way, as one of the songs says, to pack up your
troubles in an old kit bag and smile, smile, smile.
   ``Well, we pack up our troubles in an old horn bag and laugh,
laugh, laugh,'' said Trimble, 63.
   He has traded his tractor for a trumpet every year for the past
26 years during the fair.
   During this year's 11-day fair, he left 300 acres of corn that
wasn't in very good shape on his farm in Newman, about 35 miles
south of Champaign.
   ``It isn't a happy year,'' he said. ``I would say this is as bad
as we've had since 1936.''
   But Trimble said he tries not to dwell on the problems caused by
the drought when he's at the fair. Instead, he puts on his clown
face and polka-dot costume and makes music.
   Of course, there's some clowning around that goes with the music
making.
   As temperatures neared 100 degrees this week, Trimble's
five-piece band roamed the asphalt streets at the fairgrounds
playing ``Jingle Bells'' and ``Let it Snow.''
   The band doesn't play ``Raindrops Keep Falling on My Head''
every day, but maybe it should, said saxophonist Neil Mathews of
Urbana.
   ``If we had, maybe it would have done some good,'' said Mathews,
holding a saxophone sprouting plastic flowers.
   ``We'll have a crop,'' he said of the corn and soybeans his
nephew farms for him.
   But Mathews said this is the worst year that he remembers.
   ``I came over to the fair needing a vacation and about two days
here and I feel fine,'' he said. ``I'm more relaxed than I have
been since I was here last year.''
   Trimble's son, Dana, is a manager for a company that grows seed
corn, a variety he says is more stressed this year than other corn
crops.
   But the younger Trimble paints on a happy face, literally, each
day of the fair, before he straps on the band's drum. He brings a
stuffed monkey, dressed like a clown and holding cymbals, along for
the ride.
   ``These two weeks we spend over here ... is a time that you can
just go and forget all about the corn ... or other headaches that
you have,'' Dana Trimble said.
   He said he has trouble explaining to people why his family
spends its vacation each year in a trailer at the hot, dusty
fairgrounds.
   ``We tell them we come over here for 10 days and wish it lasted
three weeks more,'' he said. ``They can't understand that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
