<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF-EarlyPrison     08-17 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Early Prison,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Can't Afford Tests To Locate 211-Year-Old Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUTLAND, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Town officials say they can't afford
$3,000 worth of tests to pinpoint the site of a 211-year-old jail,
the first prison authorized by the Continental Congress.
   ``The town is in a financial dilemma,'' Town Clerk Irene Amsden
said Tuesday. ``This is not the time to be asking for money for
such a project.''
   During the Revolutionary War, the jail housed 3,000 British and
German prisoners.
   The prison was abandoned in 1783 and eventually turned over to
private hands. In 1828, part of it burned. The rest later was torn
down.
   Two Boston University archaeology students want to make sonar
tests and aerial surveys to pinpoint the jail's foundation. The
state Historical Commission pledged $3,000 toward the tests if the
central Massachusetts town of 1,400 people comes up with another
$3,000.
</TEXT>
