<DOCNO> AP880817-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0535EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CVN--KirkpatrickText 2ndAdd   08-17 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Kirkpatrick Text, 2nd Add,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEW ORLEANS: abandoning SDI.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis does not advocate the spread of communism in
Central America or Africa, but he opposes American aid to the
Contras and to UNITA _ the only forces blocking the spread of
communism.
   Michael Dukakis' ideas about defense differ sharply from past
Republican and Democratic administrations since World War II.
Unlike any of them, he believes that conventional forces can be a
substitute for nuclear deterrence.
   But the most disturbing aspect of Dukakis' approach to national
security is what he doesn't understand about defending the United
States.
   The danger of nuclear blackmail is the first security problem an
American president should face, not only because the Soviet Union
has a large and growing arsenal of ICBMs, but because half a dozen
other countries either have or soon will have nuclear arms and the
capacity to deliver them.
   To speak as though we could defend ourselves against these
weapons with more and better tanks is ludicrous.
   Michael Dukakis simply doesn't take the need for defense
seriously. He even opposed Massachusetts' participation in a
national warning system against nuclear attack. He said a good
communication system _ quote _ ``might make national leaders more
inclined to let a nuclear war begin.'' Unquote.
   This attitude _ that weak is strong, and vulnerable is safe _ is
extremely dangerous. Franklin Roosevelt didn't believe it. Harry
Truman didn't believe it.
   Dwight Eisenhower didn't believe it. John Kennedy didn't believe
it. Lyndon Johnson didn't believe it. Richard Nixon didn't believe
it. Gerald Ford didn't believe it. Jimmy Carter didn't believe it.
Ronald Reagan doesn't believe it.
   George Bush doesn't believe it. Dan Quayle doesn't believe it.
   But Michael Dukakis is more worried about an American
president's misuse of power than about an adversary's use of it.
   The Khomeinis, the Gadhafis and Ortegas, and the proliferation
of nuclear weapons make the world too dangerous for America to rely
on naive, unrealistic, uninformed strategies to defend our freedom.
   And the Soviet Union is too powerful to rely on a president with
no experience in foreign affairs.
   We all (applause), we all hope for liberalization, and reform of
the Soviet Union. I personally take Mikhail Gorbachev's desire for
economic reform seriously and also his understanding that internal
changes are required to achieve it.
   But, Gorbachev and the new generation of Soviet leaders are
sending mixed messages about what they intend _ for their own
society and for the world. Soviet troops are beginning to
withdrawal from Afghanistan. But the flow of arms and money to
Nicaragua, El Salvador, Mozambique, Cuba, Vietnam and to the puppet
government of Afghanistan continues.
   Soviet leaders have spoken of adopting a purely defensive
strategy, but they continue to produce missiles that are ideal for
a first strike against us.
   Inside the Soviet Union messages are also mixed. More Soviet
Jews and pentecostals have been permitted to leave, but the promise
of free emigration remains unkept.
   Which is real: the progress or the repression? Both are real.
   And we need a president who can respond to both realities. We
need a president who knows the world. We can't settle for less.
Mistakes in economic policy can cost us jobs and profits. That's
serious.
   But serious mistakes in foreign policy can cost us jobs, profits
and our freedom.
   We need a president who knows world leaders and world problems
who understands that we must participate and cooperate and
contribute, and protect our national interests _ all at the same
time.
   George Bush knows those things. He learned them from a lifetime
of involvement in foreign affairs. We know where George Bush was
and what he knows and where he stands.
   But in the Dukakis campaign there is a large carefully
cultivated discrepancy between conservative style and liberal
substance. Will it fool enough of the people for long enough to
elect Dukakis president?
   That Democrat who said delegates were told not to talk about
taxes also said, ``There's one problem with this strategy, the
American people are not stupid.''
   And that's right, that's right. The American people will know
better.
   They know there is no cram course for learning about global
politics and world needs and nuclear strategy and national
security. It takes years of study, practice, and being there.
   And, of course, that is why on Election Day the American people
will elect an experienced international leader who knows how to
preserve the peace and expand freedom.
   That's why they will make George Bush the next president of the
United States.
   Thank you very much.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Kirkpatrick Text _ 3 Takes</HEAD>
