<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The movie company founded by
Italian movie-maker Dino DeLaurentiis has filed for protection
under federal bankrupcy statutes after suffering a string of losses.
   The move Tuesday was expected since DeLaurentiis Entertainment
Group Inc. revealed it had failed to negotiate a debt swap with
bondholders that it had termed essential for survival.
   The company, which made the movies ``Crimes of the Heart'' and
``Weeds,'' and the TV miniseries ``Noble House,'' hasn't reported
financial results for 1987, but has released estimates of a $69
million loss.
   DeLaurentiis, who owns 61.9 percent of the company's stock,
stepped down from management in February.
   ``I am profoundly saddened to hear that DEG has been forced into
bankruptcy,'' DeLaurentiis said in a statement. ``I sincerely hope
... the company can be revived for the benefit of the shareholders,
creditors and other investors.''
   The Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing puts the company's debts on
hold and allows management to continue operating the company, under
the supervision of a federal bankruptcy judge, in an attempt to pay
creditors and reorganize.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PADUCAH, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Bruce Willis as a breathing coach,
actress Demi Moore delivered the couple's first child, a girl, at a
hospital in this western Kentucky city, a publicist said.
   The 8-pound, 1-ounce girl was delivered at 7:03 a.m. Tuesday,
according to Western Baptist Hospital and Willis' spokesman Paul
Bloch in Los Angeles.
   The baby, unnamed as of Tuesday night, measured 21{ inches long.
   ``We are ecstatic,'' said Willis, star of ``Moonlighting.''
``The baby is very happy and healthy.''
   Miss Moore recently joined her husband in Kentucky, where he is
filming the Warner Bros. drama ``In Country,'' about a family
struggling to heal the wounds of the Vietnam War.
   Willis, 33, and Miss Moore, 25, were married in November 1987
and live in Malibu, Calif.
   Miss Moore appeared in ``St. Elmo's Fire'' and ``About Last
Night.'' Willis stars in the hit movie ``Die Hard,'' and he resumes
his ABC-TV ``Moonlighting'' duties with co-star Cybill Shepherd in
October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jay Leno will continue as
exclusive guest host for NBC-TV's ``The Tonight Show Starring
Johnny Carson,'' the network's entertainment chief said.
   ``This honor for Jay is well-deserved and we look forward to
having him with us,'' Brandon Tartikoff said Tuesday in announcing
renewal of Leno's contract for the 1988-89 season.
   Financial terms weren't disclosed.
   ``Jay has one of the best comic minds working today and has
already brought his own brand of excitement to the show on his
Monday night guest-hosting as well as during the weeks he
substitutes for Johnny Carson,'' Tartikoff said.
   Leno was guest host of more than a dozen editions of the
``Tonight Show'' in 1986 before signing an exclusive contract with
NBC the following year.
   ``The `Tonight Show' is what I like doing the most,'' Leno has
said in the past.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennis star Chris Evert says she may retire this
year if she wins another major event.
   ``I'm going to play out the year. If I won a big one this year,
I would probably retire at the end of it. And if I don't, I may
still retire,'' the 33-year-old Evert said in an interview
published in September's Esquire magazine.
   But, she added, ``I'll quit when I want to quit. Not when people
want me to quit.''
   After more than 20 years of competitive tennis, Miss Evert said,
``you dream about holding that plate up over your head and winning
a Grand Slam, or Wimbledon, being Number One in the world. And it's
never what you think it's going to be. Because it lasts about an
hour.
   ``You know, the feeling is just so fleeting,'' said Miss Evert,
who married Olympic skier Andy Mill last month. ``You think it's
going to stay with you forever. But the sun comes up the next
morning, and you still have responsibilities in life.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American actress Page Hannah, star of the film
``Shag,'' says she gave an impromptu lesson in a London store on
how to do the latest dance craze.
   ``I went shopping in London and when the young (store) assistant
saw my name on my credit card, she recognized me and screamed,
`teach me the shag,''' Ms. Hannah said Tuesday.
   ``We just started dancing in the store,'' she said. ``I've been
to half a dozen English discos and people are already catching on.''
   The 24-year-old actress, younger sister of movie star Daryl
Hannah, has spent two weeks in London promoting the film, which
opened here Friday.
   The film, directed by Britain's Zelda Barron, is the story of
four girls who get into mischief during a weekend in the resort
city of Myrtle Beach, S.C., in the 1960s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Walker on second reference cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials have dedicated a new
library branch to black author Margaret Walker Alexander.
   ``I don't know whether I'm coming or going,'' the 72-year-old
writer said at Monday's ceremony. ``I'm a little shaky inside. I'm
glad you decided to do this now and not wait until I'm dead.''
   The celebrated author of the novel ``Jubilee'' said she got her
library card when she was 7 years old and has always considered the
library home.
   ``Two of the books I've done required years of research. So I
know the value of the library and I always tried to instill that in
my students,'' said Walker, who has taught at Jackson State
University for 11 years.
   Walker's ``For My People,'' a book of poetry, and ``Jubilee''
are best-sellers that won prizes as her master's thesis and
doctorate dissertation before their publication.
</TEXT>
