<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-17 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search for a tiny, eight-legged
creature called the water bear has researcher Diane Nelson
traveling the world.
   The biological sciences professor at East Tennessee State
University has strapped on snow skis and hopped aboard airplanes to
Chile, Antarctica, Bermuda and Venezuela, where she found samples
of her unique prey.
   Along the way, her habit of drawing close to trees to find the
minute water animals has drawn stares.
   ``People look at you funny when you go up to trees and start
hugging them,'' she said. ``They think you're kind of off your
rocker, a mad scientist. And when someone comes up to you and says,
`What are doing?' and you say, `I'm collecting water bears,' they
think you're weird.''
   The creatures, known scientifically as tardigrades, exist in
high-moisture areas, but when the water dries up, they merely curl
up and go into a form of hibernation.
   ``When the water evaporates they begin pulling in all their
little legs and they stay that way until it rains again,'' she
said. ``While they are in that stage you can expose them to
radiation, very high temperatures, very low temperatures and you
can't kill them. They don't age, all of their chemical reactions
stop.''
   Water bears, seen more clearly under a microscope than with the
naked eye, look like nothing more than a dirt spot during dry
spells, Ms. Nelson said.
   Ms. Nelson grew interested in water bears while working on her
doctorate at the University of Tennessee, where she saw her first
tardigrade under a microscope.
   ``I finally saw this little water bear and it just turned around
and looked up at me,'' Ms. Nelson said. ``It was love at first
sight.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boasting a 95-pound squash and a 23-pound
cabbage, Sarpy County gardeners won bragging rights over Washington
County gardeners in their annual competition to grow oversize
vegetables.
   The victory Tuesday was only the second for Sarpy County since
the counties began their competition in 1980.
   ``This might be good for the competition,'' said Mary Sully,
wife of Washington County Fair agricultural superintendent Louis
Sully. ``We've been stomping them pretty bad since it started, so
this will give them some hope.''
   Sarpy County won the competition 5-4 by producing the largest
squash, potato, onion, pepper and cabbage. Washington County
produced the largest muskmelon, watermelon and tomato and the
tallest cornstalk, 167 inches.
</TEXT>
