<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--QuayleStrategy     08-17 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Quayle Strategy,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pollsters Ponder: Will Quayle Fly?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush played simultaneously to his
weakness with Midwesterners and women and his strength with younger
voters by naming Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana as his running mate,
pollsters say.
   Quayle was not the popular choice: most voters and even most
Republican National Convention delegates are unfamiliar with him.
``Nobody ever heard of him outside of Indiana,'' said Jeff
Alderman, chief of polling for ABC News.
   Indeed, in a national ABC poll of 456 registered voters Sunday,
not one mentioned Quayle for vice president. And in an Associated
Press survey of 1,274 convention delegates, not one favored Quayle
to run with Bush.
   That is not to say Quayle won't fly. Running mates frequently
enter the spotlight from obscurity; Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas
also was little known in opinion polls before his selection to join
Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   Instead, political polling experts said Tuesday, Bush appeared
to address several strategic considerations in choosing Quayle:
   _Recent polls say Bush's weakest region is the Midwest. Voters
there are not strongly committed to either ticket, meaning a native
son might boost the Republicans.
   _Bush is strongest among younger voters, but they are the least
reliable at turning out at the polls. If the 41-year-old Quayle
energizes young Republicans and independents, it would shore up a
Bush base. Also, a running mate 23 years his junior could help Bush
appear as a strong leader.
   _Bush suffers from a well-documented gender gap, lagging far
behind Dukakis in support among women voters. Quayle, however, ran
against a woman, Democrat Jill Long, in his 1986 re-election race,
and beat her in a landslide. An ABC exit poll found he had equal
support from women and men in that election.
   ``The hope is that he can help on the gender gap,'' said
Claibourne Darden, an Atlanta-based pollster for candidates of both
parties.
   Darden also suggested that Bush selected a young running mate in
hopes of asserting his own leadership, an area in which he has been
weak in the polls after eight years of subordinating himself to
President Reagan.
   ``Bush needs to be the boss,'' said Darden, and establishing
that image could have proven more difficult had he picked a figure
as well-established as himself, such as Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas.
   Pollsters said Bush seemed to eschew the conventional wisdom
about vice presidential nominees, that they are most helpful in
their home states. Bush was considered likely to win Indiana even
without Quayle. For Dukakis, by contrast, Bentsen chiefly boosts
the Democrats in a close Texas race.
   ``The track record on vice presidential candidates is mixed on
being able to deliver their states,'' Alderman said. ``On their
ability to draw regionally, there's no track record.''
   Still, Alderman said, Bush's choice was ``a signal that he's
thinking like Dukakis. He's going to run a national campaign and he
hopes to get something out of the Midwest.''
   In a Gallup poll released last week, Bush trailed by 19 points
in the Midwest, compared to 10 in the West and nine in the East and
a lead of seven in the South. But there was a sign of opportunity:
only 27 percent of Midwest voters supported either candidate
strongly, the lowest level in any region, said Gallup pollster
Larry Hugick.
   On age, the Gallup poll found Bush leading Dukakis by 14 points
among voters younger than 30, while he trailed by nine among those
30-49 and by 16 among those 50 and up.
   The Republicans ``have been able to do better with young
people,'' said Alderman. ``But that's the group that doesn't
vote.'' Quayle could help.
   Quayle also is a strong conservative, but that is one area in
which Bush did not need much assistance; he already led by 60-29
among conservatives in an NBC News-Wall Street Journal poll last
week. Darden, in fact, saw a troublesome sign for the GOP ticket in
Bush's selection of a conservative.
   ``Bush is perceived by the great, great majority of the public
as conservative to conservative-moderate,'' Darden said. ``He
already had the conservative vote in his pocket.''
   As Dukakis moved to the center with the more-conservative
Bentsen, Darden said, he expected Bush to move to center with a
moderate. ``What bothers me is there's no reasonable ideological
balance on the Republican ticket,'' he said. ``Balance wins.''
</TEXT>
