<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Wetlands-Greenhouse     08-17 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wetlands-Greenhouse,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wetlands Threatened by Water-Level Increases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal and state agencies should start now to
find ways to protect America's coastal wetlands from the rising sea
level predicted for the next century, the Environmental Protection
Agency says.
   The agency makes the recommendation in a study warning that the
nation could lose from 30 percent to 80 percent of its coastal
wetlands by 2100 if emissions of greenhouse gases continue at
present rates.
   EPA said in the study released Tuesday that wetlands, especially
in Louisiana, could be flooded by ocean waters because of rising
global temperatures and melting glaciers and polar ice.
   ``Based on current emission trends, estimates for sea level rise
by the year 2025 range from five to 15 inches above current sea
levels and estimates for 2100 from two to seven feet higher,'' the
study said.
   ``A five to seven foot rise would result in a 30-80 percent loss
of coastal wetlands,'' EPA said.
   ``Although the timing and magnitude of future sea level rise is
uncertain, there is an emerging scientific consensus that a
significant rise is likely,'' the report said.
   Many scientists say the Earth is experiencing the greenhouse
effect, a warming of temperatures caused by heat being trapped by
an atmospheric accumulation of gases like carbon dioxide, nitrogen
oxides and methane.
   Wetlands are vital ecosystems and wildlife areas that provide
flood protection, filter pollutants and help recharge groundwater
supplies. One-half of seafood caught in the United States depends
on wetlands for some part of its life cycle, according to EPA.
   ``Coastal marshes and swamps are generally within a few feet of
sea level and hence could be lost if sea level rises
significantly,'' EPA said.
   ``Although new wetlands could form where new areas are flooded,
this cannot happen where the land adjacent to today's wetlands is
developed and protected from the rising sea,'' it said.
   ``Today's coastal development could limit the ability of coastal
wetlands to survive sea level rise in the next century. Along
developed coasts, there may not be any land available for wetland
creation.''
   EPA said federal and state agencies responsible for protecting
wetlands ``should now begin to determine how to mitigate the loss
of wetlands from sea level rise.''
   The report said the wetlands of Louisiana, which represent about
40 percent of the nation's total, appear to be the most vulnerable
to a rise in sea level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
