<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     08-17 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says He's Pleased To Run Against Quayle</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Speech in San Angelo sked for noon EDT; may be led</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Until Tuesday, the Republican vice
presidential nominee was the devil he didn't know.
   Now Lloyd Bentsen knows. And the Democratic vice presidential
candidate is saying he won't have a devil of a time handling George
Bush's choice of Dan Quayle, a colleague from the U.S. Senate.
   Bentsen, in the middle of a nine-day campaign swing through
Texas, first heard about the selection when he arrived here for a
rally. He quickly hailed the choice in his speech as ``good news.''
   ``I must say, I'm really looking forward to that one,'' said the
senator from Texas who would debate the young Indiana senator Oct.
11 in Omaha, Neb., if Quayle accepts. Bentsen already has said yes.
   ``I'm looking forward to comparing our lists of accomplishments
in the U.S. Senate, and what each of us could do for his running
mate if we were elected,'' he said.
   ``I've just had a debate with Dan Quayle and it shows again the
lack of sensitivity for the concerns and the problems of the
average working man and woman in this country'' shown by the
Republican. ``That debate was over plant closing, and Dan Quayle
and the administration lost that debate and the American working
man and woman won it,'' Bentsen said.
   President Reagan eventually signed the legislation, sponsored by
Bentsen, but only grudgingly. The bill requires that employers give
workers 60 days' notice before closing the plant where they work.
Quayle fought the bill in the Senate.
   Bentsen has been campaigning almost exclusively in Texas during
the Republican convention. In addition to running for the vice
presidency, he is seeking re-election to the Senate and he has been
seeking coverage in his home state while the Republicans dominate
the national news from New Orleans.
   His events have been targeted for the local market, with an
announcement on the space program Monday in Houston and a visit to
a strategic oil repository in Beaumont on Tuesday. He planned to
visit San Angelo, Lubbock and Tyler today.
   When reporters asked Bentsen on Tuesday why he seemed so pleased
with the choice, he said, ``I think what people are looking for in
this country is substance, and I think I bring that to the ticket.''
   Did that mean, he was asked, that he did not consider Quayle a
man of substance? Bentsen chuckled, and just said he was ready to
compare records.
   Bentsen's aides privately seemed delighted with the choice of
Quayle. ``He is a candidate we are comfortable going against
because of the obvious mismatch'' in experience, said one, speaking
on the condition that his name not be used. ``But,'' he added,
```we don't want to underestimate the guy.''
</TEXT>
