<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CourthousePit     08-17 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Courthouse Pit,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vanishing File Clerk Falls Through Floor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People know about loopholes in the law, but
how about holes in the courthouse?
   It was news to Calvin Jones, a file clerk at the D.C. Superior
Court, but he learned in a hurry when he was helping another clerk,
Michael Morris, move a heavy steel cart.
   Suddenly, there was a crash and Jones disappeared, falling
through a gap in the floor. He careened past air ducts and through
a suspended ceiling and then bounced off a desk, a chair and a
table before his descent ended, one floor down, about 20 feet from
the desk of the building's chief engineer.
   ``I couldn't figure out what happened to him,'' Morris told The
Washington Post of the Aug. 4 incident. ``I thought, `Where did he
go? Where is he?'''
   Jones was treated at George Washington University Hospital for
back pain and was released. He had not returned to work by Tuesday,
and the newspaper said he could not be reached for comment.
   Concerns about lawsuits prompted court officials and officers of
the Sherman R. Smoot Construction Co., which is renovating parts of
the courthouse, to refuse to comment on the accident, the Post said.
</TEXT>
