<DOCNO> AP880817-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--MadeforTV     08-17 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Made for TV,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Paying Heed to Convention's TV Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Substance is the buzzword of Republican
convention planners, but they're paying at least as much attention
to telegenic details as the Democrats did in their openly
made-for-TV convention.
   From a color-coordinated backdrop to a world record balloon
drop, the Republicans are living up to their reputation as masters
of sentiment, celebration and the well-oiled machine.
   The Superdome has been scaled down to a manageable size and
sessions are finishing within minutes of the official schedule. The
demonstrations are running long enough to satisfy the delegates,
short enough to hold the living room audience.
   And no one's outfit has clashed with the curtain behind the
speaker's rostrum. At least not yet.
   Washed with a spectrum of lights, the curtain changes from blue
to red to pink to purple depending on the attire of the speaker.
``We have a lighting designer who is alerted to the color of the
clothing before the person enters, and he makes a selection based
on that,'' said Bob Johnson, assistant producer of the convention.
   An elevator platform at the rostrum makes all speakers look the
same height, both for TelePrompTer readability and camera
convenience.
   ``We try to provide the cleanest head-on shot for the
networks,'' Johnson said. ``Our record is 6-foot-7.''
   Music is another personalized element of the convention. ``If
someone is from a particular state, we will select music
representative of that particular state to give it a personal
touch,'' Johnson said. ``We even take requests. Someone from
Tennessee yesterday morning requested `The Tennessee Waltz,' and we
played it.''
   Personal touches are being combined this week with spectacular
special effects such as the combined balloon-confetti drop after
President Reagan's speech Monday night.
   But that was just the beginning, a paltry 20,000 balloons
stuffed sausage-like into nylon netting and dropped from what
seemed like the heavens in the cavernous Louisiana Superdome.
   Fifty thousand balloons will drop Wednesday night when the Texas
delegation, led by George Bush's eldest son, George W. Bush, gives
the vice president the majority needed to capture the nomination.
   And after Bush's speech Thursday night, there will be 150,000
balloons _ a world record for an indoor balloon drop, according to
Johnson.
   ``Frame that and salute it every morning,'' he said gleefully.
The previous record was 100,000, he said.
   The Republicans, inevitably to best their Democratic
counterparts in balloons, already have topped them in discretion.
   Not for them a party chairman who advises delegates to be a
well-behaved studio audience for a four-night miniseries, as
Democrat Paul Kirk did in Atlanta. Nor are the Republicans issuing
continually revised, minute-by-minute podium schedules that reveal
the power struggles within; their original list of speakers minus
speaking times is holding steady.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, was seen desperately making
the cut sign _ forefinger across throat _ to Arkansas Gov. Bill
Clinton during the governor's 32-minute speech at the Democratic
convention.
   ``We haven't had to do that yet and I hope we don't have to,''
Johnson said with a laugh. The Republicans have reviewed all
speeches and some are even running shorter than planned. Any need
to move along is taken care of by the presiding officer or a quick
music cutoff.
   There was some skepticism over whether the Republicans would be
able to achieve any sense of warmth or intimacy in the 27-story
Superdome. But they reduced the size of the convention floor area
by hanging a 90-foot curtain down the middle, invited a lot of
guests, spotlit the bustling floor and left in dimness tiers of
stadium seats that aren't always filled.
   ``We think it looks crowded and warm,'' Johnson said with
satisfaction. ``The Superdome is a fantastic environment for a
convention.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0031 </DOCNO>
