<2ND_LINE>PM-Nest Thefts,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Robbery of Tasty, and Expensive, Bird's Nests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Birds' nests made of swallow saliva are
becoming popular booty for Hong Kong thiefs, as police reported a
second robbery in as many days of the expensive soup ingredient
valued by local connoiseurs.
   Two men posing as customers tied up employees of a Central
district company and snatched 66 pounds of bird's nests worth about
$57,700 Tuesday afternoon before fleeing, a police statement said.
   No arrests were reported in the case.
   The day before, burglars broke into another local business and
made off with nearly 90 pounds of bird's nest with an estimated
value of $77,000.
   Police spokesman Peter Tiu acknowledged that back-to-back bird's
nest heists are unusual in this British colony. He said police did
not yet know if the cases were related.
   Bird's nest soup is considered a healthy food that helps build
up the body and is particularly favored by the elderly.
</TEXT>
