<HEAD>Montgomery Ward Agrees to End Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission says Montgomery
Ward has promised to stop making claims about home appliances that
the government charges were false.
   The commission said in an annoucement Tuesday that the giant
retailer has signed a consent agreement to stop making reliability
claims for products unless it has evidence to support them and to
stop making contested claims relating to maintenance of products.
   The FTC had said Ward misrepresented the need to buy a service
contract that would cover routine maintenance when it sold some
products, such as televisions, washing machines, dryers and
refrigerators.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Four Replacement Warships Head For Mideast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although Iran and Iraq have agreed to a
cease-fire, the Pentagon says four U.S. warships have departed as
scheduled for routine rotations in the Persian Gulf.
   Defense officials who requested anonymity said Tuesday the
deployments and that of a fifth ship last week was simply an
indication that the United States would not reduce its military
presence in the region until officials were certain the cease-fire
was fully in effect.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci ``has said repeatedly we can
begin to reduce the number of ships in the gulf after a prudent
amount of time has passed to make certain the threat has
diminished,'' one source said.
   ``Our guideline throughout will be as stated by the secretary _
that we will maintain forces there consistent with the perceived
threat,'' said Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman.
   ``The cease-fire is scheduled for Aug. 20. We're not ready to
start really drawing down yet,'' said one source.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Sends Aid to Nicaraguan Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department says that for the past 10
days the United States has sent about six tons of food, clothing
and tents to assist a large group of Contra rebels and Nicaraguan
civilians who have fled to southern Honduras.
   According to reports from the border area, more than 1,000
soldiers and civilians arrived there last week from a central
Nicaraguan combat zone. Another group, estimated at about 2,500, is
said to be en route to the area.
   Spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Tuesday the Nicaraguan exodus
was the result of increased repression by the Sandinista government
and because Contra units have been left without any means of
resupply inside Nicaragua.
   ``The blocking of delivery of humanitarian aid by the Sandinista
regime has resulted in severe hunger, disease and injury to some
resistance fighters,'' she said.
   The assistance, part of $17 million in humanitarian aid approved
for the rebels by Congress last March, is intended to help sustain
the Contras through September.
