<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Protests     08-17 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Protests,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Supporters Jeer Gay Rights Activists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of Vice President George Bush
almost came to blows with about a dozen gay rights activists who
disrupted a speech by Bush upon his riverfront arrival for the
Republican National Convention.
   So hostile was the exchange Tuesday that police intervened and
escorted the demonstrators away. One demonstrator later was
arrested and booked for disturbing the peace.
   As soon as Bush began speaking at the rally alongside the
Mississippi River, the mostly young, male protesters locked arms
and stood in a circle about 30 yards from the podium.
   The demonstrators carried pink and green signs accusing the
Reagan administration of failing to fight acquired immune
deficiency syndrome, and chanted, ``40,000 are dead of AIDS _ where
was George?''
   Bush supporters shouted back, ``Bush '88!'' and surrounded the
protesters. Some Bush backers shouted obscenities and one reached
to tear down a protester's sign. Another man in the crowd pulled
him away saying, ``Don't do it, it looks bad.''
   Police then hustled the demonstrators away. Bush did not stop
speaking or acknowledge the protest.
   Earlier Tuesday, about 20 people staged a protest at a New
Orleans pharmaceutical company, IMREG, which makes one of the few
drugs said to be effective against AIDS.
   The point was to complain about government red tape, which has
tied up approval of the drug for general use. That protest was
peaceful and concluded without incident.
</TEXT>
