<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--HotelHell     08-17 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Hotel Hell,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pallas Hotel No Palace, New York Delegates Find</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crumbling ceilings, falling sinks, broken
toilets, no cold water. The Pallas Suite hotel, home of the New
York delegation to the Republican National Convention, is no
palace, according to guests.
   ``When we walked into our room, half of the ceiling was
convenient, where you could get at it, on the floor next to the
bed,'' Rep. David Martin, R-N.Y., said Tuesday. ``Makes it real
easy to paint.''
   The hotel cheerfully moved Martin and his wife to another room,
where the water wouldn't run out of the sink or tub, but ran out of
the toilet and onto the bathroom floor.
   ``But we've still got a sense of humor,'' he said.
   Chris Cowman, a field producer with Cable News Network who was
covering the convention, said he had to change rooms also.
   ``I put one hand on the sink and stepped out of the shower and
the sink fell away from the wall,'' he said.
   Henry Bayles, a spokesman for Delta Towers Ltd., the
Atlanta-based company that owns the hotel, admitted the Pallas
Suite was not trouble-free.
   ``We're not the finest hotel in New Orleans. If we were the
finest, we'd have (the) California or Texas (delegations),'' he
said.
   The 1,039-room hotel had some problems when delegates began
checking in on Sunday, Bayles said, but he claimed the number of
complaints received since then has been relatively low.
   ``It ran today between 49 and 52, and if you say, `God, that
sounds terrible,' call some of the other hotels. You'll find that's
extremely good,'' he said.
   The building was erected in 1950 and underwent a $56 million
renovation in 1982, said Joanne Caldwell, the general manager. She
said she didn't mind the complaints ``because I'm getting a lot of
free advertising.''
</TEXT>
