<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0408EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Parties     08-17 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Parties,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rolling On The River With Those Partying Republicans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old Man River keeps rolling, and so do
Republican bon vivants who have booked dozens of cruises on the
mighty busy Mississippi.
   Vice President George Bush made a lively entrance Tuesday aboard
the Natchez, a leisurely-moving steamboat. The California and
Louisiana delegations staged a friendly weekend race between the
Creole Queen and the Cajun Queen, both paddlewheelers.
   Insurance magnate W. Clement Stone took over the Natchez for a
four-hour Tuesday night dinner-and-drinks trip to honor House
Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill. Delegations from Utah, Ohio
and Michigan also have relaxed on river cruises.
   The Creole Queen, a replica of an 1880s riverboat, chugged
downriver Tuesday night at United Technologies' expense,
entertaining participants in a program for international political
leaders.
   Forget the brawling, bawdy days of rowdy roustabouts on Mark
Twain's big river. These tourist tubs boast amply-stocked galleys
and bars, upper-deck dance bands, and attendants in crisp uniforms.
   The Creole Queen, with its realistic but diesel-driven
paddlewheel, is host to 20 GOP river trips during convention week,
said bookkeeper Paula Hontz. Most are late-night cruises that show
off the New Orleans skyline.
   ``The attraction is the riverboats themselves, and everybody
wants to see our river. It's New Orleans, it really is,'' Ms. Hontz
said.
   For $3,200, party-throwers may have the run of the Creole Queen
at any hour of the day. ``If you buy the entire boat, we can be
very flexible,'' she said.
   But buying the boat doesn't guarantee the bar or the buffet.
   Ms. Hontz said menu prices start at $5 a head for gumbo or red
beans and rice. Or extravagant hosts can shoot the works at $30
each for smoked salmon, Beef Wellington, Crawfish Monica, or
Creole-style crudites with fresh basil and green onion.
   The Cajun Queen edged the Creole Queen in Sunday's contest. But
there were no hard feelings. The delegations shared convivial
toasts and seafood afterward, and California Gov. George Deukmejian
got a lesson in the Cajun two-step. ``It was a lot of fun,'' the
governor said.
   The Natchez will carry passengers to the outlying bayous or to
nearby Audubon Zoo. For Bush, it made a splashy arrival on the
downtown riverfront at Spanish Plaza, which was jammed with
decidedly GOP spectators.
   A silk-hatted calliope player aboard the Natchez dazzled all
with a shrill, nimble-fingered rendition of ``Dixie.'' Red, white
and blue balloons released from the top deck scattered over
downtown office towers.
   An emcee for Bush's arrival party said 1,000 supporters were
aboard the Natchez. It listed toward port as they jammed the
dockside decks to cheer the vice president. A banner hanging from
an upper deck proclaimed: ``Steaming To Victory.''
</TEXT>
