<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0421EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Reagan     08-17 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Reagan,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Quayle Will Make Great Vice President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, who learned
George Bush's choice for a running mate in a whispered conversation
before boarding Air Force One, says Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle is a
``proven vote-getter'' who would make a great vice president.
   ``George has made an excellent choice,'' Reagan said in a
statement issued after a flight from New Orleans to begin a
late-summer vacation following less than 48 hours on the scene of
the Republican National Convention.
   Before taking off from Belle Chasse Naval Air Station, Reagan
had a brief meeting with Bush on the tarmac, telling him, ``Nancy
and I want you to know that you have all our support all the way.''
   Aboard the plane, Fitzwater said that Reagan will probably visit
from eight to 15 cities on behalf of the Republican ticket during
September and October. He and the first lady will return to
Washington Sept. 7.
   After their formal airport remarks, Bush was seen to take Reagan
aside at the foot of the ramp before the president boarded the
plane.
   ``He whispered something to him, but I don't know what it was,''
Fitzwater said.
   When reporters asked him to inquire of the president, he went
forward, came back and said that the president did not want to say
what Bush told him.
   When news of the Quayle selection broke after Reagan had arrived
at his ranch north of here, Fitzwater confirmed that Bush had told
the president in the airport conversation.
   ``Vice President Bush has made an outstanding selection,'' the
president said in a formal statement.
   ``He's a proven vote-getter,'' he said. ``I've worked closely
with Dan on a number of issues. He has been a leader in the Senate
for a strong national defense, particularly the Strategic Defense
Initiative and proponent of innovative job creation programs. His
talent, intellect, family, and energy will be valuable assets
during the campaign, and I know he will be a great vice president.''
   Reagan's immediate plans are to relax, ride horseback and do
ranch chores at his 688-acre Rancho del Cielo in the Santa Ynez
Mountains. Fitzwater said he will probably also sign some bills,
probably including trade and fair housing legislation.
   Next Tuesday, he will fly to Los Angeles, with fund-raisers for
Sen. Pete Wilson, Rep. Robert Lagomarsino and the California
Republican Party planned before he returns to the ranch Aug. 27.
Fitzwater said an additional political appearance might be
scheduled during this period. As to the question of more joint
appearances with Bush, the spokesman said there would be some, but
he could not say when.
   Fitzwater said Reagan would watch the convention on television.
There is one television set at the ranch, he said. When Reagan was
last there in July, he watched parts of the Democratic National
Convention, including the acceptance speech of nominee Michael S.
Dukakis.
   The spokesman said Reagan wrote several portions of the speech
he made at the convention Monday night, submitting handwritten
material to speechwriter Ken Khachigian, who produced the final
product.
   He said the president's contributions were especially notable in
the final section of the speech, in which Reagan spoke in emotional
terms of his tenure as president and his thoughts of the future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
