<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--KeanText 10Takes   08-17 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Kean Text, 10 Takes,300-3550</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Provides as-delivered transcript</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the keynote address
by Gov. Thomas H. Kean of New Jersey to the Republican National
Convention on Tuesday night.
   Thank you, thank you, very, very much.
   You know, last week, I went to the National Governors'
Association meeting and there was a fellow governor there, his name
happed to be Mike Dukakis. You know, Mike Dukakis gave me this
hourglass and he gave it to me because people had become bored with
speeches at the Democratic convention.
   Well, tonight, I'd like to use it to send a different message,
Mike. Because it proves an important point. Time has run out a long
time ago on your liberal vision of America.
   Tonight I would like to take you on a journey into America's
future.
   We begin, oddly enough, centuries ago, when a ship on a
monumental voyage found itself beset by debate and argument.
   Some wanted the ship to reverse its course.
   They cried, ``Turn back, turn back.''
   But the Santa Maria stayed on its course, and mankind gained a
new world with unlimited hopes and horizons.
   The president that we elect this year will preside over the
500th anniversary of Columbus' journey _ the first voyage in
pursuit of the American dream.
   Historians today agree that Columbus was right to ignore his
doubters.
   But what about our voyage?
   I would not presume to predict the judgment that historians will
make of Ronald Reagan, but I do know they must report the facts.
   And, they will report that today 17 million more Americans have
jobs than just eight years ago.
</TEXT>
