<HEAD>Comments From Former Veep Candidates on Quayle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are comments on the choice of Sen. Dan
Quayle of Indiana as the Republican vice presidential nominee from
some of those who had been considered for George Bush's running
mate.
   
   SEN. BOB DOLE of Kansas: ``My reaction is they picked an
outstanding young man. I'm very happy with the choice. He's a young
man, a new generation.''
   
   ELIZABETH DOLE, former transportation secretary and Dole's wife:
``I have said before that I didn't expect to be selected. Neither I
nor Bob was running for vice president. Bob is running for majority
leader of the Senate, hopes to get five more Republican seats so
that he'll have a Republican Senate to work with George Bush. I
think it's a fine choice and look forward to supporting both of
them and working as a Bush surrogate.''
   
   JACK KEMP, congressman from New York, a front-runner and a
favorite of the party's right wing up to the last minute: ``I think
George Bush and Dan Quayle are going to make a very strong ticket
for the Republican Party. I told the vice president I'm going to
look forward to campaigning for a Bush-Quayle ticket in 1988. ... I
told him, `Mr. Vice President, I want you to know my support is
unconditional.'''
   
   SEN. PETE DOMENICI of New Mexico: ``It was kind of a mixed
feeling. Obviously one set of emotions was relief. This is not an
easy thing to carry around. The other emotion was not
disappointment in the sense that I desperately wanted this, but
there is a lingering kind of (feeling that) I think I might have
done a good job and I won't have a chance at doing that.''
   
   GOV. JOHN SUNUNU of New Hampshire said he was ``a little
disappointed'' at being passed over.
   
   SEN. ALAN SIMPSON of Wyoming: ``You will find an outstanding
legislative record. He's a budgeteer, but more importantly he is a
legislator. ... Dan Quayle is not a show horse, he's a work horse.
He may look like Robert Redford, but he has brightness and brains.''
   
   GOV. CARROLL CAMPBELL of South Carolina, a choice of some
southern conservatives, on how the choice will play in his region:
``It'll sell.''
   
   GOV. JAMES THOMPSON of Illinois, who took himself out of the
running: ``He's from our area. He can speak to the hopes and
aspirations of the Midwest.''
</TEXT>
