<DOCNO> AP880817-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CVN--KirkpatrickText 3Takes   08-17 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Kirkpatrick Text, 3 Takes,630-2110</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the transcript of the speech by
former United Nations Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick to the
Republican National Convention on Tuesday night.
   Thank you for your warm welcome.
   Thank you for inviting me to this convention where we can think
together about our problems and our opportunities.
   Presidential campaigns often become divisive and harsh, so
before we get too deeply involved in this one, I think we should be
clear that all Americans want essentially the same things: we want
freedom, we want peace, and we want prosperity.
   We all dislike spending money on weapons. We would much rather
invest our resources on teachers and schools and hospitals and
housing. We would much rather plant flowers in parks than build
bombs. We would much rather invest in medical research than weapons
research.
   We are not a warlike people. We have no imperial vocation. We
are not engaged in a struggle with the Soviet Union for global
predominance. We seek no empire.
   But we cherish our freedom and self-government. And we wish for
others what we desire for ourselves.
   We live in the most violent century in human history _ an age in
which millions have died in wars and more unarmed millions still
have been murdered by their own governments _ Jews, Ukranians,
Russians, Chinese, Cambodians, and many others.
   And so, in our times it has been more necessary than anyone
wished for free peoples to be strong to protect their lives and
freedom.
   So, the question confronting us in this election is: How can we
use our great but limited power to achieve our goals of a peaceful
world of independent nations? How can we make a wise decision about
who will use our power most wisely?
   The last 11{ years demonstrated how much it matters who is
president of the United States.
   Nearly 12 years ago, a very liberal Democrat was inaugurated as
president. The Carter administration began with high hopes and lots
of apologies. President Carter canceled the B1 bomber and the
Trident submarine and the long-range cruise missile. He thought the
Soviet Union would follow suit.
   But as one Carter official said, ``when we built, they built,
and when we stopped building, they built.'' President Carter said
he learned a lot about the Soviet Union when its armies invaded
Afghanistan and began their ghastly war against the Afghan people.
   By the time this ``learning experience'' had taken place, the
United States and the West had lost military superiority. The
Soviet Union had become a global power, a dozen countries had
effectively lost their independence, America had lost credibility
and freedom was in retreat.
   Neither the United States nor the world can afford another
``learning experience'' like that for an American president.
   By the time Jimmy Carter left office, the United States and the
Soviet Union were barely on speaking terms. Arms talks had been
broken off. Cultural exchanges canceled. The United States had
imposed an embargo on grain, and a boycott on the Olympics.
   But today, eight years later, it's fair to say that American
relations with the Soviet Union have never been better. Cultural
and educational exchange programs have been restored and expanded.
So have trade agreements and scientific cooperation.
   One arms agreement has been signed and another is well along the
way. And we are at peace.
   Some of this improvement reflects a new Soviet leader with
different ideas. But much of it is due to the restored strength and
purpose and confidence and skill and persistence of the United
States.
   When the Soviets walked out on arms talks in Geneva, SDI brought
them back to the bargaining table. Mikhail Gorbachev doesn't give
something for nothing.
   The Reagan-Bush administration has known how to strike a bargain
and has had assets to bargain with and the will to persist.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0543EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CVN--KirkpatrickText 1stAdd   08-17 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Kirkpatrick Text, 1st Add,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEW ORLEANS: to persist.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   We Americans should ask ourselves: What improves relations? What
strengthens peace? What promotes democracy? What works? A policy of
unilateral concessions and wishful thinking or a policy of strength
and clarity?
   Eight years of American prosperity, peace, and responsible
participation in the world have been good for us and good for
others. And in London and Kabul and Tel Aviv and Abijan and in
Warsaw, and all around the world, people know it.
   Everyone seems to know it _ but the Democratic leadership.
   They said the last seven years had _ and I quote _ ``witnessed
an unprecedented assault on our national interest and national
security.''
   Apparently the Dukakis Democrats do not understand how the
prudent use of American power has helped ... in Afghanistan,
Grenada, and the Persian Gulf and in the fight against
international terrorism and drugs and in the struggle for democracy
in Central America, and Asia.
   That's the bad news. The good news is _ George Bush knows better.
   Apparently the Dukakis Democrats do not understand the role of
American power in strengthening and protecting Israel, or in
negotiating the withdrawal of Soviet missiles that threatened
Western Europe. That's the bad news.
   The good news is: George Bush knows better.
   More bad news: the Dukakis Democrats do not understand how
American power helped promote arms negotiations with the Soviet
Union.
   But the good news is: George Bush knows better, and so does Dan
Quayle.
   The Democrats who met in Atlanta took pains to look nice and not
to talk much about their plans and policies. One delegate to the
Democratic convention explained why they acted the way they did. He
said, ``We're told it doesn't make political sense to talk about
taxes. We're told we should be vague and after we win, we'll get
down to business.''
   Generally speaking, the Democratic delegates did as they were
told. They didn't talk about taxes or about deep unilateral defense
cuts or about Nicaragua.
   They didn't talk about much.
   They left it to us to figure out for ourselves what will happen
when they ``get down to business.''
   Their candidate, another very liberal governor with a
technocratic style and no foreign policy experience, is attempting
now to repeat what Jimmy Carter performed in 1976 in presenting
himself as a man more concerned with competence than with ideology.
   But if you read the Democratic platform, if you listen to their
speeches, if you look at their record, it is clear that the basic
approach has not changed since George McGovern was nominated in
1972, and since Jimmy Carter was elected in 1976.
   That approach features collectivism in domestic affairs,
weakness in defense and deep confusion about America's role in the
world.
   Actually, in spite of their convention's blackout on discussion
of foreign policy, we know a good deal about Michael Dukakis'
approach to foreign affairs _ and what we know is deeply disturbing.
   We know, for example, that he never felt it necessary to
disagree with the policies of Jesse Jackson. We know he's proposed
deep unilateral cuts in most of our weapon systems. We know he said
he would end missile test flights and nuclear testing, that he
would end work on SDI and a missile defense system, and ban
anti-satellite weapons.
   We know he calls for a ``stable nuclear deterrent.'' He imagines
that we can maintain that stable deterrence without developing any
new weapons while the Soviet Union continues to produce new
offensive and defensive arms. We know Dukakis favors arms
negotiations, but his proposed unilateral cuts would leave the
Soviet Union no incentive to negotiate.
   Today foreign policy is vital to our economy, and our security.
Today it is a matter of life and death. Americans deserve a
straight discussion of what a would-be president plans for us. But
Dukakis evades such discussion.
   Michael Dukakis doesn't say he will make America more
vulnerable, but that is the inevitable consequence of unilaterally
canceling our major weapons systems.
   Michael Dukakis doesn't say he will leave us defenseless against
Soviet missiles, but that is the inevitable consequence of
abandoning SDI.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
