<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-17 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Rally, Dollar Gains Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose across the board Wednesday on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange, while the dollar gained marginally against
the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 255 selected issues, the main index
of the exchange, gained 282.31 points, or 1.01 percent, from the
previous day's close, to finish the day's trade at 28,178.86.
   The dollar closed at 133.15 yen, up 0.07 yen from Tuesday's
close of 133.08 yen. After opening at 133.17 yen, the currency
moved in a range of 133.00-133.35 yen in hectic trading.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange was 850
million shares.
   Traders said a wider-than-expected U.S. trade report did not
have a negative effect on the Tokyo market. The U.S. Commerce
Department reported Tuesday that the American trade deficit widened
to $12.5 billion in June from a revised $9.8 billion in May.
   ``The dollar is still maintaining its ground against other
currencies, and we don't expect any abrupt changes on the Tokyo
market'' said a stock broker at a major securities firm in Tokyo.
   ``The U.S. trade deficit is not a negative factor for us,'' he
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The dollar plunged overnight in New York following the release
of the report, but rebounded sharply by the close of trading to
finish at 133.73 yen, up from 133.32 yen late Monday.
</TEXT>
