<HEAD>Text Of Bush, Quayle Remarks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of remarks by Vice
President George Bush and Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana at a rally
Tuesday where Bush, the soon-to-be Republican presidential nominee,
announced his selection of Quayle as his vice presidential running
mate.
   Bush: Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.
   Barbara and I are delighted to be here.
   We pay our respects to Frank Fahrenkopf and all that have made
this marvelous convention possible.
   And I want to thank Peggy Wilson and the others for putting this
on, this marvelous welcoming event.
   Let me just tell you first how pleased we are to be here.
   And we're starting on a new era, because over the past years
we've turned around the failed and faltering policies of our
predecessors.
   We have made progress, and now I want to lead us into the future.
   We have made progress, but we can and we must do even better.
   We can spread the opportunity further.
   We can tackle new problems.
   We can advance peace and growth to even more corners of the
world.
   And I promise you that as president, I will make sure that
America remains the greatest and the freest nation on the face of
the Earth.
   Great progress has been made.
   The Soviets are pulling out of Afghanistan, the Vietnamese out
of Cambodia, the possibility of a Cuban pullout of Angola, a truce
possibly between Iran and Iraq.
   Peace is breaking out all over.
   Our policies are working, and now I want to build on them.
   America is back _ strong, proud, growing, at peace.
   It's working.
   And so I ask you today, do you want to throw it all away and
turn the crowd over to the crowd who brought you that malaise?
   No, we do not want to do that.
   Do you want the big spenders to raise your taxes?
   (Crowd: ``No!'')
   Do you want those central planners to bring back that
double-digit inflation and the interest rates over 20 percent?
   (Crowd: ``No!'')
   Do you want to send our reinvigorated military forces into
retreat?
   (Crowd: ``No!'')
   And do you want to risk the results of eight years of
achievements at home and abroad?
   (Chants of ``No!'')
   I don't think so.
   And that's why I'm here, and I have a different vision of
America.
</TEXT>
