<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RoosterFlap     08-17 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rooster Flap,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighbors Crowing About Rooster, Pet Owner May Roost in Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Sanchez' neighbors are crowing
about his 15-pound rooster, and the city says the pet has ruffled
too many feathers in the tranquil neighborhood.
   Sanchez has run afoul of the law _ illegally harboring a rooster
in a residential area. If he loses his fight to keep Travis the
rooster, he could be sentenced to six months in jail and fined
$1,000 on each of four misdemeanmor counts.
   ``Can you believe it? I might end up in county jail with
burglars and thieves. And I'll be there because of a chicken,''
said the 26-year-old Sanchez, who's been fighting the city over the
law for two years.
   His trial begins Monday.
   Deputy City Attorney Frank Rhemrev said he doubts the maximum
sentence will be assessed.
   Many people have told Sanchez he shouldn't risk jail for a
rooster.
   ``You can get warm and cuddly about a rooster just like you can
about a cat or a dog,'' Sanchez said about his 7-year-old rooster.
``Travis is real friendly. ... He's a companion, just like any
other pet.
   ``He just happens to be a chicken.''
   Public Defender Linda Van Winkle has given up trying to talk him
into giving up Travis.
   ``I ask him, `How long do roosters live, anyway?' But he told me
Travis has a good three years left. And I don't think I can get the
case continued for that long,'' the lawyer said.
   Rhemrev said neighbors began complaining about the rooster's
crowing in 1986.
   Sanchez said Travis was 3 years old and living in his back yard
when the law was passed in 1984. Thus, Sanchez said, the rooster
should be the beneficiary of a grandfather clause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
