<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Peru-MineStrike     08-17 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-Mine Strike,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Agreement Reported Reached in Mine Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government and labor leaders have agreed on a
plan to settle a monthlong mining strike that nearly paralyzed
Peru's vital silver industry.
   Prime Minister Armando Villanueva and Valetin Pacho,
secretary-general of the General Confederation of Peruvian Workers,
said late Tuesday that a tentative agreement had been reached to
end the strike, which began July 18.
   Details of the settlement were not disclosed. It was unclear
when or if miners would return to work.
   The National Federation of Mine, Metal and Steel Workers called
the strike to demand unified labor contracts for all unionized
miners. The federation claims to represent 75 percent of Peru's
estimated 80,000 to 100,000 mine workers.
   The federation said more than 90 percent of the mining industry
was affected the strike. Industry analysts said the figure was
closer to 60 percent.
   The strike affected mineral mines in general, but hit the silver
industry particularly hard. Peru is the world's second leading
producer of silver behind Mexico. It is also a major source of
copper, lead, zinc and gold.
   Mining traditionally accounts for half of Peru's exports. Total
mineral exports last year were $1.2 billion, with silver accounting
for $300 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
