<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Briefs,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Sen. Hawkins Talking About Running for Office Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Paula Hawkins of Florida, who has
recovered from a back injury which threatened to make her an
invalid, is feeling so good she's talking about running for
elective office again.
   Mrs. Hawkins, who was Florida's most prominent Republican
officeholder for more than a decade before her loss to former Gov.
Bob Graham in the 1986 Senate race, said she would prefer staying
in Florida to returning to Washington.
   ``I've been elected three times in Florida statewide and people
remember that,'' she said. ``I like serving.''
   The Republican National Convention has been a coming out of
sorts for the 61-year-old grandmother, who spent most of 1987
recovering from a series of operations to correct a chronic back
problem.
   ``The voters did me a great favor,'' Mrs. Hawkins said. ``They
said, `You need to get a new body.'''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Connecticut Woman Thought Bush Was Beckoning Her to Podium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a brief, comical moment, Adeline
MacDermid thought George Bush was beckoning her to the podium
Tuesday when he announced his choice for a running mate.
   But it turned out that Mrs. MacDermid, of Plymouth, Conn., just
happened to be standing next to 41-year-old Sen. Dan Quayle of
Indiana, the man Bush named as his choice for the Republican
nominee for vice president.
   Bush made the announcement while standing on the banks of the
Mississippi River after he arrived in town by riverboat for the
Republican National Convention. Mrs. MacDermid, an alternate
delegate, was standing in the fenced-off section for delegates and
guests.
   ``All of a sudden we saw Vice President George Bush and I think
it was a Secret Service man pointing in our direction,'' Mrs.
MacDermid said.
   ``I thought he wanted me,'' Mrs. MacDermid said. ``Then he
started saying, `I have a very special announcement.'''
   It dawned on her what was going on when ``we looked around and
saw this young man who was trying to get through the crowd.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Companies Scramble, Produce Bush-Quayle Buttons Within Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enterprising entrepreneurs had Bush-Quayle
political buttons on the streets within hours of George Bush's
surprise announcement that Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle was his running
mate on the GOP ticket.
   A man from Dallas, who refused to give his name, printed up the
first Bush-Quayle buttons Tuesday, beating the several button
companies doing GOP convention business.
   Bush announced Quayle as his choice about 4 p.m. CDT and the
simple white buttons with red letters saying ``Bush-Quayle'' were
sold by 5:30 p.m. on consignment to the Horn of Plenty Store.
   ``I don't have any company. I just knew of a fellow in the
French Quarter who had the capacity to put these out and voila!,''
said the Dallas man, who was identified by Horn of Plenty clerks as
the quick supplier of the buttons.
   
   More elaborate buttons, 200 bearing Quayle's photo, went on sale
at 9:45 p.m. at Political Americana Ltd., where clerk Megan Warlick
said 25 were sold at $10 each within the first 15 minutes. Several
hundred buttons were sold at $5 each within a few hours.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bay State Republicans Step Up Anti-Dukakis Efforts At Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Republicans have stepped up
their ``truth squad'' assaults on Michael Dukakis, releasing a
video attacking the governor and displaying huge anti-Dukakis signs
on the convention floor.
   State Party Chairman Ray Shamie released the 10-minute tape
Tuesday at an afternoon reception. The video juxtaposes segments of
the Massachusetts governor's acceptance speech last month in
Atlanta at the Democratic National Convention with local
Republicans, each taking on separate topics.
   The tape attacks Dukakis on the loss of manufacturing jobs in
the state, which regularly has among the lowest unemployment
figures in the nation, a controversial policy implemented by a
predecessor that allowed furloughs for some convicted killers, the
state's fiscal woes, pollution in Boston Harbor and problems
involving Dukakis administration officials.
   At the Louisiana Superdome, where the convention is being held,
delegates held up 6-by-12-foot signs lambasting the governor on
such issues as the state budget problems. Off the floor, state
Republicans played the tape for passing delegates and distributed
anti-Dukakis materials.
</TEXT>
