<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WindshieldWashers     08-17 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Windshield Washers,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koch's Next Target: Windshield Washers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panhandling windshield washers often intimidate
drivers, going so far as to smack a car window if they don't get
money for their unsolicited services, says Mayor Edward I. Koch,
who wants to regulate them.
   ``I believe they're horrible,'' Koch said Tuesday. ``We're going
to address this issue. It's a police issue.''
   The mayor, who drew criticism recently when he urged people not
to give money to beggars, predicted his move against the windshield
washers will bring him more flak.
   The windshield washers, who have proliferated in recent years,
stand at busy street corners and rush out uninvited to clean the
front windows of cars that stop for lights. They then ask for a tip.
   Many motorists complain that the washers use filthy rags and
leave the glass streaked and dirtier than before. There have been
some incidents of violence by windshield washers when motorists
refused to pay them.
   Koch said he was concerned about intimidation by the washers.
   ``Suddenly, if three or four guys descend on your car and
without asking you they start to polish it up with dirty rags and
filthy squeegees and dirty water and you say to yourself, `I don't
want it', but you can't stop it, what are you going to do, fight
with these guys?''
   Koch said he did not know if it was a crime to wash windshields
when not asked to, but if the panhandler intimidates the driver or
passengers, it might be a form of harassment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--ReparationsProtest     08-17 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Reparations Protest,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WWII Veteran Returns Medals To Protest Japanese-American
Reparations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENBROOK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government should have stopped
short of paying reparations to Japanese-Americans interned during
World War II, says one war veteran who has turned in his Army
medals to protest the decision.
   ``I personally think that a verbal apology would have been
enough for these people,'' said Frank Gonzol, of Middlesex Borough.
   The retired 69-year-old mechanic turned in his 11 medals and
accreditations to the office of Rep. Matthew Rinaldo despite
efforts by Rinaldo's staff to dissuade him, said Robert DeLazaro,
an aide to the Republican congressman.
   Rinaldo, who voted in favor of the reparations, represents
Gonzol's district.
   Gonzol said he served from 1942-45 and saw combat action in
Africa, Sicily and other parts of Europe.
   The reparations signed last week by Presdient Reagan authorizes
tax-free payments of $20,000 to each of the approximately 60,000
surviving Japanese-Americans who were placed in camps during the
war.
</TEXT>
