<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Flight255     08-17 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flight 255,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Victims Remembered On Anniversary Of Nation's Second-Worst Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends, family members and others touched
by the crash of Northwest Flight 255 gathered a year later on a
grassy hillside at the crash site to remember the 156 victims.
   ``Of all the days in the past year, this may be one of the worst
for you who have lost your loved ones,'' the Rev. Ron Lund, pastor
of Bethany Lutheran Church in Roseville, told about 1,000 people at
the Tuesday night observance near Detroit Metropolitan Airport.
   ``It is a very special night, a night of remembrance, a night of
sadness, a night of knowing that Flight 255 is in the arms of God
tonight,'' he said.
   ``Where else could we be today?'' asked Betty Polec of Mount
Clemens, whose daughter and son-in-law died in the Aug. 16, 1987,
crash _ the nation's second-worst air disaster. She co-founded a
support group for the victims' relatives.
   Relatives, friends and a few people unknown to the victims stood
next to 156 plastic foam hearts arranged to form the numeral 255.
Each bore an artificial rose and a ribbon with a victim's name;
flowers were laid at some of them.
   Aircraft roared overhead as Lund pointed out a wispy pink cloud
in the shape of a dove _ the symbol adopted by the support group _
in the darkening sky.
   ``If you don't believe in miracles, look ... and see the dove in
the air,'' he said.
   At 7:46 p.m. _ the hour and minute of the crash _ the names of
the victims were read. As each name was called out, tiny penlights
were turned on and held up until they formed ``255'' in the
gathering darkness.
   The Phoenix-bound MD-80 aircraft broke apart in flames less than
a minute after takeoff from Metropolitan Airport. Two people on the
ground and all but one of the 155 people aboard the plane died.
   The only survivor was Cecelia Cichan, 4, of Tempe, Ariz., whose
parents and brother died in the crash. No Cichan family members
were present Tuesday. They were represented by two employees at the
University of Michigan Medical Center, where Cecelia spent 68 days
recovering.
   Cecelia is living with an aunt and uncle in Birmingham, Ala.
   ``I'm sure their thoughts are going to be with everyone here,''
said Catherine Cureton, a hospital spokeswoman.
   Also on hand was Allison Maus of Las Vegas, Nev., the widow of
the plane's pilot, John Maus.
   Although investigators linked the crash to pilot error, Mrs.
Maus said she has been comforted by relatives of the passengers.
   ``There was never any peace to be made. They all realize my
husband was killed, just like their family and friends, and I
consider them my very dear friends,'' she said.
   The National Transportation Safety Board issued a finding May 10
that Flight 255's two pilots failed to set the airplane's flaps
properly.
   Attorneys have filed 106 lawsuits over the crash, and 10
settlements have been reached.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
