<1ST_LINE>r p PM-WyomingPrimary     08-17 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wyoming Primary,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It's Vinich Vs. Wallop For U.S. Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrons of John Vinich's Union Bar and
Lounge boisterously celebrated the Democrat's triumph in Wyoming's
hotly contested U.S. Senate primary, but the nominee faces a battle
to unseat Republican Sen. Malcolm Wallop in November.
   ``Wyoming people are ready for a change and I think by working
in a grass-roots kind of campaign, Wyoming will be able to make
Malcolm Wallop be a man of his word and limit him to two terms,''
Vinich said over the din of revellers who packed his bar in the
tiny town of Hudson.
   Complete, unofficial returns from Wyoming's primary Tuesday
showed Vinich, a state senator with 14 years' legislative
experience, with 23,165 votes, or 47 percent, in the Democratic
primary.
   University of Wyoming Professor Pete Maxfield ran second, with
14,595 votes, or 30 percent, while state schools Superintendent
Lynn Simons had 11,312 votes, or 23 percent.
   Wallop coasted to his third GOP Senate nomination, amassing
55,696 votes, or 83 percent, with all of Wyoming's 474 precincts
reporting. Wallop's four opponents _ Michael Dee, Russ Hanrahan,
Nora Marie Lewis, and I.W. ``Bud'' Kinney _ did not conduct highly
visible campaigns.
   Twelve years ago Wallop pledged to stay just two terms in the
Senate, but this year he changed his mind, saying that challenges
to Wyoming's way of life, its environment and the state's and the
nation's defense made a third term necessary.
   Official totals in the races likely will differ slightly, as a
federal judge on Tuesday ordered state elections officials to count
any absentee ballots that arrive by the end of business Monday.
   The order stemmed from a Justice Department lawsuit claiming
that the state's 23 county clerks failed to mail the ballots early
enough so they could be returned by primary day.
   However, there were not enough absentee ballots to affect
Vinich's 8,570-vote victory margin.
   The victory will pit a man considered by some to be one of
Wyoming's most liberal politicians against another thought to be
one of the state's most conservative. Vinich spent thousands of
dollars on commercials designed to combat his liberal image.
   Tuesday night, while savoring his victory, Vinich didn't worry
about labels.
   ``I think political labels are just smoke screens that other
candidates like to use when they have nothing else to say,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
   Wallop, 55, issued a brief statement from his campaign
headquarters.
   ``I look forward to informing the people of Wyoming about my
record and continuing the discussion of the issues that face us
today and in the future,'' he said.
   Overshadowed by the Democratic Senate race were the contests for
Wyoming's only U.S. House seat. Democrat Bryan Sharratt ran
unopposed, while five-term incumbent Dick Cheney easily earned his
sixth nomination by outdistancing Jackson's Bob Morris, 59,364 to
8,492.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
