<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-VOA 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-VOA, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0546,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voice of America Reporter Denied Accreditation in China</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, `Ruston is...' with reporter refusing comment.
pick up 4th graf, `The rejection...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has refused to accredit a reporter from the
Voice of America, the radio network supported by the U.S.
government and which China has criticized for its coverage of
student unrest.
   The Foreign Ministry gave no reason for its refusal to grant
credentials to Max Ruston, 26, saying only ``we find it difficult
to accept Mr. Ruston as a resident correspondent.''
   Ruston is the first reporter in recent years from a major
foreign news organization to be refused accreditation by China.
Ruston, reached in Hong Kong, refused comment on the decision.
   The rejection came more than two months after VOA requested
accreditation for Ruston. The VOA office in Beijing had no
immediate response to the decision.
   It was not clear whether the rejection was linked to China's
harsh criticism of VOA for its reports on pro-democracy student
demonstrations in December 1986 and January 1987.
   The radio network, which broadcasts in both Chinese and English,
was a major source of information for students trying to find out
what was happening on campuses in other parts of the country.
   The official press again lashed out at VOA in June when students
at Beijing University demonstrated and put up posters calling for
more democracy. It quoted an unidentified student as saying VOA was
interested only in bad news about China.
   Ruston, formerly accredited as a local hire for VOA, was in
Shanghai when thousands of students in China's largest city took to
the streets in December 1986. For several days, his reports were
some of the most detailed of the student unrest there.
   Ruston, who is fluent in Mandarin, worked for VOA in Beijing
until mid-1987, when he was transferred to Washington. He has been
reporting from Hong Kong while waiting for approval to take up his
position in Beijing.
   The Foreign Ministry statement made no mention of China's past
displeasure with VOA and said, ``we hope VOA will nominate someone
else.''
   China has expelled three foreign journalists since 1986 on
various charges of violating Chinese security regulations.
   Two of those reporters, an American working for the French news
agency Agence-France Presse and a correspondent for Japan's Kyodo
News Service, were expelled after last year's student
demonstrations and an ensuing conservative campaign against Western
liberal ideas.
</TEXT>
