<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Arrests     08-17 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Arrests,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Charge 52 Students With Pro-Unification Marches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today charged 52 students with
leading violent protests during marches supporting reunification
talks with North Korean students.
   Police said the students were accused of violating the National
Security Law or laws banning violent protests.
   Police said about 8,260 people, mostly students, have been taken
into custody since radical students began scattered protests Aug. 7
to press for unification talks with North Korean students.
   North and South Korean students called for the talks in the
border truce village of Panmunjom to mark the Aug. 15 anniversary
of Korea's liberation from Japan in 1945.
   But police, determined to prevent disturbances before the
upcoming Olympics in Seoul, enforced stringent security measures
and blocked all student marches and rallies advocating the border
talks.
   All but 252 detained were released after warnings, with only 200
of them still under investigations, police said.
   Police said 705 policemen and 45 protesters were injured, but
student sources claimed the number of students injured was much
higher.
   The Korean Peninsula has been divided since the end of World War
II between the communist North and the capitalist South.
</TEXT>
