<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Nelson, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0426,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baylor President Cancels Willie Nelson Concert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS one graf background on Nelson concert picketed last
month in Rhode Island.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WACO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Willie Nelson concert at Baylor University
has been canceled by the Baptist school's president, who said he
was ``concerned for the health and well-being of the American
people.''
   The Nov. 14 concert, which was to be a benefit for depositors of
a failed bank in Leroy, was scheduled to be held on campus.
   When the uninsured Leroy Bank was declared insolvent last
August, about 600 depositors, including many retirees, lost their
savings.
   ``Baylor University sympathizes greatly with those in the Leroy,
Texas, community where bank deposits have been lost, but our
concern for the health and well-being of the American people is an
overriding one,'' Baylor President Herbert Reynolds said in a
statement Tuesday.
   Reynolds also said he hopes Nelson will use his strong influence
``to strengthen the moral fiber of our nation.''
   Reynolds refused to discuss his specific concerns.
   ``I'm leaving that to the inference of the readers,'' he told
The Associated Press.
   Concert promoter Tom Gresham said he planned to meet with Nelson
today to discuss having the concert at another location on the same
date. He would not say what reason Baylor officials gave him for
the concert's cancellation.
   ``Willie is a singer and an entertainer. He is not a politician
or a preacher. No one should confuse that,'' Gresham said. ``His
offer to help the people of that community was from the heart.''
   Last month, a Nelson concert in Providence, R.I., was picketed
by more than 400 police officers and their supporters because of a
benefit concert he gave for a man convicted of killing two FBI
agents in South Dakota in 1975. Police withdrew their pickets the
next day after Nelson said he would stage a benefit concert Aug. 23
in Springfield, Mass., for both American Indian and police causes.
</TEXT>
