<DOCNO> AP880817-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0813EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mandela     08-17 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mandela,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Says He's Concerned Over Mandela's Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The minister of justice said
he is disturbed by reports that imprisoned black leader Nelson
Mandela is suffering from tuberculosis and that his condition is
deteriorating.
   The reports about Mandela's health have renewed speculation in
South African newspapers that the government might consider
releasing the 70-year-old African National Congress leader from
prison. But there was no official response to questions on the
subject.
   Mandela, who has been in prison since 1962, is serving a life
term for sabotage and conspiracy to overthrow the white-led
government.
   The office of President P.W. Botha said today the matter of
clemency is the responsibility of the Justice Department.
   Botha in 1986 suggested Mandela could be released if he
renounced violence. Mandela said he will do so only if the order
banning the ANC is lifted and apartheid _ South Africa's form of
racial separation _ is dismantled.
   Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee issued a statement late Tuesday
night saying, ``I have taken cognizance of the various reports and
medical bulletins concerning Mr. Nelson Mandela's condition and am
deeply perturbed by them. The entire issue, as well as steps to
ensure a speedy recovery, are receiving my personal attention.''
   Coetsee's office said the minister was going today to Durban,
where Botha is to give an address Thursday night to the governing
National Party's provincial congress in Natal. It didn't give the
purpose of Coetsee's trip.
   Neither the government nor doctors at Tygerberg Hospital in Cape
Town where Mandela was taken on Aug. 5 have said Mandela has
tuberculosis.
   Doctors say Mandela has an inflamed left lung and is in
satisfactory condition following removal of a drainage tube from
the lung. The medical superintendent of the hospital, Dr. J.G.L.
Strauss, said Mandela has been ``steadily improving since his
admission.''
   But Mandela's attorney, Ismail Ayob, told reporters Tuesday that
Mandela was suffering from the disease and has been bedridden for
nearly two weeks.
   ``His condition has been deteriorating for some time,'' Ayob
said. ``He was short of breath, he had a persistent cough, his
speech had been impaired and by last Friday he had lost his voice
completely.''
   News of Mandela's illness spurred renewed appeals within South
Africa for his release. Two Johannesburg newspapers urged the
government to avoid the possibility he might die in Pollsmoor
Prison.
   ``Living in jail, he is a symbol of resistance,'' said Business
Day. ``Dead in detention, no matter how natural the causes, he
would be a martyr, a flame to ignite the fires of anger,
condemnation and anti-South African action around the world.''
   The Star, the country's largest-selling daily, said Mandela's
illness offers the government ``a face-saving opportunity ... to
start the process of dealing with Mandela the man, rather than
Mandela the unknown and fearful myth.''
   In England, anti-apartheid campaigners again called for
Mandela's release. Dr. Trevor Huddleston, a former Anglican
archbishop and president of the Anti-Apartheid Movement in Britain,
appealed to Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher ``to intervene
personally'' to try to secure Mandela's freedom.
   Tuberculosis, which causes fatigue, fever, weight loss,
coughing, hoarseness and chest pain, is a contagious bacterial
infection that can be disabling or fatal. It responds to treatment
with drugs. Relapses of latent infection often occur among older
people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0086 </DOCNO>
