<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon     08-17 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Explode, Militias Fight Before Parliament Elects President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five bombs exploded in west Beirut two
days before Parliament was scheduled to elect a new national
president, and Druse and Christian militiamen battled southeast of
the capital, police said today.
   Police said one person was killed and four wounded in the
militias' overnight exchange of mortars and rockets.
   The violence began a few hours after former President Suleiman
Franjieh, a Christian leader backed by Syria, announced Tuesday he
will run for president.
   On Thursday, Parliament planned to meet in Beirut to elect a
successor to President Amin Gemayel, whose six-year term expires
Sept. 23.
   A police spokesman said the bombs exploded late Tuesday within
two hours in five residential districts of Moslem west Beirut. They
caused damage, but no casualties were reported.
   Gunmen of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist
Party and their right-wing Christian foes, the Lebanese Forces,
fought in the hills of Kfarshima southeast of Beirut for three
hours.
   They stopped after a committee grouping representatives of the
various Lebanese militias called a cease-fire at 3:15 a.m., said
the police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Franjieh, 78, is a personal friend of Syrian President Hafez
Assad. The Lebanese Forces, which opposes Syria, urged Parliament
not to elect a man ``who bears grudges and whose accession to power
would touch off the war anew.''
   It called for a ``reconciliatory president who could lead the
nation out of its current impasse and bring about national
entente.''
   The statement did not say whether the Lebanese Forces will fight
to prevent the election of Franjieh, who was president when the
civil war broke out in April 1975.
   The war, which has claimed more than 130,000 lives and shattered
the nation's economy, forced Franjieh to request Syria's military
intervention in Lebanon in 1976.
   Many Lebanese Christian leaders see Franjieh's candidacy as an
attempt by Syria to extend its control over Lebanon.
   Syria maintains about 40,000 troops in northern and eastern
Lebanon and in west and south Beirut.
   In Israel, a senior government official said Israel will
withdraw its forces from southern Lebanon if a strong, independent
president is elected.
   A Syrian-controlled president would plunge Lebanon into ``an
ongoing state of turmoil,'' said Uri Lubrani, coordinator of
government policy on Lebanon. He said Israel had ongoing private
and public contacts with various groups, not just its traditional
Christian allies.
   Israel maintains about 1,000 soldiers in a self-declared
security zone six to 10 miles deep in south Lebanon.
   Lebanon's 99-seat Parliament was elected to a four-year term in
1972. Since then, 22 deputies have died. Gemayel's seat became
vacant when he was elected president in 1982, leaving only 76
surviving parliamentarians.
   The civil war has prevented parliamentary elections, and the
legislature has been extending its mandate since 1976.
   According to an unwritten national covenant, Lebanon's president
should be a Maronite Catholic, house speaker a Shiite Moslem and
prime minister a Sunni Moslem. Gemayel is forbidden by law from
seeking a second term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
