<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--Quayle'sParents 1stLd-Writethru a0466 08-17 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Quayle's Parents, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents Had Watched Quayle `In The Hunt'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with parents' comments today. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, bgng: ``Our home ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of Sen. Dan Quayle today said
he watched his son ``in the chase, in the hunt'' for the GOP vice
presidential slot but still was surprised when George Bush selected
the Indiana senator.
   ``There's no way to prepare for something like that,'' said
James C. Quayle, whose 41-year-old son got the nod from Bush on
Tuesday as the vice president arrived at the Republican National
Convention.
   The senator's mother, Corinne, said she ``was kind of shocked,
but I'm not sure that I was real surprised.''
   Her impartial assessment: ``I thought he was a good choice.''
   The elder Quayle, interviewed with his wife on ABC-TV's ``Good
Morning America,'' said of the suspense that surrounded the
selection of their son: ``We watched him in the chase, in the hunt,
but you never know until you know.''
   In preceding days, as Dan Quayle's name had been bandied about
as a potential candidate, his father had rated his chances as
``slim to none.''
   But hours later, the senator's parents found their relaxed ranch
house just north of town besieged by reporters and ringing with
telephone calls of congratulations. Suddenly and unexpectedly, they
found themselves being asked to explain how they'd raised the first
Hoosier to wind up on a national ticket since Wendell Willkie in
1940.
   ``Our home was like a lot of homes, kind of raucous sometimes,
with four kids, but it was a very normal, at least I think normal,
home life,'' ventured Mrs. Quayle, 66.
   Jim Quayle, 67, publishes the Huntington Herald-Press, a
newspaper he bought in 1963 from his publisher father-in-law, the
late Eugene Pulliam. He describes himself as a conservative who
wasn't sure about his son's politics when Dan first went to
Washington as a member of the House.
   ``I don't think he's as conservative as I am, but I don't think
he's made a single vote in 12 years that I would challenge,'' the
senior Quayle said.
   The residents of Huntington and the rest of Dan Quayle's
original northeastern Indiana congressional district didn't
challenge his politics either, giving him solid support in each
election campaign.
   By Tuesday evening, the town offered some modest early
recognition of its favorite son's accomplishment. ``Congratulations
Dan Quayle. Huntington is proud of you,'' read the sign outside the
combination bus stop and Western Union Office. ``Congratulations
Dan Quayle'' read another sign outside an insurance office.
   Nearby, historical markers remember people and events little
noted beyond the town limits. One notes its position along the
Wabash and Erie canal, once a link between Lake Erie and the Ohio
River, but defunct before the Civil War. Another commemorates a
19th century U.S. Supreme Court decision, while a third says the
town was named for Samuel Huntington, a signer of the Declaration
of Independence.
   Dan Quayle should be cautious about trying to make his own
historical mark as the No. 2 man on the ticket, his father
cautioned.
   ``It's dangerous. He'd better not try,'' he said. ``He'd better
try to figure out which way Mr. Bush wants to go. It's his dictates
that should be followed. I hope Dan doesn't get any ideas about
going off on his own.''
   The elder Quayle said he held few illusions about the power of
the vice presidency. ``It's like Reagan said about George, I send
him to all the funerals.''
   But he has a clear idea of why Bush chose his son.
   In 1986, Dan Quayle soundly defeated Jill Long in his bid for a
second Senate term. His ability to draw votes against a woman may
have caught the eye of Bush advisers, who worry about the vice
president's weak support among women, said his father. ``The
demographics showed he pulled more women's votes than she did,'' he
said.
   Quayle's youthfulness may draw still more votes, his father
said. ``He's a baby boomer,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
