<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MurderPlotForgiveness     08-17 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Murder Plot Forgiveness,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Would-Be Victim Asks Murder Plot Charges Against Wife Be Dropped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose wife is charged with
plotting to kill him pleaded from his hospital bed to have the
charges against her dropped, saying, ``I still love her. I want her
back.''
   Jack Owens, recovering from gunshot wounds to the stomach and
leg suffered in an attack two months ago, sent his plea to Broward
Circuit Judge Thomas M. Coker Jr.
   ``We both made mistakes,'' Owens said Tuesday. ``We have to live
with that ... I think the two of us can be happy, if they'll let
us.''
   The judge denied Owens' request.
   Owens, 40, was shot in his sleep on June 14 in the couple's
apartment. Less than 24 hours later, police arrested his wife of 2{
years, Vicky Owens, and another woman in connection with the
shooting.
   Owens said he was disappointed in the judge's decision.
   ``It doesn't seem right,'' Owens said. ``There's a whole lot of
stuff people don't realize. You have to be married to someone for a
while to understand.''
   Mrs. Owens, 32, and her friend, Elizabeth Perron, 21, face
charges of attempted first-degree murder, criminal conspiracy and
criminal attempt.
   Owens said he would like to see Ms. Perron, who is still in
custody, prosecuted. But he said his wife, who is out on bond, has
suffered enough by spending time in jail.
   ``I do love her,'' Owens said. ``I don't want to lose her.''
   Mrs. Owens told police someone had broken into their apartment
and that she was awakened by the sound of a gun firing. She said
she only recalled seeing a shadowy figure leaving the bedroom,
investigators said.
   But a friend of Ms. Perron's told police the shooting had been
planned, and when police confronted Ms. Perron, she confessed,
police said.
   Ms. Perron also handed over maps of the Owens' apartment, a
letter outlining the plan, and keys to the Owens' apartment. Owens
later identified the handwriting on the letter and maps as his
wife's script, police said.
   ``Vicky kept telling her she was unhappy in her marriage and
they began to conspire,'' said Linda Furnell, a police investigator.
</TEXT>
