<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Ford, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0474,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Says Democrats Want to Raise Taxes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Ford comments today. Picks up 3rd graf
pvs, bgng: ``For 45 ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Gerald R. Ford today said
his speech before the Republican National Convention was designed
to meet head-on the ``snide'' barbs lobbed by some Democrats at
their parley last month.
   Ford, who came to Bush's defense in an address to the convention
Tuesday night, said he was angered by the Democrats' personal
attacks on the vice president.
   ``Some of the peripheral speakers got a little snide,'' he said
in an interview on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' show. ``I
thought that was unfair and unfortunate, I had to meet it head-on.''
   Ford expressed hope that the fall campaign won't turn nasty,
saying: ``There are some legitimate substantive differences of
opinion. The question of competence, the question of change. You
don't have to get into personalities to make your point.''
   In his address to the convention, Ford rebutted the chants of
``Where Was George?'' from the Democratic convention in Atlanta.
   ``For 45 years, George Bush has been at the center of the action
in the service of this great republic,'' Ford said.
   ``I'll be damned if I will stand by and let anyone with a smirk
and a sneer discredit the honor, service, accountability and
competence of George Bush.''
   ``If the ... Democratic standard-bearers in this campaign think
it is about competence, let any one of them ... top the
demonstrated competence of George Bush,'' Ford said.
   In an echo of themes from his losing campaign against Jimmy
Carter in 1976, Ford asked his audience: ``Do we really want to go
back to the days of spend and spend and tax and tax _ of a
government in Washington with its head in the clouds and its hand
in your pocket.
   ``I can put it no plainer than this: This year's Democratic
ticket is a tax increase on its way to happen.''
   In a backhanded slap at Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis, Ford said that Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, the Democratic
vice presidential candidate, is ``pretty solid on defense matters.''
   ``But his partners can't seem to get their act together,'' he
said.
   Rhetorically addressing Bentsen, Ford said: ``Gov. Dukakis says
you'll be the kind of vice president who will march into the Oval
Office and tell him: `Mr. President, that is a perfectly ridiculous
policy.'''
   Ford added: ``Lloyd, with all the differences between the
Democratic leaders, why wait? Speak up now.''
</TEXT>
