<HEAD>Soviet Passenger Train Derails, Catches Fire, 95 Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 760 people on train, 95
hospitalized, other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train derailed and caught fire, killing an
undetermined number of people and injuring 95, Tass and a Soviet
official reported today.
   The official news agency said the Aurora passenger train was
traveling from Leningrad to Moscow when it left the tracks between
the Berezaika and Poplavenets stations north of Moscow at 6:34 p.m.
on Tuesday.
   Anatoly N. Sobin, director of the Leningrad railway station in
Moscow, told The Associated Press the train was carrying 760
passengers when it crashed about 220 miles north of the capital.
   Sobin said in a telephone interview that 95 passengers were
hospitalized in two nearby towns. He said he did not know the
number killed.
   First Deputy Railroad Minister Vladimir Ginko told Tass an exact
count of the victims had not been made. The fire started in the
dining car and spread rapidly, engulfing nearly the entire train,
Tass said.
   Because of difficult road conditions, fire engines could not
reach the burning train and a firefighting train at the scene ran
out of water and had to be refilled before the fire was
extinguished, the agency said.
   Normal railway traffic was restored this morning, and an
investigation team was named, headed by a deputy chairman of the
Council of Ministers, Vladimir Gusev, Tass said.
</TEXT>
