<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     08-17 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Free American; Talks On U.S. Bases Recessed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American and his Filipino wife
flew to Manila today aboard a U.S. military plane after Moslem
kidnappers freed them from more than two weeks of captivity on the
southern island of Mindanao.
   Also today, U.S. and Filipino negotiators recessed talks on
American military bases. A joint statement said the talks would
resume next month.
   An American diplomat fetched David Blair Stiffler, 42, a New
York City construction worker, and his wife Elpidia from the
Mindanao city of Iligan, where they spent the night after the
kidnappers released them Tuesday near Lanao Lake in Lanao del Sur
province, 520 miles southeast of Manila.
   The Stifflers went into seclusion in Manila, saying they wanted
to ``rest and get their wits together,'' U.S. Embassy spokesman
Jerry Huchel said.
   The kidnappers, described as renegades of the Moslem separatist
Moro Islamic Liberation Front, had demanded a $7,000 ransom, which
they later lowered to $1,000. Military officials insisted no ransom
was paid.
   Col. Eduardo Resos, army commander in the area, said in a
telephone interview that the armed kidnappers robbed the Stifflers
of about $3,000 worth of cash and valuables after their abduction
July 30.
   Resos said the kidnappers agreed to release the captives after
military threats of reprisal against area villages.
   The Moro Front is one of three Moslem groups fighting for Moslem
rule in Mindanao and other southern islands since 1972.
   In Manila, U.S. and Philippine officials gave no date in
September when the U.S. bases talks will resume.
   The two sides are negotiating terms for the remaining two years
of a 1947 agreement under which the United States maintains Clark
Air Base, Subic Bay naval base and four smaller installations.
   The agreement expires in 1991, and there is growing opposition
in the Philippines to extending the lease.
   Also today, Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos told reporters the
military is ``closely monitoring'' rightist renegades to prevent a
new coup attempt following calls by the vice president for
President Corazon Aquino to resign.
   On Tuesday, Vice President Salvador Laurel said he would give
Mrs. Aquino one week to respond to his proposal that they both
resign and call new presidential elections. Laurel accused her of
incompetence.
   Mrs. Aquino was swept to power in a February 1986
civilian-military coup that deposed President Ferdinand Marcos.
Marcos lives in exile in Hawaii.
</TEXT>
