<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FreewayChase     08-17 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Freeway Chase,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arrested After Hand Grenade Thrown At Police Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who allegedly threw a hand
grenade at a policeman was arrested after a 15-mile freeway chase
that ended when helicopter-borne police fired at the fleeing car
and a police car rammed it.
   No one was injured in the incident.
   Robert D. Bodily, 33, was held today without bail at the San
Bernardino County Jail for investigation of attempted murder of
police Sgt. Ron Schwenka, said police Sgt. Dan Hernandez.
   Bodily threw a hand grenade at Schwenka on Tuesday night while
the officer was investigating reports of a man firing at a dwelling
and brandishing a shotgun, Hernandez said.
   Bodily also was arrested for investigation of violating a parole
warrant, shooting at an inhabited dwelling, brandishing a firearm,
being an ex-felon in possession of a firearm, possessing
explosives, detonating explosives, transporting explosives without
a permit and detonating explosives with intent to commit injury,
Hernandez said.
   The incident began Tuesday when police received a call reporting
shots had been fired at a retirement complex. A second call, about
45 minutes later, reported the same person brandished a sawed-off
shotgun at another address.
   An hour later, Hernandez said, Schwenka pulled over a car
similar to that involved in the incidents. The suspect held a hand
grenade out the window and pulled the pin, he said. Schwenka tried
to fire at the suspect, but his gun failed, Hernandez said, and the
suspect hurled the grenade as he drove by the officer. However, no
one was hurt by the blast.
   Bodily then drove onto Interstate 215, where deputies in a
sheriff's helicopter fired several shots at his car, hitting the
engine compartment area. Fifteen minutes later, a police car halted
the pursuit by ramming Bodily's car.
</TEXT>
