<2ND_LINE>PM-Armored Car Death,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wells Fargo Guard Crushed To Death By Money When Truck Overturns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARCHDALE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armored truck ran off a highway and
overturned, killing a Wells Fargo guard who was crushed by money
bags and spilling more than $1 million into a ditch, authorities
said.
   The driver apparently fell asleep Tuesday afternoon while
traveling 55 mph on Interstate 85 about two miles south of Archdale
in Randolph County, state trooper Ricky Doss said.
   The truck was carrying money from Greensboro to a bank in
Charlotte when it ran off the highway, crashed into a guard rail,
rolled down an embankment and overturned in a ditch.
   The driver and another guard in the front seat were thrown from
the truck, and more than $1 million in coins and paper currency
spilled out the back door, officials said.
   Firefighters spent two hours bringing large money bags up from
the embankment with a pulley, said Lt. Keith Eddins of the
Guil-Rand Fire Department.
   ``There is no telling how many millions were pulled up,'' Eddins
said. ``They already took one truckful of money away.''
   Officers guarded the money overnight.
   Scott Burger, 22, of Charlotte, was pronounced dead at the
scene, Doss said.
   Driver Donald Carol Greenway, 42, of Charlotte, was in stable
condition today at High Point Regional Hospital. Front seat
passenger Scott Pittsenbarger, 29, of Charlotte was in critical
condition today at North Carolina Memorial Hospital in Chapel Hell.
</TEXT>
