<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HeatBan     08-17 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heat Ban,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Council Bans 90-degree Temperatures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poughkeepsie Town Council members
found one sure way to beat the heat this summer. They outlawed it.
   The council Monday night unanimously passed a resolution making
it illegal to report a temperature over 90 degrees within city
limits.
   Town Alderman Pasqual Letteri, who sponsored the resolution,
declared at the council meeting, ``Whereas the residents of the
city of Poughkeepsie deserve better weather than constant 90-degree
heat, it is hearby outlawed for anyone to report a temperature over
89.5 degrees Fahrenheit.''
   So far, the extreme measure seems to be working. Poughkeepsie
has yet to see the temperature rise above the 90-degree mark since
the adoption of the new resolution.
   And a good thing too. The resolution mandates that anyone caught
violating the law will be banished to the top of the local civic
center's marquee where they will be sentenced to make ice
sculptures until they no longer melt.
</TEXT>
