<HEAD>Medillin Cartel Threatens DEA New York Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed guards were hired to patrol the Drug
Enforcement Administration's Manhattan offices after Colombia's
most powerful cocaine cartel threatened the life of the DEA's New
York chief, a spokesman said.
   Police officers also were assigned to patrol outside the
agency's headquarters, New York Newsday reported today.
   The threat against Robert Stutman, special agent in charge of
the New York DEA office, came last week and was linked to the
Medellin group, headed by cocaine billionaire Gonzalo Rodriguez
Gacha.
   ``Our intelligence indicates that in fact the Medellin cartel is
responsible for the threats,'' said DEA spokesman Robert Strang.
   The threat apparently was prompted by the recent seizure of
7,300 pounds of cocaine and the arrest of three Medellin cartel
members, agents said.

