<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MspiLegislature     08-17 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mspi Legislature,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House And Senate Compromise On Anti-Corruption Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation approved by Mississippi
lawmakers restructuring the state's century-old system of county
government is historic, Gov. Ray Mabus said.
   ``For the first time, the government of the state of Mississippi
is on record for honest and efficient government,'' Mabus said
after the bill passed 111-7 in the House and 50-0 in the Senate.
   A compromise version of the legislation won overwhelming
approval Tuesday, the seventh day of a special session called by
Mabus to deal with county government reform.
   Mabus, as state auditor for the four years preceding his
election as governor last November, assisted the FBI in an
investigation that resulted in federal graft charges against 56
supervisors from 25 counties.
   House and Senate negotiators reached a compromise Monday
afternoon; both chambers approved the bill Tuesday without debate
after lengthy explanations.
   Negotiators refused to compromise on a similar bill which died
during the regular session earlier this year.
   Lawmakers also sent to Mabus a bill raising supervisors'
salaries by 20 percent across-the-board. Mabus vetoed a similar
bill in the regular session, saying no raises would be given until
county reform legislation was passed.
   A spokesman in Mabus' office said the governor on Tuesday signed
the county unit bill, the pay-raise bill and others passed during
the special session.
   The county unit legislation requires counties to implement by
Jan. 2, 1989 central purchasing, receiving and inventory control
systems with separate clerks for each.
   Voters would decide on Nov. 8 whether their counties would
construct and maintain roads on a countywide or district basis
after Oct. 1, 1989.
   Those counties opting for central road administration would be
required to hire county administrators and road managers. Under the
bill, the chancery clerk could serve either as county administrator
or in one of the clerical positions. Supervisors could not hold any
of those positions.
   Sen. Ollie Mohamed, chairman of the Senate County Affairs
Committee, said the bill had flaws, but they could be fixed in the
regular session in January.
   ``We've been placed under the gun,'' he said. ``Everybody wants
to go home and everybody wants some form of county government
reorganization.''
   Mississippi Association of Supervisors Executive Director Eddie
Washington said he was ``extremely pleased'' with the compromise.
   Already, 22 of Mississippi's 82 counties have in place some form
of the so-called county unit system, under which supervisors set
policy and hire an administrator to handle day-to-day business. In
the remainder, supervisors oversee both policy and daily operations
in their individual districts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
