<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1012EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sudan-Floods     08-17 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Floods,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rains Fall On Flood-Stricken Capital As Nile Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain poured down on the capital today and
the Nile rose higher as the city tried to cope with the worst
flooding in its history.
   News reports today said an additional 21 people died in
accidents caused by the floods, bringing the total known death toll
to more than 90.
   Torrential rains Aug. 4-5 left 1.5 million to 2 million people
homeless as thousands of mud huts melted in the refugee camps that
ring this desert city.
   In Khartoum alone, 70 people died, 213 were injured and nearly
115,000 houses were destroyed by the flooding, Egypt's state-owned
Middle East News Agency quoted Amin Abdel-Latif, Sudan's ambassador
to Cairo, as saying Tuesday.
   The agency said today that 18 Sudanese drowned when their ferry
overturned in fast currents on the Rahad River. The river is a
tributary of the Blue Nile, which joins the White Nile at Khartoum
to form the Nile River.
   In Omdurman, across the Nile from Khartoum, the agency said
three children were killed and dozens injured when a house
collapsed because of the flood.
   In northern Sudan, 99 islands were submerged and their 60,000
inhabitants moved to safe locations, and 21 villages were washed
away and the 12,000 families who lived there were left homeless,
Abdel-Latif said.
   He said there were no figures on total casualties and damages
because the floods isolated so many places.
   Sudanese Finance Minister Omar Nour Dayem earlier estimated
damages were around $200 million and that up to 2 million people
were homeless.
   The crisis could worsen with the beginning of the Nile's annual
flooding. Heavy rains in Ethiopia, source of the Blue Nile, have
produced a plentiful flood after eight years of drought.
   Officials don't know whether the Nile will flood the city, parts
of which are already isolated by vast pools of stagnant water and
roads that have become impassable tracks of mud.
   The Nile waters have already started seeping into houses along
its banks in the capital, and many residents have evacuated their
homes for higher ground.
   The Egyptian agency quoted Sudanese Irrigation Minister Mahmoud
Beshir Gamma as saying several areas in the north were threatened
with river flooding. He said they included the large towns of
Atbara, Damer, Berber and Dongola.
   Gamma also said floods caused by heavy rains in the western
province of Kordofan washed away many houses and left 15,000
families homeless.
   The Middle East News Agency said the large crop-rich island of
Tuti, in the Nile between Khartoum and its twin city Om Durman, was
almost submerged.
   The agency quoted travelers coming from central Sudan and the
Gezira region as saying the annual flood submerged large areas of
land and left 55,000 people destitute.
   Gezira contains the country's richest agricultural lands, which
are mostly planted with cotton, one of the Sudan's most important
exports. Losing the cotton crop would add to the country's economic
woes.
   The World Health Organization in Khartoum has warned of
water-borne epidemics that could kill thousands of peasants, mostly
children, who are cut off from supplies of clean water.
   About 90 planes have brought food, medicine, tents and other
supplies into Khartoum from all over the world, but Sudanese
authorities have had difficulty distributing the aid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
