<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CampaignAbroad     08-17 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Abroad,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campaign Abroad: Comment on the Republican Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is some of what newspapers abroad had to say this week
about the Republican convention in New Orleans:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEST GERMANY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Die Welt of Bonn (conservative): ``The last big appearance (of
President Reagan) _ A star leaves the stage.''
   ``It was the best and most effective speech that has been heard
so far in this election campaign.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Sueddeutsche Zeitung of Munich (left-leaning): ``They didn't
want him to give his speech because they simply don't want him to
go. When convention participants were asked why Reagan is so
beloved and irreplaceable, the answer was unanimous: because he
doesn't seem like a politician.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Neue Presse of Frankfurt (conservative): ``We are going to miss
him. In American opinion, only one other president in this century
has filled the stage like Ronald Reagan: Franklin D. Roosevelt.
   ``The attempts by his critics to degrade him to a comic figure
have not worked. His possible successor, (Vice President George)
Bush, may be better informed on many issues but next to Reagan,
Bush is pale and without identity.
   ``When Reagan leaves offices, politics will lose one of its most
distinctive and entertaining representatives.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NORWAY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Verdens Gangof of Oslo (independent): ``The appointment of Dan
Quayle as running mate is described here as a smart move by George
Bush. Quayle has good education, talks family policy and has a view
on defense and security policy which fully satisfies the
conservatives. His choice guarantees that the Reagan succession is
carried on if the Republicans win the presidential election in
November.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Dagbladet of Oslo (independent): ``Quayle, an educated lawyer
not even a delegate to the convention, is seen as an average
conservative politician and a new and fresh name within the
Republican Party camp.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
