<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugSeizure     08-17 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Seizure,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Find $26.4 Million In Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators following an anonymous tip
found $26.4 million worth of cocaine at a suspected suburban
``stash'' house where they also arrested four suspects, authorities
said.
   Sheriff's deputies found 194 pounds of cocaine in a station
wagon in the garage during the raid Monday night at a home in
Northridge, 25 miles north of downtown, sheriff's Lt. Bill
Christiansen said. An Uzi semiautomatic machine gun and $3,000 in
cash also were found, he said.
   ``It is a significant seizure,'' Christiansen said. ``They
normally come after longer investigations and certainly more
information.''
   Officials said the four occupants of the house were arrested for
investigation of conspiring to distribute cocaine and held in the
county jail in lieu of $1 million bail each.
   The Sheriff's Department began its investigation Monday morning
when the department's narcotics unit received an anonymous call
saying a large amount of cocaine was to be moved from the home that
day, Christiansen said.
   The deputies, armed with a search warrant, raided the house
after they saw a man moving packages they believed contained
cocaine into the station wagon, he said.
   Authorities believe the home was being used as a storage point
for drugs planned for distribution in the Los Angeles area. Police
said they did not know whether any of the suspects actually lived
at the house.
   Deputies said they didn't know where the cocaine came from or
where it was to be delivered. They also said they had no clues to
the identity or motives of the anonymous tipster.
</TEXT>
