<HEAD>Mother to Fight Judge's Glass Partition Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother is appealing a federal judge's order
that a 6-year-old AIDS victim stay inside a glass booth if she
attends a school for handicapped children.
   Steve Hanlon, attorney for Rosa Martinez, said he filed notice
of appeal Tuesday, taking the case to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in Atlanta. He said he doubts the matter could be
resolved before school starts Aug. 29.
   ``We were hopeful the judge's solution might work,'' Hanlon
said. ``But after talking with pediatric and psychological experts
_ people whose judgments we respect a great deal _ we are convinced
it would be very harmful, even to the extent of affecting her
immune system.''
   Mrs. Martinez filed suit last year, saying she wanted her
adopted daughter Eliana to be in a classroom setting.
   Last week, U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Kovachevich ruled that
the Hillsborough County School Board must admit the mentally
handicapped child to Manhattan Exceptional Center.
   The child was to remain inside a plexiglass enclosure until she
became toilet-trained and learned to stop sucking her thumb and
forefingers, according to the order.
   School officials had wanted to have the girl instructed at home.
   Doctors believe Eliana contracted from multiple blood
transfusions following her premature birth in Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
