<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Hess     08-17 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Hess,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police in Hess Burial Town Arrest 15 Italian Demonstrators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WUNSIEDEL, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today arrested 15
right-wing Italians carrying banners with swastikas in the town
where former Nazi leader Rudolf Hess is buried.
   Demonstrations are banned in Wunsiedel on the first anniversary
of Hess' death. The former deputy fuhrer hanged himself at the age
of 93 in Berlin's Spandau Prison on Aug. 17.
   Also today, the former Nazi official's son, Wolf-Ruediger Hess,
visited the grave along with his wife, Andrea.
   Wunsiedel police spokesman Roland Weber did not say whether the
Italian demonstrators were able to get close to the cemetery.
   ``There were 15 Italians in all, carrying two banners with
swastika-like emblems,'' Weber told The Associated Press. ``They
are considered to be right-wing extremists.''
   Demonstrators had given notice of their plans, said Christoph
Schiller, district government chairman in Wunsiedel in far
northeastern Bavaria 11 miles from the Czechoslovakian border.
Schiller said protests are banned from midnight Tuesday until
midnight Sunday.
   ``We'd been told to expect between 500 to 1,000 right-wing
extremists,'' Schiller said Tuesday.
   Within days of Hess' death last year, police in Wunsiedel
arrested more than 100 right-wing extremists and neo-Nazis who
converged on the town. Many were wearing neo-Nazi emblems and
shouting neo-Nazi slogans.
   Hess, who was deputy to Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler, was the sole
prisoner in Spandau, which was administered by France, Britain, the
United States and the Soviet Union, the Allies of World War II.
</TEXT>
