<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0603 08-17 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0603,0827</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>105 Beaten In Gaza; Prisoners Stage Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with deportations, INSERT graf after 2nd, `The
army...' and three grafs after 13th, `The Palestine...' Pick up
14th pvs, `Tensions were...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 Palestinians were treated for
beating injuries today in the Gaza Strip, hospital officials said,
during a Palestinian general strike to protest Israeli rule of the
occupied lands.
   The army said it could not immediately confirm any injury
reports.
   Israel deported four Palestinians from the occupied Gaza Strip
to Lebanon today, said police in Rachaiya, Lebanon. The move
brought to 33 the number of deportees since an Arab uprising
against Israeli rule began eight months ago.
   Also today, the army opened an inquiry into the causes of
Tuesday's prison riot in which two Arabs were killed. A letter by
inmates at the tent prison of Kedziot said they were on a hunger
strike to press for the prison's closing.
   Soldiers sealed off Gaza for a third straight day today,
confining 650,000 Palestinians to their homes and barring reporters
from the occupied territory.
   Officials at Shifa Hospital in Gaza said 105 Palestinians were
treated today for beating injuries. ``Most of the injuries were
bruises and contusions,'' Dr. Ahmed Yazeji, chief surgeon at Shifa,
said in an interview.
   Yazeji said the bruises appeared to be caused by beatings with
``clubs and rifle butts and kicking with heavy military boots.''
   He said 90 percent of the victims said they were beaten in their
homes by troops looking for suspected stone-throwers after a surge
of violence in Gaza.
   Troops shot and wounded two Palestinians in Gaza today, and they
were treated at the nearby Ahli Arab Hospital, officials at the
hospital said.
   In refugee Camp No. 1 near the occupied West Bank city of
Nablus, soldiers opened fire on Arab stone-throwers today, wounding
a 17-year-old in the right thigh, said officials at Al Ittihad
Hospital.
   Under the general strike call, many of the 110,000 Palestinians
who work in Israel boycotted their jobs. Arab-owned shops and
businesses were closed in at least a dozen towns and cities in the
occupied lands.
   The strike came in response to a leaflet issued by underground
leaders of the uprising. It said the strike was ``in honor of
Jerusalem, the capital of our Palestinian state and to protest
oppressive measures and arrests.''
   Israel says about 5,000 Palestinians have been jailed since the
revolt began, about half without trial.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization says it plans to declare a
Palestinian state or set up a government-in-exile for the occupied
lands in response to Jordan's decision to sever administrative ties
with the territories. Israel opposes a Palestinian state.
   Police in Rachaiya, Lebanon, said Mohammed Gharableh, Ahmed abu
Muailek, Yusri Darwish al Hums and Fathi Ibrihim Shakaki, all from
the Gaza Strip, were deported today. All four dropped their appeals
with the Israeli Supreme Court this month.
   Police said the four were flown to Israel's self-declared
security zone in south Lebanon. Informed sources said they were
given $50 each.
   The United States has protested Israel's policy of deportations
but Israel defends the measure as the most effective means of
deterring violence.
   Tensions were high after the Tuesday riot in Ketziot, 20 miles
south of the Gaza Strip, by hundreds of Palestinian prisoners. The
army said two Palestinians were shot to death in the riot and a
third was wounded, but it refused to elaborate, saying the riot was
under investigation.
   Inmates in the 2,500-prisoner camp have complained about poor
conditions, including overcrowding, substandard food and
insufficient water for bathing.
   The AP obtained a copy of a letter smuggled out of the prison
and written by inmates which called for closing Ketziot. The letter
said the inmates were staging a hunger strike to press their
demands.
   ``Yes to the pangs of hunger, no to surrender,'' the letter said.
   The deaths brought to 247 the number of Palestinians killed
since the uprising began Dec. 8. Four Israelis have died.
   Arab news reports said the victims were Assad Jabra el Shawwa,
25 of Gaza City and Bassam Ibrahim al Samoudi, 27, of Yamoun
village in the West Bank. Both were serving six-month terms without
trial under administrative detention.
   The Yediot Ahronot daily said the riot began during a visit by
representatives of the International Red Cross. The organization
could not immediately be reached for comment.
   Other reports said it began after news of violence and of the
curfew in Gaza, where many inmates live.
   About 1,000 prisoners in one section of the prison shouted
Palestinian nationalist slogans, cursed and hurled rocks at
soldiers and tried to scale a barbed-wire fence, the Haaretz
newspaper said.
   Soldiers reportedly responded by firing tear gas, rubber bullets
and then live ammunition at the rioters.
</TEXT>
