<DOCNO> AP880817-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   08-17 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0956</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   Aug. 16
   The Flint (Mich.) Journal on honorariums for members of Congress:
   Too many of our representatives in Washington have been
accepting honorariums from special interests. Taxpayers can only
hope they've done nothing to deserve the gifts they accept.
   Let us assume this congressional tradition is as innocent as
congressional honorarium-takers claim.
   There is still an appearance of influence-peddling. There is an
impression Congress, or at least some of its members, can be
bought. ...
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, whose ethics have been
scrutinized recently because he accepted a highly questionable fee
from a book publisher, has joined (Rep. Dan) Rostenkowski in
proposing an outright prohibition on honorariums. ...
   Congress has seen fit to prohibit members of the executive
branch from accepting speaking fees and other honorariums. It
should set the same high standard for itself.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 15
   The Olympian, Olympia, Wash., on the Iran-Iraq cease-fire:
   On Aug. 20, a cease-fire monitored by U.N. observers is to take
effect in the Persian Gulf, ending one of the most brutal wars of
modern times.
   Both Iran and Iraq claim victory, but both are losers. ...
   The bloody war was fought largely without any foreign observers,
but it is believed 1 million soldiers were killed and perhaps twice
that number wounded. Rocket attacks on cities claimed thousands of
civilian lives. ...
   The cost in dollars is nearly as staggering _ at least $200
billion in economic loss.
   All for what purpose? None that we know of.
   The leaders of Iran and Iraq are guilty of attempted genocide
that took terrible tolls, but they never will be brought to trial.
   Since Iran and Iraq continue to proclaim victory in ignorance,
the world can only hope that others will learn from this horrible
example of the futility of war.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 14
   Sunday Sun-Journal, Lewiston, Maine, on the presidential race:
   From the time it became clear that George Bush and Michael
Dukakis would be the 1988 presidential contenders, nobody expected
high drama, inspired philosophizing or passionate rhetoric on the
campaign trail. After all, neither man is exactly overloaded with
charisma.
   But what the American public has had to endure so far is enough
to make voters devoutly wish that someone will mount a credible
nationwide write-in campaign for president.
   Both candidates are preoccupied with trading barbs; neither
seems able to dispense with sniping and deal with substantive
issues.
   If last week's exchanges were any indication of the way the rest
of the campaign will be conducted, November can't come too soon.
The voters' patience will be totally exhausted by Election Day.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 16
   The News and Courier, Charleston, (S.C., on job satisfaction:
   This will come as a surprise for Yuppies, whose mating ritual
revolves around the term, ``What do you do?'', but most Americans
don't care much for their jobs.
   Matter of fact, compared to Europeans and Japanese, they care
very little.
   A poll conducted by International Research Associates and the
Roper Organization disclosed that Americans ranked their job eighth
in importance on a list of 10 significant aspects of their lives.
   Europeans put jobs fourth and Japanese listed them second.
Americans and Europeans ranked their children's educations first;
Japanese gave top billing to health. ...
   On that same list, Americans ranked their family lives as most
satisfying; ditto the Japanese and Europeans.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 11
   The Advocate, Stamford, Conn., on polluting our planet:
   We in our own generation are becoming afraid of the sun and air.
These givers of life that sustain and nourish us have been turned
by years of humanity's greed, ignorance and indifference into alien
elements.
   Suddenly, we are more aware than ever of living in a damaged
cocoon. ...
   Daily reports on the greenhouse effect and the ozone drive us
from our natural environment in search of artificial shelter.
   The daily weather report jars us as we check the air quality and
pollution standard index. We read and find what new horror from
drought and heat awaits this delicate sphere and its inhabitants.
...
   Pollutants from rivers, cleaners and pesticides are taking a
destructive toll on the fragile body of water that hugs our shores.
The fish don't have oxygen. Careless dumping is poisoning the
waterfront.
   We are killing the water, the very place where life on the
planet began. ...
   Time is running out. We must arise, awaken and save our Earth
and ourselves.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 10
   North Jersey Herald and News, Passaic, N.J., on ``The Last
Temptation of Christ'':
   ``The Last Temptation (Of Christ)'' ... questions the divine
nature of Christ ... to portray what its creators say is the human
Christ: a man prone to self-doubt, sexual urges, temptation and
even error.
   Religious groups denounce ``The Last Temptation'' as
``blasphemous'' and ``repugnant,'' and call upon the faithful to
help keep this film far from neighborhood theaters.
   The opposition's outcry only hands Universal Pictures a golden
platter full of publicity.
   Equally troubling, the calls for boycott and bans before the
film's release touch the raw nerve of censorship.
   Prior censorship violates the First Amendment-protected right of
free speech, an amendment all churches have an abiding interest in
upholding. The First Amendment also provides for religious freedom.
   The faithful would do well to remember: Hollywood is no
theological seminary. Don't give the film credit, where credit
isn't due.
</TEXT>
