<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0826</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: isn't due.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 12
   The Brainerd (Minn.) Daily Dispatch on ``The Last Temptation of
Christ'':
   Seldom has a movie received harsher criticism prior to its
release than ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' directed by Martin
Scorsese.
   The film has been labeled blasphemous by a number of religious
groups, most conspicuously fundamentalists, for its portrayal of
Jesus.
   In the most controversial scene, Jesus, suffering agony on the
cross, imagines what life would have been like had he lived as a
normal man. In this delirium, he is shown engaging in sex.
   No doubt, behind the public breast-beating of most religious
critics lies sincere moral outrage.
   These people's opinions should be acknowledged and respected.
However, they must be reminded that the same Constitution that
guarantees them freedom of religion also provides freedom of
expression. ...
   Those who wish to experience the picture's message should be
allowed to do so in peace. Those who don't should stay home and
read the Bible, which is how Christ's message was meant to be
conveyed in the first place.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 16
   The Wichita (Kan.) Eagle-Beacon on education:
   Education of America's youngsters has become a favorite topic of
conversation for many of America's business people.
   This talk is becoming more than words as businesses are taking
an active role in the education of America's schoolchildren.
   The number of school volunteers is growing in the United States
and many of these volunteers are coming from the field of business.
They are giving their financial support as well as sharing some
innovative ideas.
   An educational booklet will be published this fall discussing
what businesses can do to help in the field of education, says
Marlene Beck from the U.S. Department of Education.
   The success of these programs will be seen not only in the
future lives of American young people, but in the future of America.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 16
   The Arizona Daily Star, Tucson, Ariz., on Edwin Meese:
   The new U.S. attorney general is less than enthusiastic about
his predecessor's dramatic parting shot, and with good reason.
   There was no need for Edwin Meese's final act in office, an
order requiring that independent prosecutors be appointed to
investigate criminal allegations against members of Congress.
   Attorney General Richard Thornburgh is the man who, during the
Ford administration, headed the criminal division of the Justice
Department. ...
   Independent prosecutors are meant to step in when a conflict of
interest might otherwise result in the course of an investigation.
   But Edwin Meese, himself dogged by two independent prosecutors,
ordered a broader use.
   On ... his last day in office, he signed an order requiring the
appointment of a special prosecutor whenever serious allegations of
wrongdoing are made against members of Congress.
   Given no need for such a change, it appears that congressional
skeptics are right in suspecting vindictiveness.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 11
   The Journal-Bulletin, Providence, R.I., on the cost of U.N.
peacekeeping:
   Peace does not come cheaply.
   The cost of arranging the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan and
the cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war will leave the United Nations
financially strapped.
   The tab for peacekeeping missions will increase from roughly 25
percent of the U.N. budget to more than twice the entire budget. In
fact, the U.N. could run out of funds by November.
   Peace may be breaking out all over, but no one is breaking out
his wallet.
   One particularly important holdout is the United States, which
has been withholding its dues since 1985, charging that the
organization was anti-American.
   Now the United States is $467 million in arrears, including this
year's assessment of $44 million.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 14
   The Miami Herald on Oscar Arias and peace in Central America:
   (Costa Rican President) Oscar Arias continues to try to earn his
1987 Nobel Peace Prize, but he gets precious little help from
either side of the ideological wars of Central America.
   His latest contribution is an open acknowledgement that Cuba's
role in the peace process must be commensurate with its role in the
war.
   President Arias has used the occasion of Ecuador's presidential
inauguration to discuss the subject with Fidel Castro. He reports
that the Cuban leader's response was moderate and constructive.
   That's important, because the Costa Rican president holds Cuba's
client, the Nicaraguan government, responsible for the breakdown of
peace negotiations this summer. ...
   For now, Oscar Arias is the only major player who focuses on the
fact that young boys are dying on both sides of Nicaragua's
fratricidal war and El Salvador's as well.
   He hopes to stop the killing, and he is willing to talk with
anyone from Ronald Reagan to Fidel Castro in pursuit of a peace
that freedom-loving Central Americans can accept.
</TEXT>
