<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionProtests     08-17 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Protests,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>78 More Arrests Today</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 78 anti-abortion protesters at
two clinics today as activists continued a four-week-old series of
demonstrations.
   Police spokesman Cal Jackson said 32 protesters were arrested at
Midtown Hospital and 46 were arrested at the Feminist Women's
Health Center, both scenes of earlier demonstrations.
   On Tuesday, protesters briefly breached police lines near an
abortion clinic before 157 demonstrators were sent to jail in the
largest mass arrest since the protests began.
   There was some shoving Tuesday between protesters and police as
the officers realigned themselves between the clinic and protesters
who had gotten through their lines.
   Officials on each side accused the other of escalating the
confrontation.
   ``They are being jerks. The police are trying to make the
situation more tense than it needs to be,'' said Michael McMonagle,
deputy director of Operation Rescue, the New York-based
organization coordinating the protests.
   Atlanta police Sgt. Melvin Denson said he heard some protest
leaders ``telling their people to head straight for my men.''
   Today's arrests raised to 671 the total arrested in the
protests, which began during the Democratic National Convention
last month. Officials said 244 of the protesters remained in the
Atlanta and Fulton County jails Tuesday night.
</TEXT>
