<DOCNO> AP880817-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Libraries 2ndLd-Writethru   08-17 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Libraries, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0538,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Recommend That Village Libraries Remove Pre-Gorbachev
Books</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with official saying act was
recommendation sted order, saying woman doesn't work for Crimean
library, details. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have recommended that village public
libraries remove from their shelves political and economic
literature published before Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev took
power, an official said today.
   The government newspaper Izvestia, in a letter attributed to a
librarian, referred to the move as an order.
   But Leonid Bely, director of the state culture agency in the
Crimea, said today that the directive from the central Ministry of
Culture in Moscow was only a recommendation and was not politically
motivated.
   ``It's for the cleaning out of the book fund,'' Bely said in a
telephone interview from Simferopol, the Crimean administrative
center.
   Izvestia published the letter Tuesday attributed to a librarian
in the Crimea, a region of the Ukraine, saying libraries were
ordered to remove works by former Soviet leader Leonid I. Brezhnev
and other top officials now in disgrace.
   The author complained that the order would create new ``blank
spots,'' or gaps, in the Soviet historical record.
   But Bely said no woman by the name given as the author in
Izvestia, I. Zavgordnyaya, worked in the Crimea's libraries.
   He said library workers were called to a meeting in May at which
cultural officials recommended outdated political and economic
literature be transferred from village to city and regional
libraries. The village libraries are becoming overstocked and do
not have room for outdated materials and new works with little
demand, Bely said.
   He said the suggestion applied to village libraries throughout
the Soviet Union.
   The letter in Izvestia said the directive suggested that library
workers they tell people asking for the removed materials that they
are all on loan. The letter said it included works by former Soviet
leaders Brezhnev and Konstantin U. Chernenko ``and a series of
other authors.''
   The letter did not say who issued the order and did not say
whether it applied to public libraries throughout the Soviet Union.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said he was
surprised by the letter and had heard of no order like the one
mentioned.
   But he said the action sounded like a ``local initiative'' by
officials who were ``doing more than necessary'' to set the country
on the right course.
   He cited a Russian proverb to say that some local officials were
incompetent: ``Make a fool bow and he will be sure to knock his
head.''
   Brezhnev's rule from 1964 to his death in 1982 has been
criticized as plagued by corruption, cronyism and nepotism. He and
his aides have also been blamed for covering up the country's
problems and repressing independent political and cultural thinkers.
   Chernenko ruled from February 1984 until his death in March 1985.
   According to the Izvestia letter, the order covered ``outdated''
material from 1961 until the March 1985 session at which Gorbachev
was named party general secretary.
   The order seems to go against the new trend of taking the wraps
off materials that were closed to the public for many years, the
letter said.
   ``Wouldn't this mean that, while opening access to archival
materials of a half-century ago, we are creating new blank spots in
our most recent history?'' said the letter.
   Gorbachev, under his policy of glasnost, or openness, has
encouraged a more accurate and honest examination of Soviet
history. He has called for elimination of ``blank spots,'' taboo
subjects such as the repressions of Soviet dictator Josef Stalin.
   As a result of the review, Stalin has been criticized for
creating a ``cult of personality,'' and Brezhnev's tenure has been
branded a ``period of stagnation.''
   Before Gorbachev, almost every other Soviet leader has
encouraged the suppression of books and other works that deal with
policies, people or events that have fallen out of favor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
