<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-PLO     08-17 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-PLO,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egypt and PLO Agree on Provisional Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak agreed that the PLO
should establish a provisional Palestinian government in the
Israeli-occupied territories, a senior PLO official said.
   Mahmoud Abbas, a member of the PLO Executive Committee, spoke on
Egypt Television Tuesday night after meeting Mubarak in Alexandria.
He led a high-ranking Palestine Liberation Organization delegation
that arrived in Cairo on Monday.
   ``We and President Mubarak reached the conclusion that the PLO
should offer through a provisional government a political program
that would be internationally acceptable,'' said Abbas, also known
as Abu-Mazen.
   He said the political program would ``explain to the world the
rational and logical PLO objectives so as to corner the enemies of
our people's independence and self-determination.''
   He apparently referred to Israel, whose Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir opposes Palestinian self-determination that might lead to
the creation of an independent Palestinian state.
   PLO officials have said a provisonal government would be ready
to recognize Israel in exchange for Israel's recognition of a
Palestinian state in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The PLO reportedly is debating whether to declare a state in the
occupied lands, home to about 1.5 million Palestinians. It is also
considering whether to establish a provisional government or a
government-in-exile.
   These options were brought up after Jordan's decision this month
to hand to the PLO full responsibility for the West Bank and Gaza.
   Asked when an announcement of a Palestinian government could be
made, Abbas said, ``This is premature because we cannot announce a
governemnt before we have shaped its program and presented it to
the Palestine National Council.''
   The council, combining representatives from all PLO factions, is
the legislative arm that makes all major policy decisions. It is
expected to meet in Algeria next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
