<HEAD>Men Caught With Stolen Radio While Singing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police persuaded two Oklahoma City men to
sing ``Singin' in the Rain'' on stolen railroad radios, then
followed the sound of music to the brothers' apartment.
   Terry C. Gordon, 27, and Warren M. Gordon, 25, were talking and
singing on a radio frequency used by MK&T Railroad Co., said police
Detective Ed Bradway. Police say the Gordons used two hand-held
radios stolen from the company last week.
   Railroad officials claimed the Gordons' makeshift radio show
interrupted railroad procedures. Officials said someone would start
singing and talking on the radio frequency, preventing the engineer
from hearing.
   Police officers used a directional radio detector to track the
men down Friday night. Det. Bill Pierce said he asked the Gordons
to sing something, knowing the detector would pick up the signals.
   It took police about an hour to locate the Gordons when one of
the brothers belted out his rendition of ``Singin' in the Rain,''
Pierce said.
   ``I kind of hoped he would sing `I've Been Working on the
Railroad,''' Pierce said.
   The men were arrested on complaints of receiving and concealing
stolen property.
