<HEAD>Newspaper Publishes Fake Story About Low-Level Flights Over Paris</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with paper saying story was hoax.
No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British newspaper, Today, said today its story
about a daredevil pilot making low-level flights over Paris was a
fake.
   ``It was a complete and absolute spoof. ... It was a bit of
summer fun,'' Today's deputy news editor Alastair Martin said of
the story about the mystery pilot, nicknamed le Baron, or Black
Baron.
   ``We weren't fooled but a whole lot of other people obviously
have been,'' Martin said in a telephone interview.
   The 458,000-circulation tabloid daily, owned by publisher Rupert
Murdoch, ran the fake story over an entire inside page, along with
a picture of a man dressed as a pilot standing beside a light
aircraft.
   The story gave no indication it had been made up, and Martin
refused to elaborate on the reasoning behind publication.
   In the story, Today reporter Bill Mouland said the mystery flier
was a French aristocrat, le Comte de Guillaume, 35, who planned to
make similar buzzing flights over London.
   Low-level flights over Paris are illegal, but several times in
recent weeks a plane has been seen over the city late at night.
   French police, who have tightened surveillance to try to
identify the culprit, say they are not certain whether the flights
are by the same pilot each time.
</TEXT>
