<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--HomelessHousing     08-17 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Homeless Housing,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds To Turn Over Some Abandoned Houses for Homeless Shelters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agency plans to turn over some
of the 1,000 abandoned houses it owns in Minnesota to private
organizations for temporary housing for homeless people, an agency
official said.
   By November, the agency hopes to offer 10 to 15 single-family
houses rent-free to non-profit groups to provide transitional
housing, Patricia Mack of the federal Housing and Urban Development
Department said Tuesday.
   ``We want to see success,'' Mack said. ``If it works, it quite
likely will be increased.''
   Similar programs are under way in Denver and Los Angeles, Mack
said.
   The houses are owned by the government because the owners
defaulted on Federal Housing Administration-backed mortgages.
   HUD is asking local governments to designate non-profit
organizations to manage and maintain the houses, Mack said.
   ``This is a step in the right direction,'' said Charles Viebahn,
president of People United for Economic Justice, an advocacy group
that has occupied abandoned homes in Minneapolis and staged
protests at the HUD office to dramatize the plight of the homeless.
</TEXT>
