<HEAD>Former Editor of Banned Magazine Gets 9-Month Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former editor of a Christian magazine
banned by the government was sentenced Wednesday to nine months in
prison for failing to file paperwork with the registrar of
companies.
   Bedan Mbugua was arrested in March, three days after the
government banned his magazine, Beyond.
   The magazine said in an editorial in its March edition that the
Feb. 22 parliamentary primary election was ``a mockery of
democracy.''
   It also had alleged that some voters were intimidated by
administration officials into voting for certain candidates. A
controversial new election system called for officials to count
votes while citizens queued publicly behind the candidate of their
choice, or behind the candidate's agent.
   Chief Magistrate Joseph Mango found Mbugua guilty of failing to
submit certain documents on several dates between January 1986 and
March 1988.Mbugua argued that his responsibilities were confined to
Beyond's editorial content, but Mango ruled that even though he was
not the publisher, ``he may be liable to being charged.''
