<HEAD>Grocer Fatally Shot By Two Gunmen</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with another group claiming
responsibility. Pick up 4th pvs, `In 1985...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen today entered a
grocery store and shot its 44-year-old owner, who later died in a
hospital, police said.
   Frederick Otley was working in a rear storeroom of his store in
a Protestant section of Belfast when the gunmen entered and asked
for the owner. When Otley appeared, they shot him several times and
fled, police said.
   The Irish National Liberation Army, an extreme Marxist offshoot
of the Irish Republican Army, claimed responsibility for the
shooting in a statement to the British Broadcasting Corp. in
Belfast.
   But the Irish News, a Belfast newspaper, said it received a
statement claiming responsibility from the Irish Revolutionary
Brigade, a group previously unheard of in Northern Ireland.
   Both news organizations said the statements they received were
accompanied by authenticating passwords.
   In 1985, Otley was accused by an informer of terrorist crimes on
behalf of the Protestant paramilitary Ulster Volunteer Force, and
was charged with a bombing at a social club which was meant to kill
a force member during an inter-organization feud.
   The charges were dropped when the informer retracted his
statement.
   The British domestic agency Press Association reported that the
murder may have been in retaliation for Protestant guerrillas'
killings of two Catholics last week in Belfast.
   Seamus Morris, 18, and Peter Dolan, 25, were gunned down in a
shopping center in broad daylight in the Catholic Ardoyne area of
north Belfast. The Protestant Action Force, reportedly linked with
the Ulster Volunteer Force, claimed responsibility.
   The Irish Republican Army has been fighting to drive the British
from the predominantly Protestant province and unite it with the
overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
