<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Pakistan,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Pakistan-Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>State Department Reaffirms Close Ties With Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department reaffirmed strong U.S.
ties with Pakistan ``at this moment of extreme trial'' following
the death today of President Zia ul-Haq.
   ``We are greatly saddened by the tragedy and convey our deepest
condolences to the government and the people of Pakistan,''
spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said.
   The U.S. official also paid tribute to Arnold L. Raphel, the
American ambassador, who died in the crash. ``The United States has
lost one of its best diplomats and grief goes out to his wife and
his family,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   Pakistan has channeled U.S. missiles and other arms to
anti-government rebels in Afghanistan and helped negotiate the
ongoing withdrawal of Soviet troops from the South Asian country.
   ``We have a long history of close and friendly cooperation with
Pakistan,'' Mrs. Oakley said. ``At this moment of extreme trial, I
want to reiterate our commitment to Pakistan and our full support
for the acting president and his government.''
</TEXT>
