<HEAD>Vice President Saddened by Loss of Zia, U.S. Ambassador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said today the
military plane crash that killed Pakistani President Mohammed Zia
ul-Haq and the American ambassador in Pakistan was a ``great
tragedy.''
   Bush, making a brief statement about today's crash before a news
conference with Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, his newly named running
mate, revealed that a second American, as yet unidentified, died in
the crash with Ambassador Arnold Raphel. No one among the 37 people
aboard were believed to have survived.
   Bush said he wanted to express ``how horrible I feel about the
tragedy in Pakistan.'' in which a C-130 transport plane exploded
just after takeoff from Bahawalpur, about 330 miles southwest of
the capital of Islamabad.
   ``Pakistan and the United States have a very special relationshp
and the loss of General Zia is a great tragedy,'' he said. He also
called Raphel, 45, an ``outstanding ambassador. ... I knew him
well.''
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., said the death of Zia was a
``severe blow to Pakistan and to our policy'' in the region.
   Although Humphrey said the ``circumstances are suspicious''
surrounding the crash, he did not have enough information to say it
was sabotage. Conflicting reports from Pakistan speculated the
plane might have been struck by an anti-aircraft missile.
   Humphrey was a key supporter in Congress of the Afghan rebels
who battled Soviet troops during their occupation of Afghanistan,
and U.S. aid to the rebels was channeled through Pakistan.
   Humphrey called Zia ``a courageous bulwark'' who ``withstood the
bullying,'' including aerial attacks from the Soviets. Where it not
for Zia, he said, ``Afghanistan would be part of the Soviet
empire.''
</TEXT>
