<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: First 4 grafs new, picking up 3rd graf pvs, Dukakis spent</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dukakis On The Road For Final Days Of GOP Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis began a four-day
campaign swing hoping to steal some of the spotlight from the
Republican National Convention with a midday rally in this Iron
Range town.
   Before addressing several thousand people at a community college
stadium, he told a welcoming gathering at the airport in nearby
Hibbing that Minnesota ``has always been very good'' to Democrats,
``and I hope and expect to have a nice victory here in November.''
   Appearing with him at the community college rally were former
Vice President Walter Mondale, the Democrats' 1984 presidential
nominee, and state Attorney General Skip Humphrey, son of the late
Sen. Hubert H. Humphrey.
   From here, he was flying to Minneapolis for a private reception
and then Miami for an address Thursday to a Greek organization.
   Dukakis spent Monday and Tuesday on a tour of central
Massachusetts but interrupted his busy schedule of state events
long enough to turn Reagan's ``facts are stubborn things'' refrain
on the Republicans and their certain nominee, Vice President George
Bush.
   ``Facts are stubborn things,'' Dukakis agreed as he listed facts
he said Republicans are failing to acknowledge at their convention:
increases in the national crime rate and the federal trade and
budget deficit.
   ``This is a nation that eight years ago was the largest creditor
nation in the world,'' Dukakis said in Worcester. ``Today we are
the largest debtor nation in the world. That's the consequence of
eight years of borrowing and spending and borrowing and spending.
Facts are stubborn things and these are the facts we are going to
be debating. ... It will be Mr. Bush who will have to respond to
those facts.''
   He then shifted to foreign policy but kept the refrain, first
used by Reagan in his address to the Republican convention Monday
night, as he reeled off a list of Reagan administration
embarrassments.
   ``Iran-Contra. Noriega. Beirut,'' Dukakis said. ``Facts are
stubborn things.''
   Dukakis said he expected the GOP convention would help Bush cut
into his lead in the polls but predicted the effect would not be
lasting and that Reagan would not be a major factor.
   ``Things will settle down,'' Dukakis said. ``This is an election
between Michael Dukakis and George Bush. The question (voters) are
going to be asking themselves is which one of us has the ability to
lead.''
   Dukakis also had his own interpretation of another remark from
the Reagan speech _ the president's assertion that Bush should be
elected because the nation could not afford to have a president who
would need ``on-the-job-training.''
   Said Dukakis: ``The same might have been said of the Republican
nominee in 1980,'' referring to Reagan, the former California
governor. ``None of us comes to the presidency with on-the-job
training, least of all vice presidents,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis also said he was not bothered by the harsh criticism of
him at the Republican convention.
   ``If you went through what I went through in the mid-70s, it's a
day at the beach,'' said Dukakis, who was voted out of office in
1978 after countering a budget crisis by slashing welfare benefits
and raising taxes in his first term. He returned to office in 1983.
   Dukakis said he spoke to former rival Jesse Jackson on Wednesday
and that he expected a joint campaign appearance soon. ``It's going
to be a close relationship,'' Dukakis said.
   After the Miami event Thursday morning, Dukakis is scheduled to
travel to Alabama and spend the night in St. Louis. Friday's
schedule includes stops in Illinois, Arkansas and Texas, where
Dukakis also is to spend Saturday campaigning with running mate
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
</TEXT>
