<HEAD>Undetermined Number Arrested On Federal Indictments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal, state and local officials
today arrested several people in three states on federal
indictments involving drug trafficking and at least $1.6 million in
stolen property, authorities said.
   Sealed federal indictments returned Monday name 105 people in
West Virginia, Kentucky and Ohio, said state Trooper Ric Robinson.
Authorities did not give a specific number of people arrested today.
   A source, who agreed to speak only on condition of anonymity,
said the majority of the cases involve the theft of heavy equipment
and parts for heavy equipment, while a handful focus on drug
trafficking.
   The investigation began in 1986 by FBI and West Virginia state
police, dubbed ``Operation Mine Stopper,'' involves theft of
weapons, cars, motorcycles, four-wheel drives, washers, dryers and
a variety of heavy equipment, Robinson said.
   Several people were arrested and taken to the federal Magistrate
Court in Huntington this morning, authorities said. About one-third
of the federal building was blocked off to the public and state
police cruisers transporting defendants took over all public
parking on the block.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joe Savage, who represented prosecutors
at the arraignments this morning, declined to comment on the
arrests.
   ``This investigation will continue over the coming months and
many more arrests are expected,'' said West Virginia state police
Col. W.F. Donohoe. ``Several hundred crimes have been involved with
these arrests.''
   About 125 law enforcement officers were making arrests,
authorities said.
</TEXT>
