<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Parties     08-17 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Parties,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bourbon Street Courts GOP, But Turnout Unimpressive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bourbon Street is courting Republicans, but
snugly sealed GOP pocketbooks and free diversions elsewhere have
made the exotic avenue a spurned suitor.
   Bar and food tabs are paltry, tips are tiny and seats are empty
in many Bourbon Street clubs and restaurants, proprietors complain.
   Money and morals are factors, they speculate, along with the
Republican National Convention's late-night schedule that leaves
many conventioneers too pooped to party in the French Quarter.
   ``I've always kind of wanted to see Bourbon Street, and now I
have,'' said Alex Day, 19, a former Pat Robertson supporter from
Litchfield, Ky. ``I've seen enough. I'm going back to the hotel.''
   Young Republicans have spent the most money, club owners said in
interviews. Older party members ``haven't been spending as much as
even other kinds of convention-goers,'' said Harold Tannenbaum,
manager of the Krazy Korner bar on Bourbon Street.
   ``They are not much in the way of tipping,'' Tannenbaum said.
``The girls have been complaining. They haven't been taking as much
as they usually do.''
   Robin Parks, who minds the door at Ryan's Irish Pub, said the
average tab for four has been $100. ``They're really not spending a
lot of money,'' she said. ``I think the Democrats would have been a
little bit rowdier.''
   Louis Karno has changed closing time at his Famous Door bar to
accomodate the conventioneers. ``Some are coming out really late,
and we're keeping our bands here,'' he said.
   Fred Sullivan, a bartender at Le Booze Bar, said the week's more
than 500 parties, brunches and receptions have hurt Bourbon Street
crowds. ``It's been taking a lot of people off the streets,'' he
said.
   John Fillman, doorman at Chris Owens' club, said he looks for an
upturn once the convention ends Thursday night.
   David Ervin, who sells margaritas and hurricanes from a tiny
stand on Bourbon Street, agreed: ``It's still early. The weekend
hasn't gotten here.''
</TEXT>
