<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--GOP-Farm     08-17 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--GOP-Farm,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Luminaries Quickly Turn Spotlight on Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A string of Republican luminaries from
certain nominee George Bush on down ridiculed Democratic nominee
Michael Dukakis' farm policies Wednesday, the day after ``a son of
the Midwest'' was picked for the No. 2 spot on the GOP ticket.
   Bush, Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole and Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng took aim at a ``Belgian endive'' comment
that's dogged Dukakis since the early days of the campaign.
   Dukakis got in trouble when he suggested that farmers could
diversify their crops, in part by growing Belgian endive.
   ``I don't think that Belgian endive is the answer to American
agriculture,'' Bush told a breakfast for farm-state Republicans.
``My wife likes Belgian endive, but I hate them.''
   ``Poor Michael, he can't be blamed,'' Lyng said. ``He grew up in
the city and he doesn't know the difference between Belgian endive
and corn.''
   ``I thought it was part of his foreign policy,'' said Dole.
   Bush tabbed Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle to be his running mate, and
there was instant speculation that the selection would bolster
Republican chances in the Midwest, where recession and drought have
hurt Bush.
   Bush lost a series of primary and caucus contests in the
Midwest, before clinching the nomination. Some polls have suggested
that Dukakis is ahead in the traditionally Republican Farm Belt.
   The selection of Quayle clearly buoyed the spirits of the
Midwesterners, and Bush and former rival Dole were upbeat about
Republican chances.
   ``It's certainly an indication that he understands the
importance of rural America,'' Dole said.
   ``I am an optimist about agricultural America,'' Bush said.
``Main street is not going to dry up under a George Bush
administration. As president, I am pledged to helping rural
America.''
   And Bush wasn't subtle about how the Quayle selection would fit
into that effort.
   ``I have suggested to the convention that a son of the Midwest
be on our ticket and Dan Quayle will be working hard to carry the
message,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
