<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CliffRescue     08-17 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cliff Rescue,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Rescued From Cliff Over Ocean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH BEND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Coast Guard helicopter pilot landed on
a cliff and helped strap a stranded hiker into a harness to rescue
her from her tiny perch 80 feet above the ocean, officials said.
   ``I'm sure if they hadn't done this it would have been certain
death for the woman, because she was perched in a very precarious
spot,'' Coast Guard Petty Officer 1st Class Jim Hinde said.
   Letitia Croom, about 50, of Nyssa was hiking Tuesday along the
cliff near Cape Blanco about seven miles north of Port Orford,
Hinde said.
   She apparently slipped off the trail to a ledge, measuring about
2 feet by 2 feet, that was about 80 feet above the ocean, Hinde
said.
   Alerted by the Curry County Sheriff's Department, the Coast
Guard sent a helicopter.
   The helicopter pilot turned over the controls to the co-pilot
and was lowered by hoist to a nearby ledge, where he gave the woman
his helmet and helped her into the hoist harness, Hinde said.
   ``They hoisted her up into the helicopter and then set her down
on the beach,'' Hinde said.
   The woman was uninjured, sheriff's deputy Karen Baker said
Wednesday. ``She's in perfect shape, no injuries whatsoever.''
</TEXT>
