<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF-CVN--ConventionBooks     08-17 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF-CVN--Convention Books,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Biggie: Thomas Kean's Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean is a bigger hit
than Vice President George Bush at the bookstore nearest the
Superdome, where the Republican National Convention is going on.
   ``That's the biggie this week,'' Stephanie Renfro, a saleswoman
at the B. Dalton Bookstore across an elevated walkway from the
Superdome, said as she pointed to ``The Politics of Inclusion.''
   ``What isn't selling is anything about him,'' she said, pointing
to Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis' portrait on the
cover of ``The Man Who Would Be President.''
   ``And also not selling is anything of this negative Reagan
stuff,'' Renfro said, pointing out books by President Reagan's
former press secretary, Larry Speakes; the president's son,
Michael, and his former chief of staff, Donald Regan.
   And ``Looking Forward,'' the autobiography of Vice President
George Bush, the man who will become the Republican nominee later
this week?
   ``It's selling. It's not on fire. But it's steady,'' Renfro said.
</TEXT>
