<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--BarbaraBush     08-17 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Barbara Bush,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Wife Reaches Out to Blacks, Hispanics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush, meeting with black and Hispanic
groups at the Republican National Convention, said Wednesday that
she's glad ``the doors of the Republican Party are wide open.''
   Praising the tone of ``inclusion'' set by keynote speaker Thomas
Kean, Mrs. Bush told the National Hispanic Assembly, ``I'm
enormously pleased that you have chosen to seek solutions in the
company of George Bush and the GOP.''
   Mrs. Bush visited a host of breakfasts hours before the roll
call vote that would give her husband the Republican presidential
nomination. She also visited a combined senior citizen and day care
center.
   In stops at breakfast meetings of black, Hispanic, Jewish and
elderly groups, she put in a plug for her campaign to improve
literacy in America.
   ``George is going to lead an education revival,'' she told the
``Black American Salute to Barbara Bush'' breakfast.
   ``George Bush will do everything he can to make a truly literate
America, where every American can read and write,'' she said.
``Now, we're counting on you to get this message out.''
   At a Hispanic breakfast, she was introduced by Florida Gov. Bob
Martinez, with one of Mrs. Bush's sons, Jeb, the state secretary of
commerce, standing by.
   She said she and her husband are interested in the problems of
Hispanic-Americans, and ``it's not just because we're linked by
blood.'' Jeb Bush's wife Columba is Mexican-American, and they have
three children.
   ``We share the same basic values, deep belief in family,'' Mrs.
Bush said. She also reiterated that her husband opposes any move
``to take the potentially divisive step of making English our
official language.''
   For that, she was given a loud ovation.
   ``Your political influence is only beginning to be felt,'' Mrs.
Bush said.
   Later, Mrs. Bush toured the Kingsley House in a poor section of
the city, a day-care facility that doubles as a place for the
elderly to congregate.
   Walking among tables covered with red and white plastic
tablecloths, she sat down next to a young man in a wheelchair. She
told Henry Neeley, 32, she had learned that he had come to the
center to be a social worker, but now was busy getting his Graduate
Equivalency Diploma.
   ``You're an inspiration to us all,'' she said.
</TEXT>
