<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeff Bridges, who's been in more than two dozen
movies since 1971, says he could have done even more.
   ``Success opens up a lot of opportunities, sometimes too many,''
the 38-year-old star of ``Tucker: The Man and His Dream'' said in
the September issue of Esquire.
   ``I don't want to go as fast as I'm capable of going, so I have
these anchors I throw out from time to time to slow things down. I
don't need more opportunity. I have too much right now, too many
choices to make.''
   One choice is a career in music, which he was serious about long
before acting entered the picture. Bridges has written more than
100 songs and has a fully equipped log-cabin studio on his 900-acre
ranch in Montana.
   ``I just don't know whether it will ever go beyond the serious
hobby stage,'' he says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Larry Gatlin has been
chosen to receive the 60th American Education Award from the
American Association of School Administrators.
   Kathy Gangwisch, a spokeswoman for Gatlin, said the singer will
be honored for speaking against drug and alcohol abuse. Gatlin has
spoken to numerous high school groups about his own battle against
addiction.
   He will be presented the award next March in Orlando, Fla., at
the association's annual convention.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kathleen DuRoss Ford, the widow of
Henry Ford II, is asking a judge to bar a new trustee of her
husband's $350 million estate from collecting a $1 million salary
she claims is extortionate.
   Attorneys asked Palm Beach County Circuit Judge Vaughn Rudnick
on Tuesday to temporarily enjoin William Donaldson, who owns an
investment firm, from acting as a trustee.
   ``It's an attempt to extort from the trust,'' said Greg
Barnhart, one of her attorneys. Donaldson ``wants a million dollars
a year for no work.''
   Donaldson has said he would become a trustee only if paid a $1
million annual salary. He said it was ``completely false'' that the
salary was unjustified. As a trustee, he said, it would be his duty
to help manage the estate, making decisions on investments and
expenditures.
   On Tuesday, the judge scheduled another hearing Sept. 26 and
barred any trustee meetings before that time.
   Ford, grandson of the founder of Ford Motor Co., died in
September 1987 at age 70. Before his death, he named as trustees of
the estate Mrs. Ford, who was his third wife; Edsel Ford II, his
son by a previous wife; and businessman and family friend Martin
Citrin. He named Donaldson as a successor if any of the other three
died, and Citrin died in April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CORNING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Samuel E. Wright plays a seedy character on
television _ a bunch of grapes in the Fruit of the Loom underwear
ads. And at 39, he's also cast against type in his current
theatrical role.
   Wright is playing Midge Carter, an 82-year-old character, in
Herb Gardner's Tony Award-winning comedy, ``I'm Not Rappaport''
this week at the Corning Summer Theater.
   ``It gives me an escape from being a young adult,'' Wright said.
``I can say anything I please, I can do all these human things I
never get to do.''
   Wright originated the role of the grapes in the underwear
commercials 15 years ago, making it one of the longest-running ads
in TV.
   ``Mr. Whipple isn't squeezing Charmin anymore, but we're still
four grown men running around in foam suits,'' he said.
   While he prefers the more human roles he plays on the stage,
Wright said he has no plans to give up his juicy Fruit of the Loom
role.
   ``It's my bread and butter,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music singer Kathy Mattea says
she doesn't perform for critics or awards.
   ``You can't put all your self-worth in what the critics say,''
she said. ``It's not something I spend a lot of time thinking
about.''
   Miss Mattea, 29, has been nominated for a Grammy, but she hasn't
won. She also has yet to win a Country Music Association award,
though she's a contender this year.
   What Miss Mattea has done is churn out hits, including ``18
Wheels and a Dozen Roses.''
   ``I don't do it for the glamour,'' said the Cross Lanes, W.Va.,
native who moved to Nashville 10 years ago. ``It's not all that
glamorous. ... I don't do it for the reviews or the awards.''
   Miss Mattea and her band recently returned from a European tour
and performed last week at the Greene County Fair.
   ``Music wasn't really something I sat down and decided to do
when I was young,'' she said the day of her Greeneville show.
``Everything that led to my career as a singer just happened. ... I
just sort of drifted into all of this.''
</TEXT>
