<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--ConventionRdp 8thLd-Writethru a0692 08-17 1072</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention Rdp, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0692,1140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Quayle Qualified to Be ``Heartbeat Away'' From
Presidency</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Reagan call, travel plans, inserting 4 grafs
after 3rd graf pvs, ``We agree; trims from end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush today called his new running
mate, Sen. Dan Quayle, ``one of the rising stars in the Republican
Party'' and said the youthful conservative is qualified to be ``one
heartbeat away from the presidency.''
   Bush said the 41-year-old Indiana senator would help the GOP
ticket in every region of America. ``We're going to tell the truth
and it's going to seem like they've (the Democrats) engaged a
couple of pit bulls,'' Bush said.
   ``We agree on the fundamental challenges that face this
country,'' the vice president said, standing alongside his running
mate at a news conference just hours before the Republican National
Convention was to deliver Bush its 1988 presidential nomination.
   From his mountaintop ranch in California, the vacationing
President Reagan telephoned Quayle with congratulations Tuesday
night. White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said a joint
Reagan-Bush appearance is being considered for next Wednesday in
Los Angeles.
   Bush and Quayle will make their first campaign appearance on the
road Friday at a courthouse rally in Quayle's hometown of
Huntington, Ind., 25 miles southwest of Fort Wayne.
   Traveling together around this convention city, Bush and Quayle
appeared at a news conference and at a rousing rally given by the
California delegation. Hoping to capture the state's huge cache of
47 electoral votes, Bush said, ``California is essential. We will
not overlook it. We will concentrate on it.''
   California Gov. George Deukmejian, who earlier said that Quayle
would neither help nor hurt in California, praised the choice of
the Hoosier senator ``bold and imaginative.''
   The first question at the news conference was whether Quayle was
qualified to step in as president should anything happen to Bush.
The vice president said, ``I've listened to his peers ... who speak
eloquently of Dan Quayle's standing to be one heartbeat away from
the presidency.''
   Describing his qualifications, Quayle said he had spent a dozen
years in Congress, had experience in Indiana state government and
``had met a payroll'' at his family newspaper in Indiana. Quayle
has been in Congress since he was 29 years old.
   Quayle was asked about whether he had been involved with Paula
Parkinson, the key figure in a sex-and-influence scandal in 1980.
Quayle and two other members of Congress spent a weekend with
Parkinson in a Florida condominium.
   ``That has been covered and there's nothing to it,'' Quayle
said. Asked if he had seen Parkinson on any other occasion, he
said, ``No.''
   Quayle said he considered it to be ``a cheap shot'' to suggest
that he ducked service in Vietnam by enlisting in the National
Guard.
   ``I have a deep affection for those men and women who sacrificed
their lives in Vietnam and for anybody to imply anything
differently is just simply wrong,'' he said.
   He said it was not a handicap that he had not served in Vietnam.
   Earlier in the day Bush practiced his acceptance speech at the
podium of the Louisiana Superdome convention hall where his
nomination will be secured late tonight.
   ``We'll do all right, I'll do OK,'' he said of his acceptance
speech, set for Thursday night.
   Quayle, an heir to the Pulliam newspaper publishing empire, was
asked about reports that his wealth exceeded $200 million.
   ``That figure is not correct,'' Quayle said. ``Believe me, you
have caused me a lot of problems at home because my wife is asking
about that.'' He promised that a full financial statement would be
forthcoming.
   Bush, asked if the addition of Quayle underscored the image of
Republicans as the party of the rich, said, ``I picked the best
man. ... It's not a question of personal wealth.''
   Bush was asked if it was smart politics to choose a running mate
so much like himself. ``He's different from me,'' Bush said. ``I'm
64 and he is 41.''
   Bush said that making his choice was ``a tough call. There were
several men and women who fit the criteria. I felt Dan Quayle was
the best choice,'' adding that ``he helps me nationally.''
   ``I didn't think I had to do something bold or different,'' the
vice president added.
   Bush bridled when a reporter asked him what he had meant Tuesday
when he introduced his three Mexican-American grandchildren to
President Reagan as ``the little brown ones.''
   ``Those grandchildren are my pride and joy,'' the vice president
said. ``I find it personally offensive'' to suggest otherwise.
``And p.s. _ I don't want to see these kids hurt. This is family
and I'm going to protect them.''
   Bush opened his news conference by expressing ``how horrible I
feel'' about the deaths today of President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq and
U.S. Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel. They were killed today when their
Pakistani military plane exploded in the eastern part of that
country.
   Turning back to politics, Bush said he and Quayle would be a
formidable challenge to the Democratic team of Michael Dukakis and
Lloyd Bentsen.
   Describing Quayle as ``one of the rising stars in the Republican
Party,'' Bush said he picked the Indiana senator for several
reasons. ``Most importantly, he's qualified,'' Bush said.
   Moroever, he said, ``We agree on the fundamental challenges that
face this country: how to keep America strong and secure, how to
create opportunities for American families. While a Midwesterner, I
believe he will help our cause in every part of the country.''
   The news conference provided Bush with an opportunity to tweak
the Dukakis-Bentsen team about the differences on policy issues.
   ``We aren't going off in two different directions like the
Demcoratic ticket. ... We won't have to debate each other,'' the
vice president said.
   On the other hand, Paul Brountas, campaign chairman for
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, said Quayle was
``relatively inexperienced.'' He suggested Bush ``seemed to make a
decision that placated the right wing of the Republican Party.''
   Many delegates admitted that they didn't know much about Bush's
choice, but seemed enthusiastic anyway about the selection of the
two-term junior senator from Indiana.
   ``Super, super choice,'' said John Lindley III, chairman of the
Vermont delegation. ``A real spark plug for Bush,'' said North
Dakota GOP chairman Layton Freborg. ``We need the female vote.
He'll do the trick,'' added Sharon Estrada of Montana. ``He's very
cute.''
</TEXT>
