<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-17 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRISCO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Could Tony Bennett leave his heart in
Frisco Bay?
   That's the question being asked around town ever since the idea
of renaming this small mountain community was floated at a town
meeting earlier this month.
   Never mind that there are no little cable cars, though there are
plenty of cable-pulled chair lifts for winter skiers.
   There's no San Francisco Bay, either _ but there is Lake Dillon.
   Robert Philippe, a real estate agent and vice chairman of a
commission formed to develop the lake area, is the proponent of the
name change. Only 200 of the town's 1,7000 residents need to sign a
petition, he said at the meeting, to put the name change on the
ballot.
   ``We think the name Frisco Bay is more descriptive of exactly
what the town is,'' said Philippe.
   Frisco Bay proponents have delayed a petition drive until after
a vote on a home-rule proposition that would help with financing
such lakeside improvements as a marina and golf course.
   Not everyone is captivated.
   Karen Mack, manager of the Frisco Historical Park, said the name
change strays from the town's heritage as an early Colorado mining
camp.
   It isn't clear how the town got its name, although one story is
told in which a sign reading ``Frisco House'' _ the name of a
notorious bordello in nearby Leadville _ was nailed to one of the
first cabins in town, and the name stuck.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Champion pigs are no lightweights.
   Take The Chief, for instance. The Berkshire pig tops the scales
at 1,110 pounds. The Indiana State Fair calls him the world's
largest hog.
   The champ's owner, Bob M. Corbett of North Lewisburg, Ohio,
collected $250 for the title and $100 because the champion was over
1,000 pounds. He also received a plaque.
   The reserve champion weighed only five pounds less. Monica and
David Lamb of Delphi collected $200 and a plaque for their entry
named Oscar.
   Both the champion and the reserve champion are on display until
Aug. 28, when the fair ends.
</TEXT>
