<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--ShyMayor     08-17 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Shy Mayor,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Pushes Barthelemy Into National Spotlight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The room was a politician's dream.
   Red, white and blue banners hung from the ceiling. An orchestra,
a jazz band and a chorus of political and religious leaders lined
the stage, and more than 6,000 potential voters sat in the audience.
   Backstage, Mayor Sidney Barthelemy was asked to deliver the
pledge of allegiance and kick off a two-hour ecumenical breakfast
honoring the Republican National Convention and arranged by his
wife, Mickey.
   ``Nah,'' said the mayor, almost mumbling. ``My wife is the star
of the program.''
   As his city basks in media attention, scores of interviewers
have forced the often bashful Barthelemy to share the spotlight.
   ``I don't seek it. It just happens,'' Barthelemy said.
   It began before dawn Tuesday.
   His face dabbed with make-up, the mayor sat in the ``Today''
show trailer, nibbling grapes and watching television. He did not
introduce himself to the two political analysts sitting beside him
on the couch.
   When his turn came to be interviewed _ for the hundredth time
this week, he sighed _ Jane Pauley asked the two routine questions:
Why is a Democratic city hosting the Republican National
Convention, and what's the economic impact?
   The mayor gave his routine answers: The Republicans were smart
enough to choose New Orleans, and the economy needs help but the
city is on its way.
   Then Pauley threw in a surprise: Former Arizona Sen. Barry
Goldwater, who forgot his credentials and had trouble getting onto
the Superdome floor Monday, called this convention the worst he'd
ever seen. Did the mayor have any comment?
   ``The Republicans run inside the Dome and we run outside, and
that's where we're doing a great job,'' Barthelemy said, bringing
warm applause from the audience.
   ``They clapped,'' the mayor said as he walked off the set. He
seemed surprised. ``They almost made me lose my concentration.''
</TEXT>
