<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-BenandJerry     08-17 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Ben and Jerry,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ice Cream Makers Promote World Peace Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben and Jerry, who make ice cream in Vermont for
fun as well as profit, came to New York on Wednesday to push peace.
   The medium of their message was, of course, ice cream _ a
four-ounce, chocolate-covered bar on a stick that they are
marketing as Ben & Jerry's Peace Pop.
   ``The purpose of the pop is to promote peace,'' Ben Cohen said
at a news conference in Ralph Bunche Park, across the street from
the United Nations.
   The partners said they will give 1 percent of the profits from
the pops and the rest of their business to their recently formed
organization, 1 Percent for Peace.
   That will amount to about $50,000 a year, said Jerry Greenfield,
the numbers expert in the partnership.
   He said the company will crank out 12{ million Peace Pops a year
in four flavors, with a retail price of about $1.75.
   The pop is packed with a message appealing to customers to join
1 Percent for Peace in its effort to persuade Congress to mandate
that 1 percent of the military budget, or about $3 billion, be
channeled into projects for peace.
   Cohen said other businesses that have agreed to contribute 1
percent of their pretax profits to the peace include Natural
Nectars, a California food company, Double Rainbow Ice Cream of San
Francisco, Stonyfield Yogurt of New Hampshire and Smith & Hawkin, a
California gardening supplier.
   Possible uses of the money include educational exchange
programs, joint U.S.-Soviet projects in third world countries, a
multinational youth corps and support for local forums in which
ordinary citizens could decide to back programs they believe will
advance peace.
   Cohen and Greenfield, both 37 and friends since seventh grade,
live in Jericho and Williston, Vt., respectively and make their
critically acclaimed ice cream in Waterbury, Vt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
