<DOCNO> AP880817-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1921EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YonkersDeseg     08-17 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yonkers Battle Moves to Appeals Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead planned by early evening, after court hearing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle to keep the city of Yonkers out of
possible bankruptcy and defiant city councilmen out of jail moved
Wednesday to a federal appeals court.
   The City Council again rejected a federal court-ordered housing
desegregation plan early Tuesday, despite potentially bankrupting
fines issued after it voted the same way two weeks ago.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals began hearing arguments
Wednesday afternoon by lawyers for the city and four recalcitrant
councilmen seeking to overturn the contempt of court citation
issued two weeks ago by U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand.
   On Aug. 1, the Council voted 4-3 against a resolution endorsing
a subsidized housing plan to integrate the state's fourth-largest
city. The plan was in accordance with a federal court order for 200
units of low-income housing and 800 units of moderate-income
housing throughout Yonkers.
   Sand then held the city and the four council members who voted
against the plan in contempt, threatening the four with jail. He
also issued heavy fines against the city.
   The escalating fines against the city began at $100 and doubled
daily with a potential total of $337 million _ the amount of the
city's entire annual budget _ within 22 days. The city's fines had
accumulated to $25,600 when a three-judge panel of the federal
appeals court ordered them temporarily halted last week pending the
appeal of the contempt order.
   Sand also ordered the council to meet once a week to cast
another vote on the housing plan. This week's meeting was the first.
   Sand's contempt ruling was the most serious step in his
continuing battle impose a plan to build hundreds of subsidized
apartments in Yonkers' predominantly white neighborhoods. That plan
stemmed from Sand's 1985 landmark ruling that Yonkers had
deliberately segregated housing and schools for four decades.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
