<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mandela     08-17 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandela,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Jailed Black Leader Getting Best Hospital Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha said
Wednesday that jailed black leader Nelson Mandela, reportedly
suffering from tuberculosis, is getting the best possible care in a
hospital and wished him a speedy recovery.
   Botha, in his first public comment on Mandela's illness, said
the 70-year-old African National Congress leader was ``in a special
category of his own'' and was receiving individualized attention
exceeding ``the normal high standards of medical care provided by
the prisons and health authorities.''
   The president's remarks were made in a letter to the Rev. Frank
Chikane, a prominent black activist who had expressed concern about
Mandela's care.
   ``We are even more concerned and do wish Mr. Mandela a speedy
recovery,'' Botha said in his letter. The text was released by the
president's office.
   Mandela, who has been jailed since 1962, is serving a life
sentence for sabotage and conspiracy to overthrow the white-ruled
government. He was transferred Friday to Tygerberg Hospital in Cape
Town from nearby Pollsmoor Prison.
   His lawyer, Ismail Ayob, announced Wednesday that doctors
diagnosed Mandela's illness as tuberculosis. Hospital authorities
have refused to confirm or deny this and said Mandela asked them to
withhold comment.
   Tygerberg's superintendent, Dr. J.G.L. Strauss, said Wednesday
that Mandela had a ``good prognosis'' for complete recovery.
   Mandela was ``up and about'' and responding well to treatment,
Strauss said, adding that Mandela was satisfied with his treatment.
   Chikane, on behalf of the Mandela family, had urged authorities
to allow an independent medical team to examine Mandela. Hospital
officials said Mandela turned down such an offer.
   Botha said Mandela ``is being treated by doctors that are
internationally recognized as experts in their fields.''
   ``I am therefore of the opinion that the medical team presently
in charge of the treatment and Mr. Mandela be allowed jointly to
decide on whether other medical assistance should be called in,''
Botha said.
   The illness renewed speculation that the government might
consider releasing Mandela. The government has given no indication
of any change in its stance.
   The African National Congress is the major guerrilla
organization fighting the government and its apartheid system of
racial segregation.
   Botha suggested in 1986 that Mandela, whom many blacks consider
their paramount leader, could be released if he renounced violence.
Mandela said he would do so only if the guerrilla movement was
unbanned and apartheid was dismantled.
   Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee, who oversees the prison system,
said Tuesday he was ``deeply perturbed'' by the reports of
Mandela's ill health.
   ``The entire issue, as well as steps to ensure a speedy
recovery, are receiving my personal attention,'' Coetsee said.
   Doctors say Mandela is in satisfactory condition after removal
of a drainage tube from his inflamed left lung. Strauss said
Mandela has been ``steadily improving since his admission.''
   But Ayob said Mandela was bedridden for most of the past two
weeks.
   ``His condition has been deteriorating for some time,'' Ayob
said. ``He was short of breath, he had a persistent cough, his
speech had been impaired and by last Friday he had lost his voice
completely.
   ``He looked very thin and suddenly looked very much older,''
Ayob said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--GOPTicket-Text 9thadd   08-17 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--GOP Ticket-Text, 9th add,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEW ORLEANS: national security.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q. Senator Quayle, listening to the Democrats trying to knock
you down very quickly _ and this morning they were attacking you as
someone who says he's tough on defense _ but from your era, you
didn't fight in the Vietnam War. I'm wondering if you think that
that's a low blow from them, or if you'd like to respond to them,
going on the attack on you on that matter?
   Quayle: Yes, I do perceive that as being a cheap shot.
   I have a deep affection for those men and women that sacrificed
their lives in Vietnam.
   And anybody, to imply anything differently is just simply wrong.
   Q. But my point is Mr. Bush was a war hero in World War II,
you're tough on defense _ do you think it's going to be a handicap
in the campaign that you didn't fight in Vietnam?
   Quayle: No, I do not.
   Q. Mr. Vice President, some of your staff have been at pains to
point out what a bold stroke your choice of Senator Quayle was. How
important was it for you to show that you're your own man, a
risk-taker, willing to take a bold stroke?
   Bush: Well, I don't think it's a great risk, because I think
that when the country sees what I have already seen, and when the
country understands why these senators with whom this man works are
so high on him, that they will see it as a very natural choice.
   So I don't think, as I went through the decision-making process,
I wasn't, I wasn't compelled to say I've got to do something bold
or something different.
   I went through a serious process.
   I hope I did it in a dignified way.
   I think we had control of the situation and as I, the more I
thought about it, the more I thought this was the best possible
choice I could make.
   Right here, yes, sir.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
