<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hess     08-17 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hess,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Right-wing Demonstrates on Anniversary of Nazi's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WUNSIEDEL, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jackbooted demonstrators carrying
swastika banners were arrested Wednesday near the burial site of
Rudolf Hess on the first anniversary of his death.
   The group of 14 Italians and an Irishman rallied briefly, but
they were taken into custody before nearing the cemetery, police
said. Such protests are banned during the week of the anniversary.
   Hess hanged himself at the age of 93 in Berlin's Spandau Prison
on Aug. 17, 1987.
   Police had encircled the cemetery to keep away the 500 to 1,000
right-wing extremists they had expected. The former deputy fuhrer's
son and daughter-in-law, Wolf-Ruediger and Andrea Hess, were
allowed to visit the grave.
   ``Everything was quiet at the cemetery,'' said Wunsiedel police
spokesman Roland Weber. ``It's all closed off.''
   Weber said the 15 protesters were apprehended for violating the
protest ban, which extends from midnight Tuesday to midnight
Sunday. They were wearing bomber jackets and ``carrying two banners
with swastika-like emblems'' as well as displaying other neo-Nazi
symbols, he said.
   Three West German ``Skinheads'' were also picked up but were set
free because ``they had nothing to do'' with the rally, Weber said.
   Within days of Hess' death last year, police in Wunsiedel
arrested more than 100 right-wing extremists and neo-Nazis who
converged on the town. Many were wearing neo-Nazi emblems and
shouting neo-Nazi slogans.
   Hess, who was deputy to Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler, was the sole
prisoner in Spandau, which was administered by France, Britain, the
United States and the Soviet Union, the Allies of World War II.
</TEXT>
