<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan     08-17 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan ``Deeply Saddened'' By Pakistan Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pakistan Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said he was
``deeply saddened'' Wednesday by the deaths in a plane crash of
Pakistani President Zia ul-Haq and two high-ranking Americans, but
his aides said the White House had no information on what caused
the C-130 aircraft to go down near Lahore.
   ``In these seven and a half years, I met with President Zia
several times and we worked together for peace and stability,''
Reagan said in a statement issued as he began a thre-week
California vacation at his ranch north of here.
   ``The United States was fortunate to have such a friend in
President Zia but our support for Pakistan is not dependent upon
any individual,'' the president said. ``We will give our full
support to acting President Ghulam Ishan Khan.''
   ``I am deeply saddened to learn of the deaths of President Zia
... and the American ambassador to Pakistan, Arnold Raphel, and
others in the crash of President Zia's C-130,'' the president said.
   ``Ambassador Raphel was a distinguished officer of the Foreign
Service. He worked tirelesslsy to build and preserve the ties
between our two countries.''
   The president's statement was written before it was reported at
the Pentagaon that the crash apparently also took the life of Brig.
Gen. Herbert M. Wassom, the chief U.S. defense representative in
Pakistan.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president's
national security adviser, Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell, was informed
of the crash by U.S. military authorities early Wednesday and
telephoned Reagan at the ranch at 7:47 a.m. (PDT).
   Fitzwater said Powell then telephoned Vice President George Bush
and White House Chief of Staff Kenneth M. Duberstein in New
Orleans, where they are attending the Republican National
Convention. ``We don't have any information on the cause of the
crash at this point,'' the presidential spokesman said. ``We can't
make any judgments along those lines.''
   He said it was too early to say whether any U.S. representative
would be sent to Pakistan, as funeral arrangements had not yet been
announced.
   Fitzwater also anounced that Reagan telephoned Indiana Sen. Dan
Quayle from the ranch Tuesday night``to congratulate and wish him
well on the upcoming campaign.'' Bush chose Quayle Tuesday as his
running mate in his quest for the presidency.
   The spokesman said the president and First Lady Nancy Reagan
watched Wednesday night's proceedings at the Republican National
Convention on the one television set in their ranch house.
   The weather at the ranch was sunny, and Fitzwater said the
president was spending the day riding horseback, clearing brush,
chopping wood and attending to routine paper work.
   The American Indian Action Group of Goleta, near Santa Barbara,
announced that more than 200 American Indians will gather outside
the ranch Saturday to protest remarks Reagan made about Indian
people during the U.S.-Soviet summit in Moscow in May. Reagan said
the United States might have made a mistake by not urging Indians
to ``be citizens along with the rest of us.''
   Reagan will go to Los Angeles Tuesday, making a stop in Irvine,
Calif., for a fund-raiser for Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
   Fitzwater said a joint appearance with Bush might be added to
the president's schedule in Los Angeles on Wednesday.
   On Aug. 27, the president will appear at a fund-raiser for the
California Republican Party in Thousand Oaks and one for his
congressman, Rep. Robert Lagomarsino, in Santa Barbara, before
returning to the ranch.
</TEXT>
