<HEAD>Conservative Groups Say They're Happy With Quayle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative spokesmen on Wednesday blessed
the political union of George Bush and Dan Quayle and said their
sometimes divergent groups are united behind the 1988 Republican
presidential ticket.
   Paul Weyrich of the Free Congress Foundation said he thought the
selection of Quayle, a conservative senator from Indiana, as Bush's
vice presidential running mate would boost the ticket's prospects
for winning.
   ``I think the odds have gone from about 70-30 against George
Bush's election to about 50-50,'' Weyrich said at a news conference
attended by other conservative spokesmen.
   Weyrich said he was not swayed to support the Republican ticket
until after the adoption of the party's platform and Bush's
decision to choose Quayle.
   ``When I came here, I was not sure I was going to leave with
wholehearted support for the ticket,'' he said.
   Quayle's conservative credentials could compensate for some
voters' ``initial prejudice'' against him because of his wealth,
Weyrich said.
   Former Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont, who ran for the 1988 GOP
presidential nomination and lost, said he was ``delighted'' at
Quayle being added to the ticket.
   ``All of us are here to celebrate a conservative ticket ... that
espouses the principles that Ronald Reagan brought to our party in
1980,'' du Pont said.
   Others attending the news conference included Don Devine of
Citizens for Free America and Dr. Robert Grant of Christian Voice.
