<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HijackingSuspect     08-17 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijacking Suspect,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijacking Witness Questioned Behind Closed Doors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Middle Eastern man jailed last week as a
material witness against a suspected terrorist charged in a 1985
airline hijacking was questioned about the case Wednesday in a
sealed courtoom.
   Mouin Abdul Ajam, who was ordered released from custody on
Monday by U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker, was questioned by
prosecutors and a defense lawyer for Fawaz Younis, the defendant
charged with leading the hijacking of the Jordanian airliner,
according to sources familiar with the case.
   Ajam, who was arrested last week in Sacramento, Calif. and
brought here as a material witness against Younis, was questioned
about his identification of the defendant at a court-ordered lineup
earlier this year.
   Younis, who was arrested last September after he was lured to an
FBI-chartered yacht off Cyprus, is awaiting trial on charges he led
the June 11, 1985 hijacking of a Royal Jordanian airliner from
Beirut.
   Ajam, who was a passenger on the airplane, gave a deposition
that was videotaped by prosecutors so it could be replayed at
Younis' trial, according to the sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Younis was allowed to attend the questioning session, which was
held in a closed courtroom in U.S. District Court.
   At a hearing last month, Assistant U.S. Attorney Ramsey Johnson
said investigators were searching for a passenger on the plane who
had identified Younis at the earlier lineup.
   Ajam was brought to Washington by U.S. marshals and kept at the
District of Columbia Jail over the weekend until Parker ordered his
release, on condition he give the deposition, the sources said.
   The airliner was hijacked by five armed men who forced the
pilots to fly the aircraft to several locations in the
Mediterranean. The next day, after the 74 passengers and crew were
released, the hijackers blew up the plane.
   No date has been set for the trial of Younis, a former member of
Lebanon's Shiite Amal militia.
   Ajam was said by a lawyer who represented him at a court
proceeding in Sacramento last week to be ``extremely concerned''
that terrorist groups would kill his family members still in
Lebanon if he testified against Younis.
   ``He has every reason to fear retaliation agianst his family in
Beirut,'' said the lawyer, Jessica McGuire.
</TEXT>
