<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Jordan,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egypt Supports PLO, Palestinian Provisional Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt said Wednesday it would put all its
resources behind the Palestine Liberation Organization, and
President Hosni Mubarak said the PLO should establish a provisional
Palestinian government.
   After a meeting between Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid and
a high-level PLO delegation, the two sides said they agreed on the
PLO's options and would have further consulations.
   ``President Mubarak has reaffirmed that the Palestinian cause
has Egypt's complete support, and that it is at the forefront of
Egyptian interests,'' Abdel-Meguid said after a 90-minute meeting,
the last after three days of talks with the PLO delegation.
   The group included Mahmoud Abbas and Abdullah Horani, members of
the PLO's executive committee, and Hani al-Hassan, a political
adviser to PLO leader Yasser Arafat. They met with Mubarak on
Tuesday and planned to leave Thursday.
   Egyptian television quoted Abbas as saying that Mubarak agreed
Tuesday that the PLO should establish a provisional Palestinian
government in the Israeli-occupied territories that would draw up
an ``internationally acceptable'' political program.
   PLO officials have said a provisional government would be ready
to recognize Israel in exchange for its recognition of a
Palestinian state in the occupied territories.
   Asked when an announcement of a Palestinian government could be
made, Abbas said any plan would first have to be presented to the
Palestine National Council.
   The council, combining representatives from all PLO factions, is
the legislative arm that makes all major policy decisions. It is
expected to meet in Algeria next month.
   Abdel-Meguid said Egypt would continue consultations with the
PLO and stressed that coordination among Egypt, Jordan and
Palestinian was still necessary.
   Asked about what Egypt thought of a Palestinian
government-in-exile, Abdel-Meguid said, ``Egypt will support what
the Palestinians decide upon.''
   Horani agreed and said the talks with the foreign minister were
``on the basis of our meeting with President Mubarak and his
directives to put Egypt's resources at the disposal of the PLO.''
   The Palestinian delegation arrived Monday from Amman, capital of
Jordan, where they discussed with King Hussein his decision to hand
to the PLO full responsibility for the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip
from Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   The PLO reportedly is debating whether to declare a state in the
occupied lands, home to about 1.5 million Palestinians. It is also
considering whether to establish a provisional government or a
government-in-exile.
   Abbas, who is also known as Abu-Mazen, said the political
program would ``explain to the world the rational and logical PLO
objectives so as to corner the enemies of our people's independence
and self-determination.''
   He apparently referred to Israel, whose Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir opposes Palestinian self-determination that might lead to
the creation of an independent Palestinian state.
</TEXT>
