<1ST_LINE>r w AM-March     08-17 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-March,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>25th Anniversary March Aimed At Reviving King's `Dream'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of a march to commemorate the
largest civil rights demonstration in U.S. history said Wednesday
they aimed to revive the vision set forth in Martin Luther King
Jr.'s ``I have a dream'' speech 25 years ago.
   ``We are concerned ... about the state of `the dream,''' said
Joseph E. Lowery, president of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference and a chief planner of the commemorative march.
   ``While the dream has been realized in some respects,'' he told
a news conference, ``in other aspects it has been deferred, it is
in a holding pattern.''
   Other organizers said they expected about 100,000 people to
attend the march Aug. 27.
   The highlight of the 1963 ``March on Washington'' by more than
200,000 people was the spellbinding speech by King, who stood on
the steps of the Lincoln Memorial and declared, ``I have a dream
... ''
   ``... That one day this nation will rise and live out the true
meaning of its creed: `We hold these truths to be self-evident,
that all men are created equal.' I have a dream.''
   King's widow, Coretta Scott King, is one of the main organizers
of the commemorative march, along with Benjamin Hooks, executive
director of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People, and other black leaders.
   Lowery said the two presidential nominees, Democrat Michael
Dukakis and Republican George Bush, had been invited to the march.
He said Dukakis' staff had indicated the Massachusetts governor
planned to attend but that no word had been received from the Bush
camp.
   Leaders of the march will call for legislation to relieve
poverty and joblessness, improve housing and human rights and
combat drugs and AIDS, the acquired immune deficiency syndrome,
Lowery said. They also will urge a moratorium on testing of nuclear
weapons and stiffer sanctions against South Africa.
</TEXT>
