<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Facility,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Home Opens for Unruly Teens With AIDS Virus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials Wednesday opened a group
home for unruly teen-agers carrying the AIDS virus.
   The first resident will be a 15-year-old Pensacola boy, who once
was locked in a mental ward by the state to keep him from spreading
the deadly virus.
   The closely supervised but unlocked cottage will house up to six
13- to 17-year-olds who carry the virus that can cause acquired
immune deficiency syndrome, but do not exhibit full-blown symptoms
of the disease.
   The residents will be foster children whose behavior is hard to
control. Many have a history of prostutition or drug use.
   The Pensacola youth was involved in a child pornography ring and
prostitution and continued to have sex after he had been diagnosed
as carrying the virus.
   He first was quarantined, then placed in a locked ward and later
placed in a shelter for juvenile delinquents. He ran away a few
times and has been held at a juvenile detention center in Pensacola.
   About 40 youngsters are eligible for the home, located at a
former institution, said officials of the state Department of
Health and Rehabilitative Services, who will supervise the facility.
   Those who are admitted will stay six months to two years.
</TEXT>
