<DOCNO> AP880817-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CorporalPunishment     08-17 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corporal Punishment,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conference: `Time is Now' to End Corporal Punishment in Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents, educators, lawyers and doctors
marshalled forces Wednesday against corporal punishment in schools.
   ``We've reached the point of critical mass,'' said Robert
Fathman, chairman of a coalition of 23 medical, legal and
educational organizations, holding the first conference of its kind
in more than a decade.
   Describing corporal punishment as ``a barbaric carryover from
the days of Charles Dickens,'' Fathman said: ``It's no longer a
question of whether we'll be able to abolish the practice, but
when.''
   Eleven states and a number of school districts, ranging in size
from Chicago's to that of Seaford, Del., have outlawed corporal
punishment in schools since New Jersey became the first to do so in
1867.
   Explaining the conference theme, ``The Time is Now,'' Fathman
noted five states have passed measures banning the practice since
1984, six legislatures have bills pending and six states will face
the issue during their 1989 sessions.
   Keynote speaker Bob Keeshan, known to millions of children as
TV's ``Captain Kangaroo,'' called corporal punishment ``a failed
practice. It rates an `F' because it does not meet its stated
purpose of maintaining discipline because it treats the symptoms
and not the cause of the underlying unruly behavior.
   ``With that behavior a child is crying out, `Help me, help me.'
And we answer with the compassion of the paddle,'' said Keeshan.
   ``Seventy years ago, the Soviet Union outlawed the practice ...
and it is the same now in virtually every country in the civilized
world,'' he said. ``Are we so backward that we haven't learned what
all these countries already know?''
   The purpose of the three-day conference that opened Wednesday,
Fathman said, is to provide organizational skills and information
to parents, educators and other interested parties so they can
effectively campaign at local and state levels to eliminate the
practice in schools.
   ``Signs of progress are everywhere,'' said Fathman, head of the
National Coalition to Abolish Corporal Punishment in Schools.
   ``The Little Rock school district has banned corporal
punishment, and that in Arkansas, the worst state ... where 14
percent of the students are paddled each year.''
   According to the U.S. Department of Education, more than a
million incidents of corporal punishment are reported in public
schools each year, ranging from paddling to confining students in
small spaces such as closets.
   Fathman said black children, who represent 16 percent of the
school-age population, make up 32 percent of those punished, and
that children ``in the Deep South are 4,000 times more likely to be
paddled than their counterparts in the Northeast,'' where
Connecticut is the only state without a law barring the practice.
   In a joint statement preceeding the opening of the conference,
the American Medical Association, the American Bar Association, the
American Academy of Pediatrics, and the American Psychological
Association denounced corporal punishment and called for
legislators to ban it.
   Conference participants said they expected their efforts would
continue to be met with stiff resistance.
   ``A study several years back found that 90 percent of parents
use corporal punishment in their own homes,'' said Adrienne Haeuser
of the National Association of Social Workers. ``That tells us
we've got a lot of educating to do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0195 </DOCNO>
