<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmExports     08-17 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Exports,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funds Provided For 46 Export-Aid Projects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Wednesday it
is giving $110 million to 46 projects under the Targeted Export
Assistance program for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
   Under TEA, as the program is called, various trade organizations
get funds to promote certain agricultural products overseas. The
program is aimed at countering or offsetting what the government
considers unfair foreign trade practices on U.S. exports.
   In most cases, the sponsoring organizations put up some of their
own money in carrying out a specific project, although the amount
of those contributions vary and are subject to negotiation with the
department.
   The $110 million for 1989 is the same as for this year, a level
set by Congress in the 1985 farm law.
   Officials said the biggest amount, $8.9 million, will go to the
U.S. Meat Export Federation to promote red meat, variety meats and
related products. Other leading recipients included: American
Soybean Association, $8.8 million; Cotton Council International,
$7.9 million; and the California Raisin Advisory Board, $7.7
million.
</TEXT>
