<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     08-17 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czech Activists Urge Soviets To Admit Responsibility For 1968</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release 6 p.m. EDT _ Time Set By Source</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A human rights group urged Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to tell the truth about the 1968
invasion of Prague and name the Czech leaders who allegedly invited
the troops into their country.
   ``We call on the Soviet leadership ... to provide an open space
for the factual assessment of the events of 1968 and to reach the
appropriate conclusions,'' Charter 77 said in a statement,
according to Palach Press, an emigre publishing house in London.
   The Charter 77 group said the military crackdown by troops and
tanks from five Warsaw Pact nations on Aug. 20-21, 1968 _ the
largest military operation in Europe since World War II _ had ``a
direct influence on the way we live now.''
   ``The Soviet Union should admit its shared responsibility for
the recent Czechoslovak predicament. It should do so not only in
the interests of Czechoslovakia, but also for the sake of the
credibility of its new policies,'' Charter 77 said.
   The invasion crushed a movement of economic and political
reforms espoused by Alexander Dubcek, the Communist Party leader
during the Prague Spring of 1968. Since then, Czechs seemingly have
been reluctant to renew their support for such reforms.
   Charter 77 also demanded in its statement that the names of
Czech leaders who allegedly invited the troops into their country
be made public.
   The Soviet Union, Bulgaria, Hungary, Poland and East Germany
published a statement in 1968 saying their troops were invited into
Czechoslovakia by leaders who were never publicly identified.
   Gustav Husak, a supporter of the 1968 reforms, took over the
Communist party leadership from Dubcek in 1969. Milos Jakes, a 1968
official who later oversaw a purge of half a million alleged
supporters of Dubcek, succeeded Husak in December 1987.
   Politburo member Vasil Bilak, head of the Communist Party in
1968, lost his post and was denounced as a Soviet collaborator
after the invasion. He regained a powerful position in November
1968 and still wields great influence.
   ``Gorbachev is subjecting the preceding era to extensive
criticism,'' the activists said, and making Czech leaders installed
under Leonid I. Brezhnev ``more and more isolated'' abroad and at
home.
   The group urged Czechoslovakia's 15.5 million citizens ``to
shake off the burden of fear'' and speak openly about the events of
1968.
   ``The government is succumbing to panic,'' the statement said.
``Since the government derives all its legitimacy from the
authority of Brezhnev's tanks, it rejects almost in desperation any
truthful account of what happened twenty years ago.''
   ``(The invasion) became de facto an overture to the later war in
Afghanistan, to the suppression of Solidarity in Poland and to the
policy of intimidation in general,'' the statement said.
   Three Charter 77 spokesmen signed the 1,000-word statement and
planned to deliver it to the Soviet Embassy in Prague on Saturday,
if they are not detained by then. Several leading dissidents have
received police warnings to leave Prague during the anniversary
weekend.
   Among Charter 77's Prague-based spokesmen are prominent
activists Milos Hajek and Bohumir Janat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Quayle-BabyBoom     08-17 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle-Baby Boom,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Quayle Question: Baby Boom or Bust?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's strategists portray the selection
of Sen. Dan Quayle as his running mate as a bold bid for the
nation's younger generation, but analysts warned Wednesday that as
a voting bloc, the baby boom could prove a bust.
   The problem is that the nation's roughly 75 million baby boomers
make up too large a segment of the population to fit into one
ideological category, experts said. Generational links do not
necessarily mean shared politics.
   ``They have different life experiences and certainly different
values'' from their elders, said Democratic pollster Peter Hart.
``But they're such large share of the American population, they
cross all income, occupational and ideological lines.''
   Bush and his aides touted the 41-year-old Quayle as the first
member of the baby boom generation _ usually defined as Americans
born after World War II and before 1965 _ to run on a major-party
ticket for national office.
   ``Do I need help in this area? Sure,'' said Bush. ``And have I
gotten it by the selection of a young, experienced United States
senator? I think so.'' Campaign chief James Baker called it ``a
bold stroke across generations.''
   But some cautioned that the stroke may prove too broad. ``In
general, the baby boomers have not voted as a bloc,'' said
Republican pollster Neil Newhouse. Moreover, ``Young people have
never reliably voted,'' he said.
   Quayle may be able to improve turnout among the one-third of
baby boomers who already identify with the Republican Party,
Newhouse said. But he and others said the next step, drawing new
adherents, may prove more difficult.
   ``Will it encourage younger Democrats, younger independents, to
cross party lines for a candidate of their generation? Who ...
knows,'' he said. ``But there's a shot at that happening.''
   Public policy researcher Edward H. Crane, president of the Cato
Institute in Washington, said he doubted it. While baby boomers are
a diverse group, he said, they share some attributes that do not
dovetail with Quayle's.
   As a proponent of deregulation, entrepreneurship and low taxes,
``Quayle fits on the economic stuff pretty well,'' Crane said. But
he said Quayle's foreign policy views are more hawkish and his
social views more conservative than those of many baby-boomers.
   ``He doesn't have that combination of views that I would argue
is unique to baby boomers,'' said Crane, whose group, which is
nonpartisan, has been a leader in analyzing the baby-boom
generation. ``So he won't be able to appeal to a large group of
them.''
   Republican pollster Linda DiVall said Quayle could have an
impact, so long as it was not overstated.
   ``I don't think anyone is saying that Dan Quayle single-handedly
is going to deliver the baby boom generation,'' she said on the
``CBS This Morning'' television program. ``But I think it's first
time that either of the major parties has made an absolute gesture
of basically passing the torch a couple of generations and saying,
`This is the future leader of our party, this is the way we're
going to go.'''
   There are openings for Quayle. Hart, who studied the baby boom
generation for Rolling Stone magazine, said that younger adults
could find it easier to relate to him ``at least in terms of
appearance and metaphor.'' And Newhouse noted that baby boomers are
less strongly committed to either political party than are older
Americans.
   ``It goes beyond whether you are liberal or moderate or
conservative to what kind of concerns you have,'' Newhouse said.
``If he can demonstrate shared concerns over the things the baby
boom generation is concerned about'' _ such as day care and
education _ ``then he can have a tremendous impact.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0199 </DOCNO>
