<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Crash-General 2ndLd-Writethru a0728 08-17 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-General, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0728,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan Crash Took Life Of US Army General</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Leads to give Pentagon confirmation.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Pakistan-Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The airplane crash in Pakistan that killed the
country's president and the U.S. ambassador also took the life of
an American Army general, the Pentagon said today.
   ``The Defense Department has been informed that Brig. Gen.
Herbert M. Wassom was aboard the plane,'' said Lt. Col. Keith
Schneider, a Pentagon spokesman.
   Wassom, 49, was the chief U.S. defense representative to
Pakistan and would have been traveling routinely with U.S.
Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel.
   Schneider said the Pentagon did not know of any other Americans
on the plane besides Raphel and Wassom.
   The Pakistani official radio confirmed today that Raphel and
President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq were killed when their Pakistani
military plane exploded in the eastern part of the country.
   The Pakistan air force C-130 transport plane with 37 people
aboard had just taken off from Bahawalpur, 330 miles southwest of
Islamabad, when it exploded about 4:30 p.m. (7:30 a.m. EDT), the
report said. A government statement read over the radio said no one
aboard the plane survived.
   Wassom was named the senior American defense representative to
Pakistan in July 1987. An Army general who won his star in
September 1985, Wassom held a bachelor's degree in industrial arts
from Western Kentucky University and a master's degree in
international relations from George Washington University.
   A native of Rockwood, Tenn., Wassom was trained as an artillery
and missile officer and served in Vietnam. He rose through a
variety of command positions with the 101st Airborne Division in
the 1970's before becoming the head of the 528th Army Artillery
Group in the U.S. Army Southern European Task Force in 1980.
   In 1981, Wassom became the deputy director of the staff for the
Army's chief of staff in Washington, then in 1983 became the chief
of staff for the 101st at Fort Campbell, Ky., He later served as
the assistant division commander for the 101st before assuming the
post in Pakistan.
   Wassom had earned numerous decorations, including the Legion of
Merit with Oak Leaf Cluster; the Bronze Star, and the Defense
Meritorious Service Medal.
   ``He was a very capable guy who was extremely well liked,'' said
one Pentagon official.
   Defense sources also disclosed today the United States had
already extended to Pakistan an offer to assist in any way possible
the investigation of the accident.
   ``There are no indications yet of any external cause for this
crash,'' said one official.
   ``But we have offered assistance ranging from forensic work to
sending over folks from the Federal Aviation Administration and the
Federal Bureau of Investigation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
