<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     08-17 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Agrees on Border Talks With South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korean and South Korean
delegates will meet Friday to prepare for a joint parliamentary
session on a non-aggression pact and the communist nation's demand
to be a co-host the Olympics.
   South Korea's National Assembly said North Korea's Supreme
People's Assembly agreed Wednesday by telephone to send five
delegates to the truce village of Panmunjom.
   The meeting will be the first between the two nations in three
years.
   The last time was in December 1985 at Red Cross talks. But the
North shelved all dialogue in early 1986 to protest regular
military exercises between South Korea and the United States.
   The latest flurry of overtures began July 21, when North Korea
proposed a joint session of the two parliaments to draft a
non-aggression pact. That was followed by another proposal that
Olympics issues be added to the meeting.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Sept. 17-Oct. 2
Olympics unless it is allowed to be a co-host. South Korea and
international Olympics officials rejected the demand, but have
offered several compromise proposals.
   North Korea originally proposed this week's meeting be held
Wednesday, but South Korea suggested the switch to Friday to avoid
dampening celebrations marking a 30-day countdown to the Olympics.
   South Korea's opposition parties welcomed North Korea's
agreement.
   ``We hope the South-North parliamentary talks would provide an
opportunity for realizing national unification,'' said a message
from the main opposition Party for Peace and Democracy.
   In Wednesday's telephone message, North Korea did not mention
its earlier demand for full-fledged parliamentary talks, according
to sources in the South Korean assembly. The two sides have been in
disagreement over Pyongyang's demand to include all representatives
in the main legislative conference.
   North Korea also says Friday's meeting should discuss only
logistical arrangements for larger talks. South Korea wants to take
up procedural matters, including the agenda and the number of
participants for the full negotiations.
   The conflicting stands cast doubt on the prospects of main
parliamentary talks between the two Koreas, left divided in 1945 at
the end of World War II.
   South Korean government officials have expressed doubts over the
North Korean proposal. Some officials interpreted it as an attempt
to stir unrest before the Olympics or to find an excuse to skip the
Games.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0205 </DOCNO>
