<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen     08-17 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Hustles Native Texas for Conservative Votes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen zigzagged across Texas looking for conservative votes
Wednesday, and he flexed his muscles at the prospect of his matchup
with Sen. Dan Quayle on the Republican ticket.
   Back in Washington, Bentsen's office released financial
statements showing his grossincome averaged $772,181 annually over
the past five years, including more than $1 million in 1983.
   Medical records made public at the same time showed Bentsen was
in generally good health.
   Bentsen flew west from Fort Worth to meet with farmers and
ranchers at a wool warehouse in San Angelo and speak at a historic
Western fort. He then viewed a medicine-by-television project in
Lubbock and planned to return to East Texas at day's end.
   ``I know that this county is principally Republican,'' Bentsen
told the 250 people at Fort Concho in San Angelo. ``I also know
that Lloyd Bentsen carried this county by 58 percent last time.''
   He turned to the more difficult task of selling Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis to his fellow Texans. Bentsen
said his selection as the Massachusetts governor's running mate
showed that Dukakis was ``reaching out... ready to listen to
differing viewpoints.''
   Bentsen also implied that George Bush, who was born in New
England but claims Houston as his home, was not a real Texan.
   ``There is only one on the ticket who was born and reared on a
farm in Texas,'' he told the crowd.
   Bentsen was accompanied during the day by Rep. Charles Stenholm
of Texas, a leader of the band of conservative Democrats in
Congress who supported President Reagan in his first term.
   Stenholm told the San Angelo meeting that Bentsen was the only
person on either ticket with ``tractor-seat common sense.'' The
congressman didn't even mention the liberal Dukakis' name.
   At Texas Tech, Bentsen took part in a demonstration of a two-way
television hookup that enables doctors at the medical center to
help diagnose and treat patients in rural areas where medical care
is scarce.
   Bentsen said he helped win financing for the project in
Congress. He decried the loss of 23 rural hospitals in Texas in the
past year, a trend he said he was trying to stop as chairman of the
Senate Finance Committee by changing the rules governing federal
hospital assistance.
   Bentsen seemed to relish the prospect of debating Quayle, tapped
as Bush's vice presidential running mate, on Oct. 11 in Omaha,
Neb., if Quayle accepts the challenge.
   ``I guess we'll have an early season on quail,'' he told
reporters.
   Bentsen, 67, dismissed questions about the ``youth factor''
represented by the 41-year-old Quayle. Bentsen said he had worked
out with weights on a treadmill in his hotel room Wednesday
morning, and had increased his usual four-pound barbells to five
pounds.
   ``It's not the miles on you, it's the depth of the tread,'' he
said, implying that he considers Quayle a political lightweight.
   Bentsen's office released medical records which showed the
senator was in generally good health although he was treated for
high cholesterol and two small skin lesions.
   Reporters joked with Bentsen's wife, B.A., that the doctors
would report he'd have ``the body of a 41-year-old.''
   ``You bet,'' she replied. ``No question about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
