<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Grenade     08-17 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Grenade,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drunken Soldier Sets off Grenade, 13 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drunken soldier on leave
accidentally exploded a hand grenade at a rural funeral, killing
himself and 12 civilians and wounding 20 others, authorities said
Wednesday.
   The grenade went off Tuesday night in a home full of mourners on
the outskirts of Santiago de Maria, about 70 miles east of the
capital, said Defense Ministry spokesman Col. Jose Galileo Torres.
   Speaking by telephone, Torres identified the soldier as Hector
Tulio Garcia Mendoza. He said the soldier was on leave and drunk at
the time.
   Torres said the army tries to prevent soldiers from taking
weapons when they go on leave, ``but they always manage to take
them out for their own protection when they visit their hometowns,
where the guerrillas know them.''
   Many soldiers on home leave have been killed by rebels, Torres
said.
   The U.S.-backed government has been fighting a war against
leftist guerrillas for nine years, with an estimated 65,000 people
killed, mostly civilians.
   A police source in Santiago de Maria said by telephone that the
grenade went off Tuesday night in a home where a child's wake was
being held. The child died earlier in the day of natural causes.
   Authorities gave no details on why the soldier pulled the pin
from the grenade.
   The soldier belonged to the army's 6th Infantry Brigade, the
source said, speaking on condition of anonymity. The unit is
deployed in that area of Usulutan province because of frequent
activity by leftist guerrillas.
   The explosion killed the soldier and 10 civilians almost
instantly, the source said. He said two more civilians died soon
after, and 20 people were wounded.
</TEXT>
