<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Anarchists 1stLd-Writethru a0729 08-17 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Anarchists, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Band Of Young People Bring Their Brand Of Anarchy To Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 13th graf, bgng ``Most of xxx, to delete extraneous
words</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They say they eat food from garbage cans, get
their clothes in thrift stores, and wander the country, taking
their politics seriously.
   They might be called modern-day hobos, but they call themselves
anarchists and at the Republican National Convention, which has
drawn few protesters, this band stands out.
   ``We don't think our lifestyle is appropriate for everyone,''
says Mark Kynik of New Orleans. ``But we do think people should
take control of their communities and resources _ the land, the
oil, banks _ and use it for the good of all, not just a few.
   ``That's what anarchy is about,'' he said.
   Anarchists see nothing good in American politics. They also
protested last month in Atlanta at the Democratic National
Convention. About 30 are in town for the GOP convention.
   The group, most in their early 20s, say there are many more like
them across the nation. Many met during the Great Peace March of
1986 and have been protesting ever since.
   Their appearance in New Orleans has made little impact. It is
likely that only a few, if any, delegates noticed.
   The group staged one demonstration at a city park this week,
watched by a few policemen and a reporter or two. It was
``guerrilla theater,'' with the members banging pots with sticks.
Then they destroyed a television set to ``smash illusions'' created
by the media.
   At another demonstration, about 20 of them marched in the middle
of rush-hour traffic toward the Superdome, where the GOP convention
was being held.
   Karen Eliot, 21, who described herself as an Army brat
originally from North Carolina, said she became an anarchist after
she dropped out of college to self-educate herself.
   ``This lifestyle is so much healthier to me. There is no one
telling you what to do,'' she said as she took a break between
protests and rolled a cigarette.
   In New Orleans, many of them say they are staying at a house
with Steve Vermont, 22, sleeping on floors with blankets.
   ``Most of us know each other through anarchist networks,'' says
Vermont. ``In the winter a lot of us settle in one place, maybe
work as a janitor or dishwasher, and save half the money. Then in
the summer we travel.''
   They also sell their blood to blood banks and panhandle, and
``Dumpster Dive,'' gathering day-old bread and vegetables from
trash bins behind restaurants and supermarkets. The trash cans also
are good source for clothes (they favor T-shirts, jeans and
military-style boots).
   The anarchists do not seem miffed that few people appear to be
heeding their message.
   ``We work pretty quietly,'' Vermont said. ``We don't have a
party line or a rap. We're asking people to think for themselves.
You can't get that message across in five seconds on TV.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0210 </DOCNO>
