<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Unisys-ArmyContract     08-17 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unisys-Army Contract,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unisys Says It Will Plead Guilty In Army Contract Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Unisys Corp. has told the Securities and
Exchange Commission that the defense contractor plans to plead
guilty in federal court to three counts of labor mischarging on an
Army contract in Arizona, a company spokesman said Wednesday.
   The company's plans were outlined in a filing required by the
SEC to outline any company actions that might affect stockholders,
according to Bill Beckham, a Unisys spokesman.
   The $9.2 million contract involves administrative and computer
work for the Army Information Systems Command at Ft. Huachuca,
Ariz. The case is not related to the ongoing Pentagon bribery
investigation, in which Unisys also has been mentioned, although no
charges have been filed.
   The Unisys-Army probe is being conducted by the U.S. attorney's
office in Tucson, Ariz., and is one of three federal
investigations, outside of the Pentagon case, made public in a July
19 letter from Michael Blumenthal, chairman of Unisys, to employees.
   Bluementhal's letter said the three other investigations were
under way before the November, 1986 merger between the Sperry Corp.
and Burroughs, which created Unisys. The Ft. Huachuca contract
involves a former Sperry office in Sierra Vista, Ariz.
</TEXT>
