<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Murders     08-17 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Murders,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Army Officers Accused in Killings By Death Squads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two army officers were charged Wednesday
with involvement in a political assassination by right-wing death
squads.
   The leftist Patriotic Union party has long claimed the army is
behind the death squads, which have killed 800 people in the last
three years. This is the first time any army officers have been
charged.
   The army captain and major were accused of plotting the
assassination of Alvaro Garces Parra, mayor of Sabana Torres and
one of more than 600 members of the Patriotic Union party killed by
the death squads.
   Garces was shot to death Aug. 16, 1987, in his northeast
Colombian town. The Colombia attorney general's office said Capt.
Luis Orlando Ardila Orjuela and Maj. Oscar Echandia Sanchez
supplied weapons to the killers.
   Echandia had one of the paid assassins admitted to a hospital as
a soldier after he was wounded in the attack, the attorney
general's office said.
   The assassin died in the hospital. Among his belongings was
found a safe conduct pass signed by Ardila, the attorney general's
office said.
   On the day of the murder, the two officers met with three men
believed to be members of a death squad known as the Crickets, the
attorney general's office said. Arrest orders also were issued for
the three men.
</TEXT>
