<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     08-17 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Criticizes Unchecked Inflation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raif Dizdarevic said
inflation is continuing at a runaway 190 percent this year, it was
reported Wednesday.
   Statistics officials took issue with Dizdarevic's figures,
saying the annual rate of inflation actually has decreased compared
with last year.
   In a speech at a Bosnian industrial town delivered Monday,
Dizdarevic said prices in the first seven months of this year had
been rising at a rate of about 190 percent, the official Tanjug
news agency reported.
   The government had hoped to keep the inflation rate down to 95
percent, he said. That is the figure demanded by the International
Monetary Fund for rescheduling of Yugoslavia's $21 billion debt.
   Statistics officials, however, said the 190 percent inflation
figure pertained to the entire period from July 1987 to July 1988.
   For the first eight months of this year alone, they expect
inflation to be only 90 percent. But then it is projected to rise
to 150 percent by the end of this year, the officials said.
   Even that would be down somewhat from the 170 percent inflation
rate reached in the 1987 calendar year.
   Dizdarevic also said in his speech that foreign exchange
reserves had increased significantly, with hard currency from
tourism and money sent home by Yugoslavs working abroad. The number
of such workers is growing ``much faster than expected,'' he said.
   Yugoslavia is undergoing economic reforms that include
liberalizing price and import regulations to orient the economy
toward the market. Dizdarevic said the federal body charged with
carrying out the reform is optimistic, Tanjug said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
