<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--ChoosingaVeep     08-17 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Choosing a Veep,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Campaign Releases Names of 12 Veep Also-Rans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush made extensive notes on potential
running mates on legal pads and reviewed them closely last weekend
before making his final choice of Sen. Dan Quayle, aides said
Wednesday.
   Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, also disclosed for the
first time the complete list of 12 also-rans.
   They included Sen. Bob Dole and his wife, former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole; New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu,
California Gov. George Deukmejian, South Carolina Gov. Carroll
Campbell, Gov. Jim Thompson of Illinois, Sens. John Danforth of
Missouri, Alan Simpson of Wyoming and Pete Domenici of New Mexico,
Rep. Jack Kemp, and Attorney General Richard Thornburgh.
   Bush called the 11 on Tuesday before talking with Quayle, Fuller
told a group of reporters.
   The 12th person on Bush's list, Sen. Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas,
was not called because she had removed herself from contention,
Fuller said.
   The list did not include some other prominent Republicans who
were thought to be under consideration, including Howard Baker, a
former senator and chief of staff to President Reagan, and former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander.
   Robert Teeter, Bush's pollster, said that his own past work with
Quayle gave him added insight into the Indiana lawmaker's
vote-drawing abilities.
   ``He is a first-rate campaigner,'' Teeter said. ``He can help
out among marginal Democrats and blue-collar workers.'' Teeter did
polling for Quayle in his congressional races in the late 1970s and
in his two Senate races in the 1980s.
   Quayle ``never had a gender gap problem'' in any of those races,
Teeter said. Teeter said he did not push Quayle in his
conversations with Bush, despite his long relationship with the
Indiana senator.
   Roger Ailes, Bush's media adviser, also helped Quayle in his
1980 and 1986 Senate races. ``I had a chance to observe him first
hand,'' Ailes said in a separate interview. He declined to say
whether he had advocated Quayle's selection to Bush.
   Campaign sources, in fact, said that Ailes believed Bush would
select Kemp.
   ``It doesn't make any difference what we wanted. What mattered
is what the vice president wanted,'' Teeter said.
   Teeter and Fuller described Bush's process in reaching his final
decision as complex _ beginning with surveying Republican senators
on whom they thought would be the best choice among themselves, and
doing the same with House members, governors and party leaders.
   But in the end, Bush kept his own counsel. He wrote the names
and information on each candidate ``on long legal pads''' and
studied them in Washington over the weekend to help make his final
decision, Fuller said.
   Said Teeter: ``The presumption that we sat down and made a list
of what we wanted demographically and tried to create a candidate
is just not true.''
   Quayle's age, 41, turned out to be a strong suit in Bush's mind,
said Teeter. And so did ``chemistry.''
   ``One of the most important things about a candidate for public
office is just to be interesting,'' he said, adding that Quayle
would be ``interesting to a large group of voters.''
   ``I think you've got a group of voters who now have a candidate
of their own generation ... that alone will make him an interesting
pick to a large number of voters.''
   ``Someone of that age symbolically will be popular,'' Teeter
continued.
   Questions on Quayle's association with former model Paula
Parkinson and the fact that he went into the National Guard in 1969
instead of joining another service that could have brought him into
combat in Vietnam were closely scrutinized, Fuller and Teeter said.
   Quayle _ as other candidates _ also was queried on whether he
had ever used illegal drugs, the aides said.
   His response was that he had not, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
