<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN-Bentsen-Quayle     08-17 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN-Bentsen-Quayle,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice Presidential Nominees Have Already Debated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Lloyd Bentsen and Dan Quayle face off in
their first vice presidential debate, it won't be the first time
the senators have debated on television.
   The senators went head-to-head four months ago on public
television's MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour. Their segment concerned a
trade bill eventually vetoed by President Reagan for its
controversial plant closing notification requirement.
   PBS has released the transcript of the April 22 show, billing it
as ``the only known televised debate between the two candidates.''
   Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee,
called the 60-day notification requirement ``a very mild proposal
that says if you've been working for a company 25, 30 years, you
deserve something better than a 7-day layoff'' if your plant is
going to close.
   ``When I was in business, and running a company, I closed down a
division,'' Bentsen added. ``I gave them 90 days' notice and it
worked out very well.''
   Rejoined Quayle, R-Ind., ``I think companies should give notice.
... The objection to it is the federal government coming in and
mandating on a legislative basis on how a company is going to close
its plant. ... Our judiciary is now going to get involved in
determining whether a plant is closed properly or not. It takes
away flexibility.''
   Bentsen called the plant-closing provision ``a peripheral
issue'' in a giant trade bill, ``magnified by the administration''
even after senators accomodated objections in other areas. He also
said most companies already give 60-day notices and those with
fewer than 100 employees would be exempted.
   But Quayle countered that the bill's financial penalties would
deter businesses with just over 100 employees from taking risks.
   And when Bentsen contended the trade bill was critical to stem
the nation's rising trade deficit, Quayle retorted, ``You would
think that perhaps the economy is going in the wrong direction.''
He then listed increases in exports, industrial growth, domestic
auto sales and jobs.
   Quayle and Reagan ultimately lost their battle.
   The Senate went on to pass the trade bill, Reagan vetoed it and
Bentsen devised the successful strategy of putting the
plant-closing provision into a separate measure. This time an
election-conscious Senate passed the provision overwhelmingly and
Reagan, tacitly acknowledging defeat, let it become law without his
signature.
</TEXT>
