<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hinckley     08-17 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hinckley,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hinckley Attorneys Seek To Block Release of Letters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense attorneys accused prosecutors
Wednesday of trying to ``inflame public passion'' against John W.
Hinckley Jr. by seeking to release letters written by the man who
shot President Reagan.
   The attorneys asked U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker to
deny the government's application to release the letters. The
application prompted a mental hospital holding Hinckley to withdraw
a proposal to take him on a field trip with other patients.
   Hinckley has been held at St. Elizabeths Hospital here since
1982, when he was acquitted by reason of insanity of shooting and
wounding President Reagan, White House press secretary James S.
Brady and two others on March 30, 1981.
   ``By disclosing the sealed documents now, the government hopes
to inflame the public passion against Mr. Hinckley,'' the defense
lawyers said in a court filing.
   ``Such publicity might prejudice his rights to fair and
impartial treatment of his illness in the future because of the
potential unwillingness of both Mr. Hinckley and the hospital staff
to deal with such a negative portrayal.
   ``More importantly it risks damaging the very treatment
relationship of confidence and trust that must exist for Mr.
Hinckley to make any progress in his fight against mental illness.''
   U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens last week asked Parker to release
the letters Hinckley wrote, saying they were of great public
interest.
   Defense attorneys Vincent Fuller and Judith Miller said Hinckley
had a property right to the letters, which they contended were
obtained only because government investigators had been given
copies of Hinckley's medical records to prepare for a hearing on
the hospital's proposal to include him in the field trip.
   ``The government did not obtain the materials at issue entirely
on its own,'' the lawyers said. ``Instead, it relied upon the
documents produced by the hospital in connection with the hearing''
about the field trip.
   ``Disclosure would be an abuse of governmental power and would
destroy Mr. Hinckley's right to privacy in his medical records as
well as in the materials themselves,'' the court filing said.
</TEXT>
