<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1745EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--ConventionRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0755 08-17 1069</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Convention Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0755,1050</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Poised to Claim Long-Awaited Nomination, Will Work Like a
`Pit Bull'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with new Quayle, Dukakis quotes; pick up 12th graf
pvs bgng ``Running mate...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>SANDY JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush moved toward uncontested
nomination at the Republican National Convention on Wednesday,
promising that he and newly minted running mate Dan Quayle would
work like a ``couple of pit bulls'' to whip the Democrats this fall.
   Bush confidently made the rounds of the convention city as his
hour of triumph approached. Campaign officials waited backstage for
their cue to release 50,000 balloons from the Superdome ceiling in
celebration.
   ``Bush-Quayle'' buttons sprouted on the lapels of delegates
while the vice president pronounced his 41-year-old political
partner one of the ``rising young stars'' of the GOP. But
qualified, he quickly added, to be ``one heartbeat away'' from the
presidency.
   At a joint, nationally televised news conference, Quayle sought
to fend off a barrage of questions about his youth and background
and struck an aggressive campaign pose. ``There is no compromise on
raising taxes,'' he said. ``...If the party of McGovern, Carter,
Mondale and Dukakis got back in power...I think it would be a
disaster.''
   ``I can't wait to get out there and tell the story about what
America would look like under a George Bush administration,'' he
said.
   Later, Quayle told Indiana Republicans elated over his
selection, ``Boy, do I look forward to going out there and
campaigning against Dukakis and Bentsen.''
   GOP officials said he would get his chance beginning Friday,
with an appearance back home in Indiana with Bush.
   Despite a dozen years in Congress, Quayle seemed like the new
kid on the Republican block _ but the day belonged to Bush.
   He spoke at a breakfast for farmers, met with delegates from
California and then made a brief visit to the Superdome podium
where he will stand to deliver his acceptance speech on Thursday
night. ``We'll do all right. I'll do OK,'' he said of the address
that will launch his come-from-behind quest for the White House.
   The presidential nomination was the main order of business at
the convention's evening session, and there was not the slightest
doubt that it belonged to Bush. He earned it in stunning fashion
during the Republican primary season when he routed the field with
a 14-state primary sweep on Super Tuesday in March.
   Campaign officials tapped Texas Sen. Phil Gramm to place their
man's name in nomination. Penn State football coach Joe Paterno led
a parade of seconding speakers.
   With losing 1984 nominee Walter F. Mondale at his side, Democrat
Michael Dukakis opened a four-day campaign swing in Minnesota with
a jibe at the celebrants in New Orleans. ``While they're partying
on Bourbon Street, we're talking to people on Main Street,''
Dukakis said. ``While they take a trip down Memory Lane, we're
looking to the future.''
   Running mate Lloyd Bentsen disclosed his income over the past
five years averaged $772,181 and he had paid $264,453 in taxes.
Quayle said he would be making a full financial disclosure, and
Bush challenged the Democratic ticketmates to make public their
last 10 income tax returns.
   Bush and Quayle stressed their agreement on fundamental issues
at a news conference. ``We're not going off in two different
directions on policy issues. We aren't going to have to debate each
other,'' Bush said in a jab at Dukakis and Bentsen.
   Behind in the polls, Bush said, ``We're going to tell the truth
and it's going to seem like they've engaged a couple of pit bulls.
... Competence is important but ideology is very important and
we're going to be talking on both.''
   The youthful Quayle said he had been tempered by a dozen years
in Congress, had experience as a young man in Indiana state
government and ``had met a payroll'' at his family's newspaper in
Indiana.
   He made a stab at humor, saying his wife had been asking him
about press reports that he had personal wealth in the millions.
   ``Why do you think I picked him?'' Bush joked.
   But Quayle also snapped at reporters who questioned him about
sensitive subjects.
   ``That has been covered and there's nothing to it,'' he said
when he was asked about Paula Parkinson, the key figure in a
sex-and-influence scandal in 1980.
   Asked why he went into the National Guard in 1969 rather than
joining a service that might have sent him to Vietnam, he said, ``I
have a deep affection for those young men and women who sacrificed
their lives in Vietnqam and for anybody to imply anything
differently is just simply wrong.''
   Bush bristled, as well, when asked about the criticism he's
received since introducing his Mexican-American grandchildren to
President Reagan on Tuesday as ``the little brown ones.''
   ``Those grandchildren are my pride and joy,'' he said. ``And I
find it personally offensive to suggest otherwise. And P.S. _ I
don't want to see those kids hurt. This is family and I'm going to
protect them.''
   One day after Bush hailed the Indiana senator as a man of the
future, campaign chairman James A. Baker III was stressing the
41-year-old lawmaker's experience. He ``has more defense and
foreign policy experience, if I may say so, than the Democratic
ticket combined,'' Baker said on NBC.
   Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad said Quayle would help in the uphill
race against the Democrats. ``He's a Midwesterner, he understands
agriculture, he is just 41 years old, he is a pro-life
conservative.''
   But California Gov. George Deukmejian said that while Quayle
wouldn't hurt Bush's chances, he wouldn't help him either in the
state with the largest number of electoral votes.
   Quayle's ascension left other Republicanms pondering their
future.
   Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, who contested Bush for the
presidential nomination and then campaigned to be his ticket mate,
confessed to disappointment. ``I'm not going to get emotional,'' he
said, clearing his throat, as he met with the New York delegation.
``But I was brought up by my parents to believe that all things
work together for the good.''
   Sen. Bob Dole offered his customary quip. ``I think he made an
outstanding choice in Dan Quayle,'' said the man who twice tried
but failed to gain his party's presidential nomination. ``I tried
to call him and he called me the other day. He was shaving. First
time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
