<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Sphinx     08-17 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Sphinx,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Trying to Keep Ailing Sphinx Together</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GIZA PLATEAU, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chunks of stone that fell from the
4,500-year-old Sphinx have been returned to their place, and the
statue will undergo emergency restoration at five other weak
points, an official said Wednesday.
   Besides weathering the ravages of desert sands and winds over
the centuries that caused the pieces to fall from the right
shoulder of the half-man, half-lion, the statue also has been
victim of a ``bad restoration project,'' which had further worsened
its condition, said Zahi Hawass, director general of the Pyramids
area.
   ``The Sphinx is like a suffering old man who needs an
operation,'' Hawass said of the world-reknowned statue, which lies
near the three famed Giza pyramids on Cairo's western outskirts.
   ``There are five weak points where stones can fall off any
minute,'' Hawass said. The worst problems, he added, stem from a
rising water table and a restoration project that ended just last
year.
   Hawass, who was appointed to his post in 1987, estimated the
repair cost at $10 million.
   Since the Sphinx was built of limestone around a large rock
about 2,500 B.C., it has alternated between being buried under the
sand or subjected to restoration projects that were begun by
ancient Egyptian pharoahs.
   About 3,000 years ago, Tuthmosis IV saw in a dream a suffering
Sphinx buried under the sand, which promised him rule of Egypt if
he cleaned up the area. Tuthmosis had the sand covering the statue
removed and soon afterward he became pharoah.
   Restoration work on the statue also was done during the
Greco-Roman era 16 centuries ago, and by enthusiastic foreign
Egyptologists in the early 20th century. Officials of the Egyptian
Antiquities Organization pitched in between 1982 and 1987.
   Close-up, the proud-looking statue is a patchwork of the results
of the various restoration operations. The Greco-Roman and early
20th century attempts involved giving the vulnerable parts of the
statue a second protective skin of limestone.
   The restoration that ended last year included giving the Sphinx
a 10-inch thick coat of limestones, using cement and gypsum to
stick them together.
   It is this last operation that Hawass and other Egyptologists
have attacked, saying the cement and gypsum did not allow the
limestone to breath. Another problem, they said, was a rising water
table that caused salts to weaken the limestone structure.
   ``It was a very bad restoration project,'' said Hawass. ``We
have to remove this layer, but when we tried that, we found that it
will hurt the original body of the Sphinx. So now we do not know
what to do.''
   He said that Egyptologists and scientists were trying to develop
a chemical mixture to serve as mortar to hold the stones together
while allowing them to breathe.
   Hawass stressed that no damaging cement or gypsum were used in
Tuesday's restoration. The stones will be held in place with a wall
of dovetailed pieces of limestone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1748EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     08-17 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army, Police On Alert On Eve Of Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli-linked Christian militia on
Wednesday threatened to organize a boycott of a parliamentary
session to choose a new president because it opposes a
Syrian-backed candidate, sources said.
   The election cannot proceed unless there is a quorum in
Parliament.
   An informed source said at least 25 Christian deputies have
pledged to boycott the session. A quorum of at least 53 members of
the 76-member Parliament must be present for a president to be
elected.
   Warring factions declared a cease-fire as hundreds of soldiers
tightened security around the Parliament building, police said.
   Southeast of Beirut, at least one person was killed during the
night and four were wounded in clashes between Druse and Christian
factions.
   Parliament is to convene in Beirut on Thursday to elect a head
of state to succeed President Amin Gemayel, who completes his
six-year term Sept. 23.
   Members of the Christian Lebanese Forces militia have threatened
to prevent the possible election of former President Suleiman
Franjieh by keeping some members of Parliament from attending the
voting session. Franjieh, a Christian, is backed by Syria.
   ``There will be no quorum ever as long as Franjieh remains a
candidate,'' said a high-level official of the Christian Lebanese
Forces, speaking on condition of anonymity. He pledged that the
militia would use ``all political options to prevent Franjieh's
election,'' but refused to elaborate.
   Police reported at least one death in a pre-dawn battle with
mortars and rockets between Christian and Druse militiamen along
the Kfarshima area southeast of Beirut.
   On Tuesday, five bombs exploded in Syrian-policed west Beirut.
No damage or casualties were reported, said a police spokesman, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The wave of violence erupted a few hours after Franjieh
announced he would run for president.
   A police spokesman said the Progressive Socialist Party of Druse
warlord Walid Jumblatt and the right-wing Christian Lebanese Forces
militia agreed to a cease-fire called by the various militias that
began 3:15 a.m. Wednesday.
   Security sources, who demanded anonymity, said the army and
police ``summoned all personnel to their barracks'' and Syrian
soldiers tightened security throughout Moslem west Beirut, frisking
pedestrians and motorists.
   About 800 Lebanese police officers in armored personnel carriers
were deployed Wednesday around the Parliament building to provide
security for the presidential election.
   The Christian Lebanese Forces on Tuesday declared their
opposition to the candidacy of Franjieh, 78, a personal friend of
Syrian President Hafez Assad.
   Franjieh was president from 1970 to 1976. The civil war, which
has claimed more than 130,000 lives and shattered Lebanon's
economy, broke out in 1975. Franjieh requested Syria's military
intervention in Lebanon in 1976, and there are now 40,000 Syrian
troops in the country.
   Lebanon's right-wing Christian leaders see Franjieh's effort to
seek a new term in office as an attempt by Syria to impose its
control over Lebanon.
   The English-language Syrian Times, based in Damascus, said the
presidential election was a chance to rebuild Lebanon and expel
Israel from the south of the country.
   In Israel, Uri Lubrani, coordinator of government policy on
Lebanon, said the election of a Syrian-controlled president would
plunge Lebanon into ``an ongoing state of turmoil.''
   Lebanon's Parliament was elected to a four-year term in 1972
with 99 members. Twenty-two deputies have died since then and
Gemayel's seat became vacant when he was elected president in 1982,
leaving only 76 surviving parliamentarians.
   The civil war has prevented elections and Parliament has been
extending its mandate since 1976.
</TEXT>
