<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BeatenJudges     08-17 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beaten Judges,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judges Beaten for Trying to Deliver Court Verdict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two judges and a colleague were attacked and
beaten last month while trying to deliver a court order, it was
reported Wednesday.
   One judge was kicked in the stomach and another judge and a
court secretary were beaten with a stick in the attack by workers
at the city bus company in Xiangfan, Hubei province, China's Legal
Daily said.
   The attack began after officials of the bus company refused to
accept a court document charging the company with selling old cars
as new. The report did not say whether it also set penalties
against the company.
   The bus company has a history of obstructing justice, but had
always gone unpunished, the paper said.
   Lu Tianbao, deputy manager of the bus company, threw down the
court document when it was handed to him, and kicked judge Ma
Tingyi in the stomach when Ma tried to give it to him a second
time, the report said.
   Ma, judge Ma Dongshen and court secretary Zhou Daxin were
attacked by a growing crowd, apparently from the bus company, as Ma
tried to tell them regulations on delivering a court order.
   The incident drew more than 1,000 onlookers and ended only with
the arrival of police.
   The daily, known for its exposes of legal injustices, said the
local government and Communist Party committee had begun an
investigation of the incident, but so far no action has been taken
against the assailants.
   In the past decade, China has tried to develop a body of law and
guarantee rights to a fair trial, but there are still frequent
reports of police abuse of power, and of lawyers and other court
officials being harassed during legal proceedings.
</TEXT>
