<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--At-A-Glance     08-17 0862</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--At-A-Glance,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Highlights at a Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of the
third day of the Republican National Convention:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>THE NOMINATION</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush moved toward uncontested nomination at the
Republican National Convention, promising that he and newly minted
running mate Dan Quayle would work like a ``couple of pit bulls''
to whip the Democrats this fall.
   Campaign officials waited backstage for their cue to release
50,000 balloons from the Superdome ceiling in celebration.
``Bush-Quayle'' buttons sprouted on the lapels of delegates while
the vice president pronounced his 41-year-old political partner one
of the ``rising young stars'' of the GOP. But qualified, he quickly
added, to be ``one heartbeat away'' from the presidency.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>BUSH</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush planned to stay in his hotel suite and watch on television
when the Republican National Convention formally delivered him the
party's nomination. He had no opposition. Aides said Barbara Bush
would be in the Superdome, watching the roll call with Indiana Sen.
Dan Quayle, Bush's choice for the vice presidential nomination.
   Bush, seeking to match the warm family images of the Democratic
convention, said he would show off three generations of Bushes when
he accepts the Republican presidential nomination. ``I get my
strength from my family,'' he declared.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>QUAYLE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Quayle, soon to be the Republican vice presidential nominee,
began to tell his story to the nation's voters, but he was
immediately bombarded with questions about his wealth, his military
record and his private life.
   At the first news conference with running mate George Bush,
Quayle denied suggestions he had a sexual relationship with
Washington lobbyist Paula Parkinson in 1980: ``There's nothing to
it.' The Indiana senator angrily dismissed as ``a cheap shot'' any
suggestions that he joined the National Guard in 1969 in order to
avoid going to Vietnam. And Quayle also knocked down reports of a
personal fortune as great as $200 million, pledging to disclose all
his holdings fully.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>SELECTION PROCESS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush made extensive notes on potential running mates on legal
pads and reviewed them closely last weekend before making his final
choice of Quayle, aides said. Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller,
also disclosed for the first time the complete list of 11 also-rans.
   They included Sen. Bob Dole and his wife, former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole; New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu,
California Gov. George Deukmejian, South Carolina Gov. Carroll
Campbell, Gov. Jim Thompson of Illinois, Sens. John Danforth of
Missouri, Alan Simpson of Wyoming and Pete Domenici of New Mexico,
Rep. Jack Kemp, and Attorney General Richard Thornburgh.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>IMAGE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the convention say Bush should step out from
President Reagan's shadow and ``come out of the chutes raising
hell'' to capture the White House. Some delegates believe Bush must
sharpen his image to succeed, with the advice ranging from
declaring his independence from President Reagan to using fewer
hand gestures, wearing horn-rimmed glasses and standing straight.
Others prefer that Bush ignore the suggestions and be himself.
   Although Bush cited Quayle's ``strong appeal'' to women in
introducing his choice for a running mate, analysts of the
Republicans' gender gap problem say youthful good looks won't be
enough to attract women's votes. ``It appears like the Republicans
are attempting to woo the women's vote rather than win it,'' said
Jane Danowitz, executive director of the Women's Campaign Fund, the
largest women's political action committee.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>BABY BOOM</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush strategists portray the selection of Quayle as his running
mate as a bold bid for the nation's younger generation, but
analysts warn that as a voting bloc, the baby boom could prove a
bust. The problem is that the nation's roughly 75 million baby
boomers make up too large a segment of the population to fit into
one ideological category, experts said. Generational links do not
necessarily mean shared politics. ``They're such large share of the
American population, they cross all income, occupational and
ideological lines,'' said Democratic pollster Peter Hart.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>QUAYLE IMPACT</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   As the initial surprise over the selection of Quayle as Bush's
running mate wore off, questions were raised about just what the
second-term senator brings to the Republican ticket.
   Bush and his aides argue that the 41-year-old Indiana senator,
as a member of the huge post-World War II generation, will be a
beacon toward the future for young American voters. They also say
he will attract votes in the Midwest, hit hard by farm woes. But
Quayle is unknown outside his native state, a blank slate for
voters that the GOP and the Democrats alike will rush to write on.
And that clearly worried Republican leaders.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>FARM VOTE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A string of Republican luminaries from certain nominee Bush on
down ridiculed Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis' farm policies,
the day after ``a son of the Midwest'' was picked for the No. 2
spot on the GOP ticket.
   Bush, Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole and Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng took aim at a ``Belgian endive'' comment
that's dogged Dukakis since the early days of the campaign. Dukakis
got in trouble when he suggested that farmers could diversify their
crops, in part by growing Belgian endive. ``I don't think that
Belgian endive is the answer to American agriculture,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
