<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN-Bush-JustPracticing     08-17 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN-Bush-Just Practicing,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush To Do Without Specs, Use TelePrompTer for Acceptance Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush rapped a gavel Wednesday,
surveyed the vast expanse of empty seats at the Superdome and put
his eyeglasses in his pocket.
   ``I'd like to do it without my specs,'' the vice president said,
spending a few minutes practicing his delivery from the podium
where he will accept the Republican presidential nomination
Thursday night.
   Bush, who rarely speaks in public without his wire-rimmed
glasses, told onlookers he felt comfortable using the TelePrompTer
without his glasses.
   With the TelePrompTer, a speaker's text is flashed onto two
large panes of see-through glass attached to the rostrum. Bush has
seldom used the device, and aides had expressed some concern over
his ability to use it effectively on Thursday.
   But Bush said, ``I like it. I feel comfortable with it.''
   He made his comments during a 20-minute visit to the cavernous
hall.
   ``Right height,'' he said of the hulking podium.
   Bush spoke playfully into the microphone and announced he was
calling to order a convention session at ``3:45 a.m.''
   ``Call to order, call to order, call to order,'' he repeated,
listening to his own voice reverberating.
   ``Any questions?'' he said, pointing far back into the cavernous
hall at a row of empty seats. ``Yes sir, back there. Do you have a
question? No questions? Thank you. I've just finished answering
questions,'' he said.
   ``This is great,'' he declared.
   Media adviser Roger Ailes said, however, ``We're a little
nervous about the TelePrompTer. He's not used to it.''
   Ailes said Bush also doesn't want to ``over-rehearse'' for the
speech.
   However, speechwriter Peggy Noonan, who wrote much of the
address Bush will deliver, said that Bush was practicing a good
deal, and continuing to fine-tune the speech.
   ``He's writing and practicing, writing and practicing,'' she
said. ``He'll probably do that up until 5 p.m. Thursday.''
</TEXT>
