<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--TVRatings     08-17 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--TV Ratings,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Ratings Drop on Second Night</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The viewing audience for the Republican
National Convention dropped Tuesday night, and ABC wound up with
the biggest share.
   ABC's average rating for the night was 6.4 and 13 percent of the
total television audience, according to the A.C. Nielsen Co. NBC,
the first-night winner, had a 6.0 rating and 12 share and CBS had a
5.2 rating and 10 share.
   The combined rating of 17.6 was down from the 19.9 cumulative
rating on Monday night, when President Reagan addressed the
convention.
   The second night was the biggest night for the Democratic
National Convention, which drew a 23.3 rating as Jesse Jackson
spoke.
   For the first two nights, the Democrats' average rating was 20.5
while the GOP has averaged 18.8.
   Each rating point represents 866,000 homes with television; the
share is the portion of all television sets in use during the time
period.
</TEXT>
