<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1832EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Quayle-Issues     08-17 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle-Issues,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Gets High Marks From Conservatives, Low From Liberals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle's voting record in the Senate has
earned him the admiration of conservatives and the enmity of
liberals on labor, education and civil rights issues.
   The two-term Indiana senator, tapped by George Bush as his
running mate, is the father of the Job Training Partnership Act,
which replaced the old CETA program and provides training through
the private sector instead of government-paid jobs.
   He led the battle against the plant closing notification bill,
which President Reagan eventually let become law without his
signature, and is currently opposing a bill to raise the minimum
wage from $3.35 to $4.65 an hour.
   On the Senate Armed Services Committee, Quayle has staked out a
hawkish position on defense. But at times he has also favored
smaller Pentagon increases than Reagan wanted and pressed for
military procurement reforms.
   Quayle voted twice this year against the Civil Rights
Restoration Act _ once when it passed the Senate 75-14 on Jan. 28
and again on March 22 when his colleagues overrode Reagan's veto,
73-24.
   He voted for confirmation of Robert Bork to the Supreme Court in
a losing cause this year, but led the successful 1986 fight to win
confirmation of Daniel Manion, a conservative South Bend, Ind.,
lawyer, to an appeals bench.
   The Senate's final approval of Manion came on a 50-49 vote, with
Vice President George Bush breaking the tie. Democrats had charged
Manion was inexperienced and a poor crafter of legal opinions.
   Civil rights groups are still upset with Quayle for voting in
1980 to weaken enforcement powers of the Fair Housing Act. The
amendment Quayle supported failed, 205-204.
   ``From the perspective of civil rights, Dan Quayle is a terrible
choice,'' said Ralph G. Neas, executive director of the Leadership
Conference on Civil Rights.
   On Social Security, during the 1985 fight over a budget freeze
backed by many Senate Republicans, Quayle voted with the majority,
51-47, to kill an amendment by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., to restore full cost-of-living increases.
   The freeze never became law. Quayle voted last year against a
move to trim the Social Security COLA.
   The National Committee to Preserve Social Security and Medicare
give Quayle a 38 percent rating for the current session of
Congress. ``That's far down in the pack,'' said Ken Hoagland, the
group's associate director of public affairs. ``It's not a good
senior voting record.''
   He was an early advocate of a tax simplification plan like the
one eventually enacted in 1986. Quayle's 1982 ``SELF'' tax plan _
Simplicity, Efficiency, Low Rates and Fairness _ would have
squeezed deductions and compressed tax rates, with a top rate of 30
percent.
   Quayle supports a Constitutional amendment to outlaw abortion
and has voted consistently against Medicaid funding of abortion.
   He has opposed Democrats' bills currently awaiting Senate votes
to require employers to offer workers a minimum package of health
benefits and to offer parents unpaid leaves upon childbirth or the
sickness of a child or parent.
   And he has voted for tuition tax credits and for voluntary
prayer in public schools.
   Mary Hatwood Futrell, president of the National Education
Association, said, ``We're disappointed that Bush, who says he
wants to be the education president, didn't choose somebody with a
strong voting record in education.'' The NEA gave Quayle a 15
percent correct voting record over the past seven years _ primarily
because of his votes to cut education spending _ which Futrell said
wasn't ``a passing grade in any classroom in America.''
   Americans for Democratic Action gave Quayle 5 percent on its
scorecard last year, and the AFL-CIO gave him a 20 percent rating.
   Quayle gets much higher marks from conservative groups: 89
percent from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and 81 percent from the
American Conservative Union in 1987. A pro-defense group, the
American Security Council, gave him a perfect 100 percent score in
1986.
   He has voted for the Superfund to clean up toxic wastes and the
Clean Air Act, but in 1986 opposed an acid rain bill he said would
impose ``staggering'' costs on the industrial Midwest.
   Quayle was also one of a handful of GOP senators who recently
urged Reagan to veto the $299 billion defense authorization bill.
   Quayle, as chairman of a Labor and Human Resources subcommittee,
worked with Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., to produce the Job
Training and Partnership Act, which replaced the 1973 Comprehensive
Employment Training Act that Reagan wanted to scrap.
   Quayle, in leading the fight against the bill to provide 60
days' notice of plant closings, said it would impose ``a
legislative straitjacket'' on industry'' and ``would impede our
capacity to compete in world markets.''
   But after the provision was cut from an omnibus trade bill that
Reagan vetoed and passed as a separate item, Quayle reportedly
advised the White House to let it become law without Reagan's
signature, rather than lose another veto fight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
