<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DroughtForecast     08-17 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Forecast,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little or No Relief Seen For Areas Hit By Drought, Heat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's no good news in the National Weather
Service's 30-day forecast for areas suffering drought, high heat or
the threat of forest fires.
   The weather service forecast for mid-August to mid-September,
released Wednesday, said that rainfall will be scarce for the
Dakotas, Nebraska, Iowa and the western Great Lakes area, the
farming heartland already withered by drought.
   The same area, and the Eastern region from North Carolina to
Maine, also are expected to continue to endure higher-than-normal
temperatures.
   Forest fire risk will continue high in the timberlands from
Minnesota west to Washington and south through California, the
weather service said. It warned that the forest fire risk will be
``extreme'' for parts of Wymoning, Montana, Idaho, Oregon, Nevada
and California.
   The weather service said that recent rains provided some relief
for parts of the Mississippi Valley, but it warned, ``much more
preciptiation is needed for areas east of the Rockies for moisture
to return to normal levels.''
   Higher than normal rainfall is predicted for the Texas-Louisiana
Gulf Coast and for the Southeast, from Florida to North Carolina,
the weather service said.
   Temperatures are expected to dip to below normal for Washington
and Oregon, but remain at blistering levels for much of California.
</TEXT>
