<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Senators-Quayle,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Senators Praise Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican senators trying to aid their
colleague Dan Quayle's rise from obscurity threw a tag-team
testimonial in front of reporters Wednesday to praise George Bush's
vice presidential running mate.
   ``We know him well,'' said Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
   For those who didn't know Quayle, the senators repeated his
vital statistics: he's young, he's conservative, he's married, he
has kids, he's not ugly.
   ``He's attractive because of his looks, he's attractive because
of his enthusiasm,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
   ``I think Dan Quayle, although he's 41 years of age, he's going
to send a message to the American people that the Republican Party
respects young people who achieve,'' said Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.
   Oh, yes, he's also rich, but the senators said that should not
hold him back.
   ``Let's not start this business of who's wealthy,'' Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., said after a question on whether Quayle's being a
millionaire will lose votes for the ticket.
   They also didn't like to dwell on his military record. During
the Vietnam War, Quayle served in the National Guard, a strategic
move taken by many during that era to satisfy their military
obligation while minimizing the risk of going into combat.
   ``He didn't carry a sign, he didn't go to Canada, he didn't
shirk his responsibility to the country,'' McCain said in response
to a question. ``I respected those who went into the guard.''
   Senators came and went at the hastily called news conference the
day after Quayle's name popped into the headlines. By the time it
was over, eight of them had stepped to the microphone to say how
much they liked him.
   The others attending the event were Sens. Nancy Kassebaum,
R-Kan.; Ted Stevens, R-Alaska; Alan Simpson, R-Wyo. and Arlen
Specter, R-Pa.
</TEXT>
