<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador     08-17 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arrested in Attack That Killed Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested another
suspect in a 1985 rebel attack on two cafes that killed four U.S.
Embassy Marines, two American businessmen and seven Salvadorans,
the military said Wednesday.
   Leftist Salvadoran rebels said Wednesday they will ask President
Oscar Arias of Costa Rica to act as go-between in an effort to
renew peace talks with the U.S.-backed government.
   The military statement identified the man arrested as Juan
Antonio Morales Lucero, 38, also known as ``Ruperto.'' It said he
is believed to belong to one of five rebel groups in the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front.
   In the attack in the capital's Zona Rosa entertainment district
June 19, 1985, guerrillas fired submachine guns at people in
sidewalk cafes. One attacker was killed by the rebels' own gunfire
but the rest escaped.
   Morales Lucero confessed after questioning that he helped
provide cover for the attack. He identified the two gunmen who
fired only by their pseudonyms of ``Ulysses'' and ``William,'' the
Defense Department said.
   According to Morales Lucero, the gunmen fled to a guerrilla
stronghold on the Guazapa volcano, 14 miles north of the capital,
immediately after the attack and were killed several months later
in a gunfight with soldiers, the communique said.
   It did not say when he was arrested or give other details. He
was not listed with San Salvador courts handling the Zona Rosa case.
   Three other men _ Juan Garcia Melendez, Jose Dimas Aguilar and
William Celio Rivas _ are being held for trial, charged with
providing cover to the gunmen.
   A military judge last fall ordered the three released under a
political amnesty the government decreed as part of a Central
American peace plan signed by five regional presidents Aug. 7, 1987.
   After the U.S. Embassy protested, President Jose Napoleon Duarte
revoked the judge's order.
   The Central American peace plan, drawn up by Arias, aims at
negotiating an end to civil strife in El Salvador, Nicaragua and
Guatemala. Arias won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for devising and
negotiating the agreement.
   A rebel statement broadcast by the clandestine Radio Venceremos
said they would seek to establish contact with Arias and ask him to
act as an intermediary in reviving peace talks.
   Several rounds of talks ending in October produced no agreement
on an end to the war, which began in 1979.
   The guerrillas insisted on sharing power in a provisional
government but Duarte wants them to stop fighting and join the
legal opposition.
</TEXT>
