<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1913EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Shultz-GOP     08-17 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Shultz-GOP,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Quayle Praised for Foreign Policy Contributions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz heaped
praise on George Bush and Dan Quayle on Wednesday, telling an
audience of foreign diplomats and business leaders the Republican
standard bearers had both made valuable contributions to U.S.
foreign policy.
   Shultz credited Bush with confronting the leaders of political
factions in El Salvador several years ago and telling them they
needed to unite against that country's terrorist death squads.
   ``I still don't know what George Bush said to them,'' Shultz
said. ``But, by God, they did it.''
   He said the vice president had also opened the human rights
dialogue between the United States and the Soviet Union in a
meeting with new Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev at the funeral of
his predecessor, Konstantin U. Chernenko.
   Gorbachev challenged Bush to discuss human rights lapses in the
United States, Shultz said, and the vice president told him: ``It's
a deal.''
   The agreement was that the U.S. side would listen to Soviet
criticism as long as the Soviets permitted a thorough discussion of
alleged Soviet human rights failures, Shultz said.
   ``We now have the most far-reaching human rights dialogue with
the Soviet Union that we've ever had,'' Shultz said.
   Shultz also credited Bush with persuading European leaders to
accept the deployment of U.S. medium-range missiles on their
territory, a step he said led to the treaty banning such weapons.
   As for Quayle, Shultz said his tough challenges to that treaty
as a member of the Senate Armed Services Committee had improved the
pact.
   ``Senator Quayle gave us a tough time on that treaty in the
Senate and wanted to know everything about it,'' Shultz said. ``He
wouldn't accept our explanations or staff papers. He did his
homework, and ultimately he convinced himself it was a good treaty
and he voted for it.''
   As vice president, Shultz said, Quayle will ``do his homework,
dig in, persevere, look at all the facts until he figures out what
the right thing is to do and then he will do that right thing.''
   Before beginning his speech to the foreign leaders, here to
observe the Republican National Convention, Shultz asked everyone
to stand for a moment of silence to mourn the deaths of President
Mohammad Zia ul-Haq of Pakistan and U.S. Ambassador Arnold L.
Raphel. They were among 37 people killed Wednesday when a Pakistani
military plane exploded upon takeoff.
   Shultz called Zia ``a great fighter for freedom'' and a great
supporter of ``the efforts that have finally brought the departure
of the Soviets from Afghanistan, where they shouldn't have been in
the first place.''
   He called Raphel ``a man of immense ability who was doing a
super job in Pakistan.''
   In speaking about foreign affairs, Shultz said the United States
and its allies ``have a success on our hands.''
   ``By success I mean we are seeing the ideas we have stood for
gaining ground, gaining ascendancy,'' he said.
   Shultz ticked off the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan, the
``settling down'' of the Iran-Iraq war, movement toward a
settlement in Angola, the strengthening of democratic policies in
the Philippines and South Korea and the development of ``more
constructive and productive'' relations with the Soviet Union.
   ``I could go on and on,'' Shultz said. ``It's really fun to do.''
</TEXT>
