<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-17 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Record-Setting Heat In Many Cities; Storms In New York, New
Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures once again soared to 100 or higher Wednesday in
parts of the mid-Atlantic states and Midwest, while strong
thunderstorms hit New Mexico and western New York state.
   Chicago tied a record for number of days in a year at or above
90 degrees with 46. The record was set in 1955. Beckley, W.Va., had
a reading of 95, an all-time high in the 25 years that records have
been kept.
   The National Weather Service said by midafternoon it had hit 100
in Baltimore; 101 in Washington; 103 in Nashville, Tenn.; and 104
in both Des Moines, Iowa, and Paducah, Ky., all records for the
date.
   During the morning, intense thunderstorms produced locally heavy
rainfall and high wind as in western New York state.
   At Wheatfield, N.Y., thunderstorm winds demolished a garage,
while a large tree limb knocked down a power line at North
Tonawanda. More than half an inch of rain fell in less than 5
minutes during a thunderstorm at Warsaw, N.Y.
   Farther west, a flash flood watch was posted for parts of New
Mexico, where showers and thunderstorms Tuesday night and Wednesday
morning created flooding that forced the closing of at least one
highway and more rain was expected.
   Thunderstorms also were reported in the Colorado Rockies, and
scattered storms were reported in Texas, South Dakota, the lower
Mississippi Valley, the Gulf Coast region and Florida.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT
included 0.96 inch at Deming, N.M.; 0.80 inch at Brownsville,
Texas; 0.30 inch at Texarkana, Texas; and 0.28 inch at Park Falls,
Wis.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 60
degrees at Arcata, Calif., and Durango, Colo., to 110 degrees at
Palm Springs, Calif. Wednesday's morning low was 30 degrees at
Jackson, Wyo.
   The national forecast for Thursday called for showers and
thunderstorms from the middle Mississippi Valley to the Virginia
coast, and from Eastern Texas to southern Florida; early-morning
showers in northern Maine; and late-day thunderstorms in the front
range of the Rockies in Colorado and New Mexico, and in central
Arizona.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were forecast for the Pacific Northwest
and along the Pacific Coast, as well as the upper Mississippi
Valley, the Great Lakes and a large portion of New York state and
New England; between 95 and 100 degrees from southwestern Texas
across Oklahoma, northern Arkansas, southern Missouri, the
Tennessee Valley, and the southern Atlantic Coast states; between
100 and 115 degrees in the desert Southwest and valleys of
California; and in the 80s and 90s in most of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
