<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PosterChildren     08-17 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poster Children,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Together as Tots, They Are Reunited on First Date</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTER PARK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first date between teen-agers Lara
Sontag and Gene Mayo was to celebrate their first meeting 11 years
ago, as poster children for the March of Dimes.
   The reunion of the high school kids, who suffer from spina
bifida, was a memorable one, with a chauffeured limousine, flowers
and a fancy dinner.
   The youngsters have used wheelchairs since childhood, but that
posed little problem Tuesday night.
   The Children's Wish Foundation of Winter Park provided the ride
in a white stretch limousine and the dinner at a top French
restaurants, Le Cordon Bleu. Gene provided a dozen miniature red
roses.
   It was the 16th birthday for Lara, who now lives in Carlisle,
Ind. She was in Orlando visiting relatives and wanted to celebrate
it by getting together with Gene.
   They were cherubic 4-year-olds when they posed, holding hands
and giggling, for publicity photographs for the Florida chapter of
the nationwide organization.
   She's considered him special since then, and they've kept in
touch sporadically.
   ``I proposed to Gene on television'' when they were 4, she said.
``He was shocked, but I don't remember what he said.''
   Spina bifida, a genetic defect that leaves the spinal cord
partly exposed, usually causes paralysis from the waist down.
   ``We're able to cope with it, but we haven't found a cure for
it,'' said Brian Ziegler, executive director of the Orlando March
of Dimes chapter.
   Lara basked in the attention Tuesday, saying she felt like a
movie star.
   Soft-spoken and polite, Gene, 15, is a wheelchair jock. He
placed among the top eight wheelchair racers in the Sunshine
Olympics junior games in Tennessee this year.
   The dark-haired Lara described herself as a bookworm. Gene said
he wasn't much of a reader, but they found plenty to talk about.
   ``This is much, much better than a prom night,'' Lara said.
</TEXT>
