<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Pakistan 2ndLd-Writethru a0858 08-17 0998</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Pakistan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0858,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Will Assist In Investigation Into Pakistan Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 7 grafs new to update.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will assist in Pakistan's
investigation into the mysterious crash Wednesday that claimed the
lives of President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq and American ambassador
Arnold L. Raphel.
   Until the results are known, senior U.S. officials are
withholding any conclusions about the disaster, which Pakistan's
U.N. ambassador said was preceded by an explosion aboard the plane.
   ``There is no confirmation of any foul play, but we are not
taking anything for granted,'' said a U.S. official who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``We offered to help and that offer was
accepted. An incident like this arouses suspicion.''
   There was no announcement of American participation in the
probe. Publicly, the Reagan administration refused to speculate
about any possibility of foul play.
   While joining Pakistan in mourning Zia's death, the State
Department stressed that it anticipated no slowdown in the flow of
U.S. weapons to Afghan rebels through the South Asian country.
   Nor do U.S. officials expect the loss of the pro-American
strongman to have any noticeable impact on the Soviet army's
orderly withdrawal from Afghanistan which Pakistan helped arrange
last April in Geneva.
   Without announcement, American and Soviet diplomats met quietly
in Washington Wednesday and agreed the pullout should continue, the
U.S. official said.
   Questions remain on Capitol Hill and within the State Department
whether Pakistan is bent on developing a nuclear bomb. For U.S. aid
to continue, President Reagan must certify in October that Pakistan
does not possess an explosive nuclear device.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, has taken the lead in criticizing the
administration for failing to get ``ironclad assurances'' that
Pakistan is not developing the bomb.
   Current U.S. aid totals $611 million, making Pakistan the fourth
largest recipient of U.S. military and economic assistance after
Israel, Egypt and Turkey.
   After the crash of Zia's plane in southern Punjab which also
killed U.S. ambassador Arnold L. Raphel, it also is unclear whether
Pakistan would proceed with elections scheduled for Nov. 16.
   Zia had dismissed his civilian government in May, but did not
call for elections within the 90 days prescribed by the Pakistani
constitution.
   He also barred candidates from running with party labels. Zia
took the position that party-based elections could mislead the
voters.
   Critics said this would focus attention on local issues and work
against Zia's main national opposition, the Pakistan People's
Party. That party is headed by Benazir Bhutto, whose father was
toppled in Zia's coup in 1977 and was later executed.
   In light of Pakistan's help in Afghanistan, the administration
was reluctant to make an issue of Zia's political maneuvers.
   ``We will stress that elections should be free and fair, but it
is not up to the U.S. government to prescribe how they should be
held,'' said one American official who spoke only on condition that
he not be identified.
   The State Department was quick to express both condolences and
U.S. support for Pakistan after the fatal crash.
   ``We have a long history of close and friendly cooperation with
Pakistan,'' department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said. ``At this
moment of extreme trial, I want to reiterate our commitment to
Pakistan and our full support for the acting president and his
government.''
   Pakistan not only funneled U.S. weapons to Afghan rebels in
their fight against Soviet forces in Afghanistan but provided haven
for millions of refugees.
   Some anaylsts considered Zia's actions risky, but the Soviets
did not retaliate. Nor did they menace Pakistan after invading
Afghanistan in December 1979. Mindful of the Soviets' long quest
for a warm-water port, the Carter administration assured the region
of U.S. protection.
   Mrs. Oakley stressed that U.S. aid to the Afghan rebels would
continue. ``There is no reason to have any doubt,'' she said.
   In New Orleans for the Republican National Convention, Secretary
of State George P. Shultz said Zia ``has been a great friend and a
great fighter for freedom,'' as well as a ``supporter of the
efforts that finally brought the departure of the Soviets out of
Afghanistan.''
   Zia's death is ``a great loss to the people of Pakistan,'' said
Shultz, who noted there had been a ``quick and orderly transition''
of government.
   Jeane Kirkpatrick, former U.S. ambassador to the United Nations
who also was in New Orleans, reacted to news of the crash with
''shock, just shock.''
   She called Zia ``a very strong person, very important to the
whole geopolitical strategic constellation of the region, very
important to the freedom fighters of Afghanistan.''
   Mrs. Kirkpatrick said Zia's death ``raises the question of
whether Pakistan can continue to as strongly support the mujahedeen
and whether Pakistan can resist the extremes of Islamic
fundamentalism.''
   Through Pakistan, the United States provided Stinger missiles
and other arms to Afghan rebels fighting Soviet forces and the
pro-Soviet government in Afghanistan.
   Last month, Zia stirred alarm in Washington with charges the
Soviets were replenishing their forces despite a commitment to pull
all of them out by next Feb. 15.
   It turned out the information was based on a statement by the
Soviet commander in Kabul, and Pakistan subsequently retracted the
allegation.
   Symobically, Zia, ambassador Raphel and U.S. and Pakistani
generals had flown to the southern Punjab to watch a field
demonstration of the U.S. M-1 tank which Pakistan considered buying
from the United States.
   Pakistan is receiving $260 million in U.S. military aid this
year. It recently struck a deal to lease up to half of 16 U.S. Navy
frigates that are being retired for budgetary reasons.
   State Department officials said they did not know what caused
the crash, which also claimed the life of Brig. Gen. Herbert M.
Wassom, 49, the chief U.S. defense representative in Pakistan.
   Mrs. Oakley said Pakistan authorities were investigating.
   She said the U.S. Air Force was sending a plane to Islamabad to
return the victims' bodies and Raphel's wife, Nancy, to the United
States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
