<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZumwaltService     08-17 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zumwalt Service,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Admiral's Son Remembered For Sense of Mission, Sense Of Humor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elmo R. Zumwalt III, son of the
admiral who ordered the spraying of Agent Orange in Vietnam and was
exposed to the defoliant himself, was remembered Wednesday as a man
with both a sense of mission and a sense of humor.
   ``It did not take me long to realize Elmo was a very special
person,'' said Bob Barrett, a friend who first met Zumwalt eight
years ago. ``He was full of fun, always the life of the party and
he had a teasing sense of humor that was punctuated with a loud
laugh.''
   A few months ago, the two said goodbye as Zumwalt, 42, was dying
of cancer, Barrett remembered at the memorial service at a funeral
home here.
   ``He looked really sick, and as I was leaving the house, he gave
a big bear hug,'' Barrett said. ``I knew then I would never see him
again. I said: `Elmo, do me a favor. Give me your laugh.' And he
laughed for me. He could laugh and joke even in his tremendous
plight. Let's not be sad. We'll see him again someday.''
   Zumwalt died Saturday after a five-year battle with cancer.
   John Pekkanen, one of the publishers of ``My Father, My Son,''
the book by the Zumwalts, also recalled Zumwalt's sense of humor.
   He said Zumwalt had just undergone a bone marrow transplant and
was drifting in and out of consciousness. When he would awaken,
Pekkanen peppered him with questions.
   Pekkanen left the house for a minute. When he came back,
Zumwalt, who appeared to be asleep, began thrashing around. He was
moaning, ``No more questions, no more questions.'' Then he stopped
moving.
   ``He opened one eye, then he opened the other eye. Then he burst
into laughter. I wasn't the only one struck by the Zumwalt humor,''
Pekkanen said.
   Ten friends spoke at the memorial service, which was attended by
350 to 400 people.
   Zumwalt was exposed to Agent Orange while he was serving in
Vietnam. In 1983, he was diagnosed with cancer. His father, Adm.
Elmo R. Zumwalt, had ordered the spraying of the defoliant, which
contains highly toxic dioxin, to push back the Viet Cong.
   But Zumwalt said he never blamed his father for his illness. And
his father said last week that his son's death would make him work
harder for benefits for the veterans affected by Agent Orange.
   Walter Anderson, editor at Parade magazine, met Zumwalt when the
publication wrote a story about him and his father.
   Anderson said Zumwalt had asked him to address his children,
Elmo Russell Zumwalt IV and Maya, and his wife, Katherine, directly.
   ``To my children, there is a loss of a father, a feeling that `I
lost my dad,''' Anderson said. ``Actually, you have not lost your
father's presence because when you have to decide what to do or
between right and wrong, you think `what would Daddy say.' You
can't argue, you've got to listen to him. And he will influence you
in more ways than you will know.''
   To his wife, Anderson said Zumwalt left the following message:
``As unlikely as it seems right now, there will come a time when
the pain of grieving will be less than the joy of remembering. It
will come.''
   James Caldwell, a longtime family friend and professor emeritus
of history at the University of North Carolina, said: ``Some
inherent quality made Elmo believe he had to be tested to the
limit. That was true of school and it was true of Vietnam. He did
not have to go to Vietnam, but he could not have lived with himself
if he didn't.''
</TEXT>
