<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Waite 1stLd-Writethru a0861 08-17 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Waite, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0861,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caller Says Terry Waite Alive, Could Be Freed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 CORRECT that Waite was going to meet Islamic
Jihad people when he disappeared, not unidentified hostage-takers.
PICKS up 7th graf pvs, Islamic Jihad usually ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anonymous telephone caller purporting
to speak for Islamic Jihad said Thursday that Church of England
envoy Terry Waite is alive and could be freed soon if Britain
``showed good intentions.''
   There was no way to verify the call, to a Western news agency in
west Beirut, as being authentic.
   No one claimed responsibility for Waite's disappearance after he
left his his west Beirut hotel and vanished on Jan. 20, 1987.
Thursday's phone call was the first indication Waite was with
Islamic Jihad, a Shiite Moslem underground faction loyal to Iran's
revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   ``The British hostage Terry Waite is alive and we might release
him if the government of (Prime Minister Margaret) Thatcher showed
good intentions,'' said the caller, speaking in classical Arabic
with a Lebanese accent.
   Waite disappeared while bound for a rendezvous with the Islamic
Jidah (Islamic holy war) captors of two American hostages _ Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press,
and educator Thomas Sutherland.
   Waite, 48, was acting as personal envoy for Archbishop of
Canterbury Robert Runcie in trying to secure the release of foreign
hostages.
   Islamic Jihad usually does not telephone statements and
repeatedly warned news media against using any telephoned
statements attributed to it.
   It usually sends written Arabic statements with a picture of one
or more of the hostages it is holding for authentication.
   But last May 4, Islamic Jihad telephoned the
Christian-controlled Voice of Lebanon radio to say it was releasing
three French hostages it was holding.
   Less than an hour later, Frenchmen Marcel Fontaine, Marcel
Carton and Jean-Paul Kauffman were freed.
   ``We are not doing it for her (Mrs. Thatcher's) sake, but on the
occasion of Ashoura,'' said the caller before he hung up.
   The 10-day Ashoura celebrations began last Friday evening,
commemorating the 7th-century killing of the Shiite Moslem sect's
saint Imam Hussein and 40 of his followers in Iraq 13 centuries ago.
   Runcie on Sunday urged Iran to use its influence in Lebanon to
secure the release of British hostages, including Waite.
   Relations have improved markedly between Britain and Iran in the
past few weeks.
   The 18 foreigners missing in Lebanon include nine Americans,
three Britons, one Irishman, one Indian, one West German, one
Italian and two unidentified men.
</TEXT>
