<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0720 08-17 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memo to Reagan on Iran-Contra Deal Recalled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 5th graf bgng ``Radzimski's
statements ... '' to update with Radzimski's role in last year's
Iran-Contra investigation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors say a onetime White House employee
recalled seeing a memo detailing diversion of U.S.-Iran arms-sale
profits to Nicaraguan rebels that had been attached to a letter to
President Reagan.
   James R. Radzimski, a former National Security Council aide,
told prosecutors that the memo by former NSC aide Oliver L. North
referred to $12 million in arms-sale proceeds that went to the
Contras, according to a filing in U.S. District Court.
   North's memo to former national security adviser John M.
Poindexter was attached to a letter that Poindexter sent to Reagan,
according to an account of Radzimski's statements to prosecutors.
   Reagan has denied knowing about the diversion and independent
counsel Lawrence E. Walsh has said he found no evidence the
president knew anything about it.
   Radzimski's statements were recounted in a letter Walsh sent to
North's defense lawyers and filed Monday in court. The former White
House aide has also told Congress he didn't know if Reagan ever saw
the memos.
   During last summer's congressional probe of the Iran-Contra
affair, Radzimski's name was dropped from a list of public
witnesses who were to appear at the hearings after investigators
decided that his memory of the affair was faulty.
   He ended up testifying to the House-Senate committee behind
closed doors.
   North, Poindexter and two arms dealers, retired Air Force Maj.
Gen. Richard V. Secord and Albert Hakim, are accused of illegally
conspiring to divert arms-sale profits to the rebels.
   Radzimski's recollections about the memo were offered to the
defense as evidence that might help exonerate North of wrongdoing.
Walsh's July 28 letter also includes statements by other witnesses
that North told them that lawyers advised him his activities were
legal.
   North, whose trial was recently postponed until after the
presidential election, could opt to offer these statements as
evidence that he had no intention of violating the law since he
acted under the assumption his activities were considered legal.
   Radzimski described North's memo as similar to one found by
then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III in November 1986 that
revealed the diversion of arms-sale proceeds, according to Walsh's
letter.
   Meese's investigation led to the dismissal of North and
Poindexter's resignation.
   North told Congress last year that he intended for Reagan to see
his memo about the diversion, but Poindexter testified he never
gave it to the president.
   The memo Radzimski ``recalls seeing was two to three pages long
and was written by Oliver North and addressed to John Poindexter.
Attached to the memo was a letter from Poindexter to the
president,'' Walsh wrote in the July 28 letter to North's lawyers.
   Radzimski told the House and Senate committees that investigated
the Iran-Contra affair that he recalled seeing ``two memorandums,
one addressed to Poindexter from Oliver North and a second
memorandum from Poindexter to the president.''
   But he told the panel he couldn't recall whether the memorandum
was delivered to Reagan.
</TEXT>
