<2ND_LINE>AM-Body Hidden,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: For 10 Days, Youths Hid Friend's Body After Shotgun
Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three young brothers panicked after
a teen-age companion was shot while they were fooling with a
shotgun, so they hid the body for 10 days, police say.
   Finally, one of the brothers led police to the decomposing
remains of his 14-year-old friend on Tuesday.
   ``The kids got panicky. They thought he was dead and they took
him over to the apartment next door,'' said police Detective Ralph
Pflieger.
   Preliminary results of an autopsy performed Wednesday revealed
William Dennis Bowen III died of a shotgun wound to the head, said
police spokesman George Pinckney.
   He said tests were still being conducted by the medical
examiner's office to determine, among other things, whether Bowen
died instantly.
   No charges were filed. Detectives questioned the brothers, ages
12, 14 and 15, and tentatively concluded the shooting occurred
accidentally on Aug. 7, Pinckney said. Bowen was reported missing
by his mother on Aug. 8.
   Names of the three brothers were not released because they are
juveniles.
   The 14-year-old who came forward told authorities that he, his
brothers and the victim had been playing with a shotgun they found
in a cousin's apartment. After the gun discharged, the brothers
dragged the victim next door and left him there, Pflieger said.
   The 14-year-old told an adult about the shooting after he was
taken into custody at Pinellas County Juvenile Detention Center
several days ago on a charge related to an auto theft, officials
said.
   ``We're not sure how long the third party (the adult at the
center) knew. That's part of the investigation,'' Pinckney said.
</TEXT>
