   The council's statement, carried Tuesday by two news agencies,
said the actions by the security units violated the Burmese
constitution and the U.N. Declaration of Human Rights.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Global arms sales are on the decline
and the superpowers are losing an important source of political
leverage as nations that once relied on them for weapons turn
elsewhere, a report said today.
   In its 1988 yearbook, the Stockholm International Peace Research
Institute said international arms trading reached $35 billion last
year.
   It said $24.7 billion worth of weapons, about 70 percent, were
delivered to Third World countries. India was the world's largest
buyer with $5.2 billion.
