<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BinghamFuneral     08-17 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bingham Funeral,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prominent Newspaperman Buried</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STAATS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Bingham Sr., patriarch of a
three-generation media family, was buried in historic Cave Hill
Cemetery Wednesday following a traditional Episcopal service
attended by nearly 700 people.
   Bingham died Monday at the age of 82, less than a year after he
was diagnosed as having a brain tumor, and just five days before
one of his many public gifts _ the 400-foot high, $2.6 million
Louisville Falls Fountain _ was to be dedicated.
   A longtime family friend, Katharine Graham, chairwoman of the
Washington Post Co., was among those attending, as well as a
delegation headed by Allen H. Neuharth, chairman of The Gannett
Co., which purchased the newspapers from the Binghams.
   Others in attendance included former Courier-Journal executive
editor Norman Isaacs, Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., former Govs. Edward
T. Breathitt and John Y. Brown and Louisville Mayor Jerry Abramson.
   At the direction of the Binghams, the service followed the order
for the burial from the Episcopal prayerbook of 1928, said Margaret
Dickinson, the church's music director.
   There were no eulogies and Bingham's name was never uttered
during the music-filled service led by the Rev. E. Benjamin Sanders.
   The downtown church is just a few blocks from The
Courier-Journal and Louisville Times building, the anchor structure
in a block that also contains the broadcast properties and
Standard-Gravure.
   During Bingham's ownership of The Courier-Journal and Louisville
Times, the morning Courier-Journal won eight Pulitzer Prizes and
championed education, mental health, civil rights and humanitarian
causes.
   Until two years ago, he had directed a media empire that also
included WHAS television, two radio stations and Standard Gravure
Corp., a printing company, as well as other smaller companies.
   The family holdings were sold because of changing economic
conditions and disagreements among his children.
</TEXT>
