<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Colombia-Americans     08-17 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Americans,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Chicago Men Held in Amazon Headed Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two college students released by guerrillas after
being held for 10 months in the Amazon left the U.S. Embassy in
Bogota, Colombia, and were headed home Wednesday, officials said.
   Stephan Koneman, 22, and Jason McLachan, 21, both of Chicago,
were released Sunday by Colombian leftist guerrillas who captured
them Oct. 4.
   Officials at the State Department in Washington, D.C., and at
the U.S. Embassy in Bogota said the two men were on their way home
Wednesday.
   Koneman's mother, Doris Koneman, said Wednesday that she hadn't
heard when her son would return, but was preparing to fly here from
her home in Breckinridge, Colo.
   ``I'll come when I hear, when I know,'' Mrs. Koneman said
Wednesday morning in a telephone interview.
   Tom Rissman, a spokesman for both families, said the two
students were scheduled to arrive in Chicago about 6:30 a.m.
Thursday. He said he had no further details, although the parents
had been notified.
   ``Obviously, they're delighted and can't wait to see their
children,'' said Rissman, a partner in the elder McLachan's law
firm.
   The two young men, both geography majors, were canoeing down the
Amazon last October when they were captured by members of the
Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces, a leftist rebel group,
Stephan Koneman told reporters Tuesday in Bogota after their
release was announced.
   Family members had not heard from the two since Koneman's
brother received a letter dated Sept. 22, Mrs. Koneman said.
   ``I'm filled with gratitude, I have a deep sense of the
miraculous and I really look forward to seeing him,'' Mrs. Koneman
said late Tuesday night after hearing her son was alive and well.
   ``The weight of the world is off our shoulders,'' added
Koneman's father Elmer Koneman, who lives in Chicago.
   Koneman said he and McLachan were kept at various jungle camps,
and were given the same food and shelter the guerrillas had.
   ``They always treated us well, although they had their
suspicions about what kind of work we were doing. But talking with
them we wiped out their doubts and they saw that we were
innocent,'' he said.
   Both students, who met at the Latin School in Chicago, were
seniors majoring in geography _ Koneman at the University of
Wisconsin-Madison and McLachan at Columbia University in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
