<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protests,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>78 Arrested As Abortion Protests Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion foes continued their 4-week-old battle
against abortion clinics Wednesday, with 78 more activists arrested
during two demonstrations.
   Police spokesman Cal Jackson said 32 protesters were arrested at
Midtown Hospital and 46 were arrested at the Feminist Women's
Health Center, both scenes of earlier demonstrations. Police said
those arrested would be charged with misdemeanors, mostly
obstructing the road and sidewalks.
   The arrests raised to 671 the total number arrested in the
series of demonstrations, which began July 19. The protests are
being orchestrated by the New York-based anti-abortion group
Operation Rescue.
   Many of those arrested in earlier protests have remained in jail
while refusing to give their names, saying they were calling
themselves ``Baby Jane Doe'' or ``Baby John Doe'' in solidarity
with aborted fetuses. Operation Rescue has promised to pack local
jails with protesters to bring national attention to its cause.
   Mayor Andrew Young said Wednesday that 44 U.S. representatives
had written him urging that he ask law enforcement authorities to
free the ``Baby Doe'' protesters. But Young refused the Congress
members' request, saying the prisoners could be released if they
reveal their identities.
   ``I don't think I'm required in any way to be involved in these
demonstrations,'' Young said.
   He pointed out that the city is spending $10,000 a week in
overtime pay to police officers assigned to the protests. Jail
costs in Atlanta city jails run an extra $42 per day per prisoner,
and $50 per day in Fulton County.
   Those signing the letter, made public by Young, included onetime
presidential candidate Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., and the entire
Louisiana delegation to the U.S. House. The letter was written by
Rep. Clyde C. Holloway, R-La. Many of the protesters have come from
Louisiana.
</TEXT>
