<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Duarte     08-17 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Duarte,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Confined to Avoid Danger of Disease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
has been confined to his home because a decline in his white blood
cell count makes him vulnerable to disease, a government official
said Wednesday.
   The decline in the number of white blood cells, which fight
infection, results from chemotherapy treatment Duarte has received
for liver cancer, Eduardo Colindres, the presidential press
secretary, said.
   Colindres spoke at news conference called to deny rumors that
Duarte was in a coma.
   According to the three physicians attending Duarte, ``his
general condition is good and stable and his spirit is more than
satisfactory,'' Colindres said.
   ``His health is not as delicate as is being speculated and he is
expected to resume his presidential duties next week,'' he said.
   The medical report said the decline in white blood cells is ``a
secondary effect that appears normally between the 10th and 15th
day after the application of chemotherapy,'' Colindres said.
   Duarte received his second chemotherapy treatment the first week
of August at Walter Reed Army Hospital in Washington, D.C. He
returned to El Salvador Aug. 10.
   Colindres said a physician from Walter Reed was expected to come
to El Salvador to examine Duarte. The visit already had been
planned in anticipation of the effects of the chemotherapy, he said.
   Duarte is ``being protected with broad-spectrum antibiotics,''
he said.
   Doctors at Walter Reed removed part of Duarte's stomach in June,
when he received his first chemotherapy treatment. He returned home
in mid-July, then flew back to the United States for the second
treatment.
   The president's Salvadoran doctors say he has advanced liver
cancer and have given him six to 18 months more to live.
 
</TEXT>
