<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Harper     08-17 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Harper,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actress Valerie Harper Gets Her Day in Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Valerie Harper said she's thrilled to
be having her day in court against her former employers, Lorimar
and NBC-TV, as trial of their multimillion-dollar suits and
countersuits opened Wednesday.
   The bitter dispute over the TV series ``Valerie'' began about a
year ago and came to trial faster than most cases because of an
unusual ``rent-a-judge'' program.
   All parties agreed to share costs of about $15,000 a week to
hire retired Superior Court Judge William Hogoboom and a staff of
court personnel to handle the case. The hearing is expected to last
five weeks.
   If they had waited for a regular court assignment in the
backlogged Los Angeles system, it could have taken five years to
bring the matter before a jury.
   ``I'm very glad to finally have my day in court,'' Miss Harper
told reporters. ``And it's wonderful to have it settled in a very
timely fashion. ... I'm just happy that I'm here in court. It's
thrilling.''
   Miss Harper was fired from ``Valerie'' last summer after a
heated dispute with Lorimar and the show's producers. They claimed
she threw tantrums and was difficult to work with. She claimed they
fired her without reason.
   Also at issue was a dispute over Miss Harper's request for an
increase in her $56,750-per-episode salary.
   Miss Harper and her husband, Tony Cacciotti, who was
co-executive producer of the series, sued Lorimar as well as NBC,
which carries the show, and two producers for $180 million,
alleging she was wrongfully fired. Cacciotti also was ousted from
the show.
   The defendants countersued Miss Harper, the Emmy-winning
comedian of the ``Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and ``Rhoda'' before she
launched ``Valerie, for $70 million, alleging breach of contract on
her part.
   A portion of the original case, which centered on the use of the
name ``Valerie'' in the show's title, was resolved when the name of
the show was changed recently to ``The Hogans.''
   In the opening round of jury selection, Hogoboom told
prospective jurors they would be seeing some famous faces in the
courtroom.
   In addition to Miss Harper, he said, witnesses are expected to
include two current stars of the show, Justin Bateman and Sandy
Duncan. Comedian Carol Burnett also was listed as a potential
witness.
   Merv Adelson, chairman of Lorimar, and the show's executive
producers, Robert Boyett and Thomas Miller, also were named as
witnesses along with Brandon Tartikoff, head of NBC's entertainment
division. They are defendants in Miss Harper's suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
