<DOCNO> AP880817-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pakistan-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru a0860 08-17 1096</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0860,1124</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Zia, U.S. Ambassador Killed in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos ISL1,ISL2, NY46,WX7,WX9,LON2 and LaserGraphic NY48.
^Eds: 4 grafs SUB for 6th graf pvs, In Washington ... UPDATING with
U.S. to aid investigation. PICKS up 7th graf pvs, Pakistan's
official ... SUBS 20th graf pvs, Zia, then ... to CORRECT that it
was May 29, 1988, not 1986; ADDS one graf at bottom with U.S.
Pakistani comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq and
U.S. Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel were killed Wednesday in an
explosion that destroyed their aircraft shortly after takeoff from
a remote airport.
   Among the 35 others aboard were Brig. Gen. Herbert M. Wassom,
chief U.S. defense representative to Pakistan, and several
Pakistani army generals. All were reported killed.
   Unofficial reports and rumors circulated that the Pakistan air
force C-130 was sabotaged, hit by an anti-aircraft missile or a
helicopter or was shot down by India, whose border was just 80
miles away.
   Zia was a close U.S. ally and ruled Pakistan for 11 years,
longest of anyone in the nation's 41-year history. In accordance
with the constitution, he was succeeded by Senate chairman Ghulam
Ishaq Khan, who declared a state of emergency and 10 days of
national mourning.
   ``The plane was engulfed in a big ball of fire ... somersaulted
and tumbled to the ground,'' said Azhar Imam Zaidi, a government
spokesman in Bahawalpur, where the crash occurred. He said wreckage
was strewn on a sandy plain about six miles from the city's
civilian airport.
   A U.S. official in Washington, speaking on condition of
anonymity, told The Associated Press that the United States will
assist in Pakistan's investigation of the crash.
   ``There is no confirmation of any foul play, but we are not
taking anything for granted,'' he said. ``We offered to help and
that offer was accepted. An incident like this arouses suspicion.''
   No announcement was made of the U.S. participation and publicly
the Reagan administration refused to speculate about any
possibility of foul play.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Zia and Raphel
had flown to Bahawalpur, 330 miles south of Islamabad, for a field
test of the U.S.-made M-1 tank, which Pakistan was considering
buying.
   Pakistan's official radio said the American-built transport
plane had just taken off when it exploded about 4:30 p.m. (7:30
a.m. EDT).
   At the United Nations in New York, Pakistani Ambassador S. Shah
Nawaz said Zia ``lost his life today in an airplane crash which
followed an explosion on board shortly after takeoff.''
   He told The Associated Press later: ``The C-130 is a very sturdy
plane. I have never heard of one exploding like this.''
   When asked it another aircraft might have collided with it, he
declared: ``No, no, no. When the president flies, no other planes
fly'' in the area.
   Neither Pakistani nor U.S. sources could confirm any of the
reports about what caused the crash. Ishaq Khan said sabotage could
not be ruled out, but officials refused further comment.
   Pakistan was created from Moslem-dominated areas of India when
the subcontinent became independent of Britain in 1947 and the two
countries have fought three wars. East Pakistan became the nation
of Bangladesh after a 1971 civil war in which India sided with the
secessionists.
   India and Pakistan each have tens of thousands of troops posted
along the 1,836-mile border and a U.N. frontier observer force has
been stationed since 1949 in the disputed Kashmir-Jammu region.
   Rajiv Gandhi, India's prime minister, said in New Delhi he was
``deeply shocked and distressed'' by the death of Zia, 64, and sent
condolences to the president's family.
   Ishaq Khan, Pakistan's acting president, met with the Cabinet
and armed forces chiefs.
   ``The nation will face the present hour of trial with unity,
fortitude and courage and will emerge more united and stronger from
the ordeal,'' he said in a midnight address to the nation.
   He said general elections scheduled for Nov. 16 would be held as
planned.
   Cities were reported to be calm and there was little immediate
reaction from Zia's political opponents. Official radio and
television broadcast prayers and readings from the Koran, the
Moslem holy book.
   There were no immediate reports of unusual military activity in
Pakistan after the president's death was announced.
   Zia, then army chief of staff, seized power in a bloodless coup
in 1977 and ruled under martial law until December 1985. He began
sharing power with a civilian government in early 1986, but
dismissed it last May 29 on grounds it failed to maintain law and
order and enact Islamic law.
   After the coup, Zia had the Cabinet arrested and sent ousted
Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto to trial for conspiracy to
murder a political opponent, who was not killed. Bhutto was hanged
in 1979 and his daughter, Benazir, later became Zia's main
political foe.
   ``Life and death is in the hands of God,'' she told The
Associated Press on Wednesday. `We will not say anything.''
   She said passing the mantle to the Senate chairman was ``a
positive development'' and added: ``Whatever should have been done
has been done. We are sure the changeover will be as smooth as
possible.''
   Zia supported guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed communi the Soviet
troop
withdrawal began May 15 the Kremlin has accused Pakistan of
continuing to funnel arms to the insurgents.
   In recent months, he faced an unprecedented challenge from the
increasingly unified political opposition led by Ms. Bhutto.
   Raphel, 45, was a native of Troy, N.Y and appointed ambassador
in January 1987 by President Reagan.
   It was his second assignment to Pakistan, where he served there
from 1975 to 1978 as political officer in the U.S. Embassy. Raphel
played a key role in negotiations to end the U.S. hostage crisis in
Iran in 1981.
   Vice President George Bush said at a news conference in New
Orleans, site of the Repblican Party convention, that Pakistan and
the United States ``have a very special relationship and the loss
of Gen. Zia is a great tragedy.''
   He called Raphel ``an outstanding ambassador.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said in New Orleans that Zia
``has been a great friend and a great fighter for freedom,'' as
well as a ``supporter of the efforts that finally brought the
departure of the Soviets out of Afghanistan.''
   Salam Hamid, secretary-general of the Pakistan League of
America, said in New York, ``We strongly feel it (the plane
explosion) was a sabotage.'' It was a military plane, he explained,
and ``usually military planes are totally unscheduled.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
