<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Bennett, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0863,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bennett Defends Administration's Education Policies</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs grafs 2-3 to reflect quote as delivered; picks up 4th
graf pvs, Bennett, the xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of Education William J. Bennett
said Wednesday night that Democratic leaders are embarrassed by
efforts to teach schoolchildren values and the pledge of allegiance.
   Bennett, in a brief address to the Republican National
Convention, said the Reagan administration has sparked controversy
by calling for teaching school children moral values and the
Judeo-Christian tradition.
   But ``there are some fights worth having,'' added Bennett, who
leaves his post next month.
   Bennett, the only Democrat in the Reagan Cabinet until he
switched to the GOP two years ago, said, ``the Democratic elites
regard much of American history as a mistake to be corrected, not a
legacy to be extended.''
   ``The sanctity of human life, moral standards, personal and
institutional responsibility _ even the pledge of allegiance _ too
often these are the subject of denigration or embarrassment among
leaders of the Democratic party,'' said Bennett.
   He charged that Democrats ``have lost confidence in our
principles and they have lost the will to defend our principles, at
home and abroad.''
   He said Ronald Reagan and George Bush have ``helped advance the
educational goals of the American people'' by pushing ``standards,
discipline, choice, accountability and the teaching of right and
wrong.''
   Bennett said, ``The American people expect our children to leave
school as better people _ better intellectually and better morally.
And they are right to expect this.''
   ``In reaffirming our beliefs, Republicans have looked to our
founders, to the Declaration, to the Constitution, and to our
history. And following Lincoln, we have sought guidance from our
Judeo-Christian tradition,'' he said. ``We have done this, we have
been criticized for doing this, and we shall continue to do this.''
   Reagan recently named Lauro Cavazos, president of Texas Tech
University, as Bennett's successor. If confirmed by the Senate,
Cavazos would be the first Hispanic Cabinet member in U.S. history.
</TEXT>
