<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Train     08-17 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Train,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix summary line and reflect 22 killed, sted of
17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Train Crash Kills 22, Injures 106</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-speed passenger train en route to Moscow
from Leningrad derailed in a swamp and caught fire, killing at
least 22 people and injuring more than 100, the state-controlled
media said Wednesday.
   Soviet officials blamed the crash of the Aurora train Tuesday
evening on dispatchers in the town of Bologoye, 180 miles northwest
of Moscow, near the midpoint of the route between the Soviet
Union's two largest cities.
   They said dispatchers failed to alert the engineers that a speed
limit of 40 mph had been imposed a day earlier on a section of bad
track, the official Tass news agency said. The train was traveling
90 mph when it slid off the rails and crashed, Tass said.
   ``The fast express train jumped the rails ... and a blaze
immediately broke out in it. Diesel fuel in the restaurant car,
which poured out of full fuel cans for the stoves, caught fire.
Flames spread to the other cars,'' Tass said, quoting an
unidentified Railway Ministry spokesman.
   Tass reported that 22 people had been killed and 107 were
hospitalized. The fatalities included children, the newspaper
Izvestia said without elaborating.
   Trains on the Moscow-Leningrad route typically operated at
capacity.
   The TV news program ``Vremya'' said a rail inspection team had
determined Monday there was bad track near the town of Belogoye,
and ordered trains be instructed to slow to 40 mph. But rail
dispatchers in Belogoye did not inform engineers and the Aurora
sped onto the bad track at full speed, the newscast said.
   Anatoly N. Sobin, director of the Leningrad railroad station in
Moscow, the train's destination, said the train was carrying 760
passengers when it crashed about 190 miles north of the capital.
   He told The Associated Press that 95 of the injured were
hospitalized in Bologoye and Vyshny Volochok, the towns near the
accident site.
   Sobin said he did not know the exact death toll from the crash,
but said it was not as deadly as a June 4 explosion aboard a
freight train in the city of Arzamas, 240 miles east of Moscow.
That blast killed nearly 100 people, wounded 200, and forced the
evacuation of 700 families.
   Tass said the Moscow-bound train left the tracks between the
Berezaika and Poplavenets stations at 6:34 p.m. Tuesday. Izvestia
said 15 cars derailed.
   Izvestia said firefighting equipment could not approach the
burning cars fast enough because they derailed in swampland. It
also reported that the first railway water tanker sent to the scene
turned out to be empty.
   Residents of nearby villages, soldiers and civilian emergency
workers went to the scene to treat the injured, Izvestia said.
   Traffic on the Moscow-Leningrad route was restored by Wednesday
morning, and an investigation team headed by a deputy chairman of
the Council of Ministers, Vladimir Gusev, was set up, Tass said.
   Disaster reports by Soviet media still are slow in appearing and
often lacking in important details. But the accounts Wednesday of
the fatal train derailment less than 24 hours earlier reflect the
closer watch Soviet media have been keeping on public matters under
Communist Party chief Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or
greater openness on subjects affecting the population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WyomingPrimary     08-17 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wyoming Primary,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic National Committee Gearing Up For Run Against Wallop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state lawmaker seeking to unseat U.S.
Sen. Malcolm Wallop got a boost to his war chest Wedneday from the
Democratic National Committee, but the incumbent still packs a far
greater punch.
   State Sen. John Vinich handily defeated two opponents in
Tuesday's Democratic primary, and Wallop faced only token
opposition on the GOP side.
   With the primary out of the way, Vinich settled down to woo
voters in the heavily Republican state away from Wallop, whom the
Democrats say has lost touch with his constituents in his 12 years
in Congress.
   That task was made a little easier by the Democratic National
Committee's grant of about $16,000, with hopes of more aid coming.
   ``We always felt that it (Wyoming) had the potential of being a
strong opportunity state,'' said DNC Communications Director Anita
Dunn. ``It was an impressive victory done the old-fashioned way _
Vinich clearly earned it. It was a hard campaign, a good campaign
with a very populist message.''
   While the race between Vinich, state schools Superintendent Lynn
Simons and University of Wyoming law professor Pete Maxfield
appeared tight going into Tuesday's election, the state senator
from Fremont County pulled away to a decisive victory.
   Unofficial returns showed Vinich with 23,165 votes, or 47
percent, while Maxfield collected 14,595, for 30 percent, and
Simons finished with 11,312 votes, or 23 percent.
   Although Vinich closed the primary race with $40,000 in debts,
his immediate cash flow problems for the general campaign will be
eased a little by the DNC contribution.
   Federal law allows the committee to give candidates $17,500 in
cash contributions, plus more in in-kind contributions based on
state populations. In Wyoming's case, Vinich could get as much as
another $109,000, according to Dunn.
   In-kind funds may be used in conjunction with campaign
expenditures on such items as polls, advertising and mailings,
according to Dunn. The DNC also may provide the campaign with
technical assistance.
   Dunn said Vinich would not begin receiving the in-kind funds
until some time after the DNC's senatorial committee meets early
next month.
   Panel members will decide then whether to give Vinich any or all
of the in-kind funds, based on how successful they feel he can be
against Wallop, Dunn said.
   Vinich will not get quite all the $17,500 in cash because the
committee had already given him about $1,000 for the primary race,
the same amount that went to Maxfield and Simons.
   Wallop's pocketbook is said to total more than $500,000, and in
Tuesday's voting, Wallop polled more votes than the three Democrats
combined _ 55,696, or 83 percent of the GOP vote.
   Vinich acknowledged that he has a tough battle ahead of him.
   ``We'll be working right along. It's an awesome task and I don't
think we can let up now,'' he said. ``We're on the downhill
stretch.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
