<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CourthouseHostages 1stLd-Writethru a0870 08-17 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Courthouse Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0870,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage-Taker Surrenders To Police, Wife Fatally Shot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The standoff ...,' to make it clear that
Firth was in jail prior to the hearing. INSERTS 1 graf after 10th
graf, ``We huddled ...,' with hostage's comment about Mrs. Firth.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who took three hostages at a
county courthouse surrendered peacefully to authorities Wednesday,
ending a 23-hour standoff during which he released his captives but
reported his wife killed herself.
   Kevin Patrick Firth, 30, was taken into custody at 9:15 a.m.,
police Sgt. Greg Kuhn said. He had reported four hours earlier that
his wife, Helen, had committed suicide.
   Authorities were uncertain, pending an autopsy, whether the
woman had killed herself or was shot to death by her husband, Mesa
County District Attorney Steve ErkenBrack said.
   The standoff began Tuesday morning when Firth's wife slipped him
a gun, and the two took three hostages just prior to the jailed
Firth's hearing on sexual assault charges. A jailer was sprayed in
the face with Mace during the apparent escape attempt, authorities
said.
   Mrs. Firth said she had smuggled explosives into the courthouse,
according to police. During the standoff, Firth threatened to blow
up the two-story building.
   A bomb squad searched the courthouse after Firth was taken into
custody, but no explosives were found, authorities said.
   ErkenBrack said hostages had reported seeing wire, tape and
round objects inside the courthouse. ``There apparently was
something there to make the hostages believe there were
explosives,'' he said.
   The hostages, court clerks Joyce Bailey and Sheila Shumway and
receptionist Linda Romersberger, were released one at a time, the
last walking out about 2 a.m. Wednesday.
   Shumway, the first to be set free, said Firth made the hostages
lie on the floor in a judge's chambers.
   ``We huddled together for two hours, holding hands and
praying,'' she said.
   Shumway said she was more frightened of Mrs. Firth than of Firth
himself. ``She was aggressive, and nervous and mad,'' she said
during a news conference by the three hostages Wednesday. ``He was
relatively calm, but I was only there for two hours.''
   Shumway said she thought Firth meant to kill her when he told
her she was going home.
   ``He told us not to cry and I said: `I'm sorry. I'm scared.' And
he said, `You get up. You're going home.' I thought he meant he was
going to kill me.
   ``Those 10 steps to the door, to the landing, was the longest
walk of my life.''
   Authorities said Firth appeared willing to give himself up about
3:30 a.m., but his wife balked and threatened many times to
detonate explosives.
   At 5:10 a.m., Firth used a police radio he had taken to report
that his wife had shot herself. When negotiators tried to calm him
down, he said:, ``I can't. I've got to be with her. It's too late.''
   Police said they believe the incident began as an abortive
escape attempt. But Firth made no demands, except to talk with
investigtors about the sexual assault case pending against him,
authorities said.
   Firth, a Delta auto mechanic, was released from prison in
October after serving time on a rape conviction.
   He was arrested again on March 8 and charged with first-degree
sexual assault and kidnapping in the Feb. 24 attack on a grocery
store employee.
   ErkenBrack said Firth faces possible charges including taking of
hostages, kidnapping, a felon in possession of a weapon and being a
habitual criminal.
</TEXT>
