<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0818 08-17 0973</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0818,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Faces Barrage of Questions</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2 grafs for 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``At the ...'' to UPDATE
with new Quayle quotes; SUBS 3 grafs for 9th graf pvs, bgng:
``Quayle was ...'' to UPDATE with Quayle in hall; INSERTS 2 grafs
after 13th graf pvs, bgng: ``Asked whether ...''; Picks up 14th
graf pvs, bgng: ``Later, Bush ...''
^By EVANS WITT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle, soon to be the Republican vice
presidential nominee, began to tell his story to the nation's
voters Wednesday, but he was immediately bombarded with questions
about his wealth, his military record and his private life.
   At the first news conference with running mate George Bush,
Quayle denied suggestions he had a sexual relationship with
Washington lobbyist Paula Parkinson on a 1980 Florida trip with
other congressmen: ``There's nothing to it.''
   ``I went down and I played golf and I came home and anybody that
knows me, knows that's exactly what I did,'' Quayle said in a
combative interview on the Cable News Network.
   The Indiana senator angrily dismissed as ``a cheap shot'' any
suggestions that he joined the National Guard in 1969 in order to
avoid going to Vietnam.
   And Quayle also knocked down reports of a personal fortune as
great as $200 million, pledging to disclose all his holdings fully.
   On his first full day as the Republican Party's new rising star,
Quayle held the joint news conference with Bush and traveled with
him to talk to the California delegation.
   With his wife Marilyn, the nominee-to-be greeted their three
children _ Tucker, 14; Benjamin, 11; and Corinne, 9 _ after they
arrived here on a chartered flight from Washington.
   Quayle also got a thunderous ovation from the Indiana
delegation, making an appearance that was scrapped Tuesday so Bush
could introduce him at a rally as his choice for the vice
presidential slot.
   ``Boy, do I look forward to going out there and campaigning
against Dukakis and Bentsen,'' Quayle told the cheering Hoosiers.
   Quayle denounced suggestions that his looks _ he has been
compared with actor Robert Redford _ would influence women to vote
for him, calling the suggestion ``sexist.''
   ``That is an insult to women,'' Quayle told CNN. ``I think it's
absolute nonsense. It is demeaning to women.''
   Quayle sat with Barbara Bush, the vice president's wife, in the
Superdome Wednesday night to witness the presidential nomination
roll call.
   The news conference was a tough one for Quayle as he faced a
series of sensitive questions.
   Foremost among those was the issue of his relationship _ if any
_ with Parkinson.
   In 1981, news reports said Quayle was one of three congressmen
who traveled to Florida on a golfing trip with the Washington
lobbyist. Quayle denied having sexual relations with her at the
time. Asked about his relationship with Parkinson, his answer was
terse: ``That has been covered and there's nothing to it.''
   Asked whether he had seen her on any other occasion, Quayle
simply said ``No.''
   Later in a CBS News interview, Quayle said the matter would not
be a campaign problem.
   ``There's nothing there. It's not going to be a problem,'' he
said.
   Later, Bush aide Robert Teeter said that the Parkinson matter
had been investigated in detail by Washington lawyer Robert
Kimmitt, who handled the probes of potential candidates for Bush.
   ``Kimmitt looked into it very carefully and gave the vice
president absolute assurance there was nothing there,'' Teeter said.
   He added that Bush and Quayle had discussed potential questions
before the news conference, including the Parkinson query.
   The 41-year-old politician also defended his qualifications to
be vice president or president, touting his knowledge of foreign
policy and defense matters.
   ``I know perhaps as much about national security as anybody,
with few exceptions,'' he said. ``The Senate Armed Services
Committee and my national security background gives me a very
important background for if some accident would befall the
president to have an understanding about what needs to be done to
preserve the freedoms and the opportunities in this country. I feel
prepared.''
   Quayle's claim of expertise brought up the issue of his military
service. Quayle joined the National Guard after graduating from
school in 1969, thereby avoiding the possibility he would be
drafted and sent to Vietnam.
   He bristled at any criticism of his choice.
   ``I do perceive that as being a cheap shot. I have a deep
affection for those men and women that have sacrificed their lives
in Vietnam. And anybody _ to imply anything differently is just
simply wrong,'' Quayle said.
   Asked whether his lack of a combat record would be a handicap
compared to Bush's distinguished war record, Quayle said it would
not.
   Teeter said Quayle had been asked as part of the selection
process whether he had used any family influence to get into the
National Guard _ which was flooded with applicants during the time
of Vietnam and the draft. Quayle denied invoking any such influence.
   Quayle, heir to a family trust that owns several newspapers,
denied he was very wealthy.
   When asked if he was worth $200 million, Quayle did not get a
chance to answer immediately. Instead, Bush stepped forward to
joke: ``Why do you think I chose him?''
   Then the Indianian tried a light answer to the question:
   ``That figure is not correct. Believe me, you have caused me a
lot of problems at home because my wife is asking about that.''
   Quayle said that, in any case, he would disclose his finances
fully, as will Bush.
   The Indiana senator also explained that he had executive
experience, listing several executive positions in state government
before going to Congress, including one as the chief inheritance
tax officer for the state.
   ``I was known as the chief grave robber of the state,'' he said.
</TEXT>
