<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Protests 1stLd-Writethru a0864 08-17 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0864,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Find Little Protest Work at Republican Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS day of week in 2nd graf; Inserts new grafs 4-8,
bgng, On a xxx, with details of small demonstrations</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican National Convention is so
short on protests that police officers working 12-hour shifts have
been left chatting among themselves in the sweltering heat.
   The New Orleans police, accustomed to the raucous Mardi Gras
celebrations, have found that the staid Republicans are an easier
crowd to control. A small number of demonstrations also have kept
arrests to a minimum _ 12 as of Wednesday and none in the
designated protest site of Lafayette Park.
   ``It's not as intense,'' said Lt. R.A. Paisant, who is
supervising a handful of officers at the park.
   On a rainy afternoon Wednesday, about 50 police officers ringed
the free speech stage as 20 well-dressed young people heckled a
half-dozen ``Skinheads'' who were using their scheduled 90 minutes
to blame blacks, Jews and Hispanics for all of the world's troubles.
   Earlier, an AIDs awareness group, Act Up, got heckled by
college-aged young people identifying themselves as Young
Republicans.
   Police ringed the stage for that, too, although nobody in the
park seemed tempted to do anything but shout insults back and
forth. About 100 people, apparently office workers on their way
home, stood around under the live oaks and magnolia trees watching.
   A young man who had been heckling the Skinheads refused to step
back when officers said he got too close to their line. He was
arrested _ the first person taken into custody at a demonstration
in the park _ but his identity was not immediately available.
   Afterwards, a phalanx of 25 officers, including four on
horseback, surrounded the six Skinheads and hustled them two blocks
safely to their cars.
   Police are on 12-hour shifts during the convention, as they are
during the two-week Carnival season leading up to Mardi Gras. But
the resemblance ends there.
   ``No. 1, the convention's only four or five days. So you don't
have everyone on 12-hour shifts for 10 or 12 days. You have the
time cut in half,'' Paisant said.
   Also, most convention events are during the day, while Mardi
Gras parades and parties are held at night and on weekends.
   But the biggest difference is the size of the convention crowds,
which are smaller and more spread out than at Mardi Gras, when one
million people jam the parade routes and fill the French Quarter.
   While most of the estimated 30,000 people are in the Superdome
when the convention is in session, the rest of the time the
delegates and delegate-watchers are spread out with many attending
the more than 500 parties scheduled during the week.
   When they do party, out-of-town Republicans don't seem to get as
rowdy as New Orleans residents, especially not Mardi Gras revelers.
   ``They're not as hard drinking,'' Paisant said.
   Moreover, neither convention-related events, such as a rally for
Vice President George Bush held Tuesday, nor the demonstrations
have drawn large numbers of local residents.
   A lot of idle time appears to make for irritable police officers.
   About 10 plainclothes officers became frustrated on Monday night
when a group of about 20 demonstrators marched toward the Superdome
and ended their protest on a lightly-traveled back street near the
arena.
   While there, they handed out leaflets denouncing Bush to the few
Republicans who passed by headed for the Superdome, and taunted the
officers for watching them so closely.
   The officers remained stone-faced, arms folded, in the
late-afternoon heat.
   When a reporter asked an officer what he made of the situation,
he snapped ``No comment,'' the standard reply from most officers on
the convention beat.
   The busiest officers appear to be those directing traffic near
the Superdome.
   A motorist who falls short of making it through a yellow light
will get at least a glare and a growl from an officer if the car
juts into the intersection.
   And woe to the motorist who stops to let someone out at Poydras
and Loyola streets, the busiest intersection in the city these
days. Such a transgression could warrant a tongue-lashing.
   One officer was asked to comment on the oppressively hot job.
``No comment,'' he snapped.
</TEXT>
