<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Quayle-Impact 3rdLd-Writethru a0884 08-17 0857</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle-Impact, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0884,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Candidacy Runs Into Questions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 24th graf pvs, bgng: ``That's sexist
...'' to UPDATE with new Quayle quotes on ``sexist'' question.
Picks up 25th graf pvs, bgng: ``In addition...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the initial surprise over Dan Quayle's
selection as George Bush's running mate wore off Wednesday,
questions were raised about just what this second-term senator
brings to the Republican ticket.
   ``Politically, I don't know what he brings to the party,'' said
Richard Bernstein, a delegate from Westchester County, New York.
``I'm not sure I understand the dynamics of it.''
   In particular, questions have been raised about whether Quayle
is up to the job of vice president _ or president.
   ``His reputation as a lightweight is overstated,'' said Norman
Ornstein, a congressional scholar at the conservative American
Enterprise Institute in Washington. ``When Quayle applies himself,
he can do quite well. ... He doesn't apply himself much.''
   Bush and his aides argue that the 41-year-old Indiana senator,
as a member of the huge post-World War II generation, will be a
beacon toward the future for young American voters. They also say
he will attract votes in the Midwest, hit hard by farm woes.
   The conservative senator is an attractive, energetic campaigner
who is comfortable with television and the new campaign
technologies of the 1980s, they add.
   But Quayle is unknown outside his native state, a blank slate
for voters that the GOP and the Democrats alike will rush to write
on.
   And that clearly worried Republican leaders.
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel told Arizona delegates on
Wednesday to stop telling reporters they know little about Quayle
``because anything negative will be reported and anything positive
will not be.''
   But most delegates were willing to speak their minds.
   ``It was a surprise to me,'' E. Leroy Owens, a GOP district
leader from Manhattan, said of the Quayle selection. ``But I hope
he does not have any skeletons in his closet.''
   Quayle faced questioning about potential skeletons at a joint
news conference with Bush on Wednesday.
   Quayle said there was nothing to speculation that he'd had a
sexual relationship with Washington lobbyist Paula Parkinson on a
golfing trip to Florida with two other congressmen in 1980. He said
suggestions he had ducked service in Vietnam with National Guard
duty were a ``cheap shot.'' And he said stories putting his net
worth at $200 million were just wrong.
   But the hardest, and most important, question Quayle must
answer, with word and action, is whether he is qualified to assume
the presidency.
   ``I don't think he's the right man for the job,'' said Jack
Dunlop, a delegate from Auburn, Ala. ``I don't think the people of
Alabama will support him. He's too young and too inexperienced.''
   Dunlop's choice for the No. 2 spot was former United Nations
Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick.
   The Democrats made it clear they would draw telling comparisons
of Quayle's qualifications and those of their vice presidential
candidate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas. A joke already making the
rounds Wednesday cracked that the Bush-Quayle ticket could be
called ``Bush Lite.''
   ``Nobody ever asked any questions about whether Lloyd Bentsen
was qualified to be president of the United States,'' Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis said Wednesday at a campaign
stop in Virginia, Minn.
   Ornstein, who has studied Congress for many years, said Quayle
``has potential, but it's just potential. ... I would not describe
Dan Quayle as a mature 41-year-old.'' Ornstein said he would rank
Quayle only at the midpoint of all senators, ``in any dimension of
quality you want.''
   Beyond the question of his qualifications, Quayle also comes
under opposition fire as the darling of the GOP's far right, as
represented by Sen. Gordon Humphrey of New Hampshire. Earlier this
week, Humphrey threatened that conservatives would sit on their
hands this fall if Bush did not choose a true conservative.
   ``It just showed that Bush picked somebody from Humphrey's short
list,'' Washington Democratic Chairwoman Karen Marchioro said in
Seattle. ``If (Bush) can't stand up to Gordon Humphrey, God only
knows what he'd do with the Ruskies.''
   Even one of Quayle's assets, his youthful good looks, is turning
into something of a liability.
   Several Republicans were quoted as saying Quayle's handsomeness
would attract female voters, who prefer Dukakis over Bush by large
margins in several surveys.
   ``That's sexist. It's ridiculous,'' Nancy Neuman, president of
the League of Women Voters, said in an interview Wednesday.
   Quayle agreed with that description of the idea.
   ``Women ought to resent the suggestion that they would vote for
somebody on looks,'' Quayle said in an interview on Cable News
Network. ``That is an insult to women. ... I think it's absolute
nonsense. It is demeaning to women.''
   In addition, Quayle's stance against abortion and the proposed
Equal Rights Amendment drew heavy fire from some women's groups.
   ``With the nomination of Dan Quayle for vice president, George
Bush has essentially written off the women's vote,'' said Kate
Michelman, executive director of the National Abortion Rights
Action League. ``Quayle has an extraordinary anti-women record in
his tenure in the Senate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
