<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HeatRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0859 08-17 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heat Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0859,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>From Carolinas to Des Moines, The Heat Wave Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Misery Summer, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE temperature records, and that
TVA again broke power demand record; ADDS new quote. Picks up 7th
graf pvs, `In the ..'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More temperature records fell Wednesday as the Heat Wave of '88
kept its grip on a wide area from the Carolinas to the upper
Midwest.
   ``It's miserable,'' said photographer Chuck Novara of
Murphysboro, Ill. ``We have a window fan. You wake up, you sweat.''
   The temperature hit 104 in Baltimore, 101 in Washington and in
Louisville, Ky.; 103 in Nashville, Tenn.; and 104 in both Des
Moines, Iowa, and Paducah, Ky., all records for the date, the
National Weather Service said.
   Beckley, W.Va., broke its all-time temperature record when it
reached 96 degrees, but it's a town where official weather records
date back only 25 years. The old high was 94 degrees, which was
reached two times last month.
   The Tennessee Valley Authority, having already set back-to-back
summer power usage records Monday and Tuesday, issued an urgent
appeal Wednesday for customers to conserve.
   But despite the request, power usage climbed again, setting
another TVA summertime record.
   The federally owned utility has never been forced to reduce
electricity to residential customers, but ``if electrical usage is
not reduced sufficiently, some areas may experience an interruption
of service,'' said Robert C. Steffy Jr., senior vice president of
power. TVA serves about 8 million people in Tennessee and parts of
six other states.
   Among the other cities for which high-temperature records were
set or tied were Cleveland, where it hit 99; Columbus, Ohio, 97;
Detroit, Mich., 97; Indianapolis, 99; Madison, Wis., 102;
Milwaukee, 100; Norfolk, Va., 98; Philadelphia, 94; Pittsburgh,
100; Raleigh, N.C., 98; and Richmond, Va., 99.
   In the usually breezy mountains of North Carolina, the
temperature at the Grandfather Mountain tourist attraction sizzled
up to 80 degrees for the first time in five years. One man said it
was time to ``take those sweaters off.''
   ``Most homes don't have air conditioning,'' said Katherine
Morton, a spokesman for the attraction. ``I have a fan going in my
office right now. I don't know what the creative people who don't
have to work are doing, but I imagine some people are finding a
cold stream.''
   Another tourist attraction was affected by the heat in Boston.
The famed Minuteman statue, the 113-year-old tribute to New
England's revolutionaries, has begun dripping a black substance
from its musket, making it look like the statue was melting.
   But experts believe that a resin applied in 1975 to make a
plaster casting of the monument seeped into the statue and is now
being liquefied by heat and humidity, said Ed McManus, a National
Park Service conservator in Boston.
   At the Illinois State Fair in Springfield, officials reported
the scorching heat was reducing attendance and killing at least
seven birds and two sheep on display.
   And in Chicago, Animal Control Director Peter Poholik urged the
city's three main horse carriage companies, operating along the
lakefront, to suspend all daytime service while temperatures remain
above 90 degrees.
   Members of the Poughkeepsie, N.Y., town council had a
tongue-in-cheek way of fighting the heat: They unanimously declared
it illegal for anyone to record a temperature above 89{ degrees.
   Since the resolution was approved Monday night, the thermometer
in the Hudson Valley college town has behaved, with Wednesday's
midafternoon high a chilly 84 degrees.
   Paradoxically, scientists said this week, the same overall
weather pattern that is creating record temperatures is contributed
to unusually cold water at East Coast beaches this summer.
   Southwesterly winds are pushing warm surface water away from the
shoreline, and the surface water is being replaced by colder water
from the oceanic depths.
   ``It's nothing new, but it's usually not noticeable on the
Eastern seaboard,'' said James A. Eberwine, a National Weather
Service forecaster in Atlantic City, N.J.
   ``On the July 4 weekend, we had water temperatures in the 50s.
We had to put out an alert notice for hypothermia. People just
can't believe it.''
   Satellite photographs show unusually cold water extending from
just south of Long Island all the way down to Virginia Beach, said
Dorothy Kropp, a weather service meteorologist in Camp Springs, Md.
</TEXT>
