<DOCNO> AP880817-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2341EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--BennettText 1stLd-Writethru a0866 08-17 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Bennett Text, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0866,790</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Provides an as-delivered transcript; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the speech by
Education Secretary William J. Bennett to the Republican National
Convention Wednesday night.
   Ladies and gentlemen, there's a story about a young legislator
who sought the advice of a much older, wiser legislator about how
to conduct himself on the first day of a legislative session.
   The older, wiser legislator said, ``Stand up, say what you have
to say, and sit down.'' And that's what I plan to do.
   Over the past seven years it has been my privilege and pleasure
to work for the greatest president in my lifetime _ Ronald Wilson
Reagan.
   And tonight, we are here to nominate his successor, the vice
president of the United States, the leader of our Republican Party,
and the next leader of the free world _ George Bush.
   Ladies and gentlemen, as you know, the Reagan-Bush
administration has helped advance the educational goals of the
American people. I know, cause I've been there. I've visited and
I've taught at over a hundred elementary and secondary schools.
   Plato taught that there is above all one crucial political
question. It is the upbringing of children. The American people
understand this.
   When asked what they want from our schools, Americans
consistently call for two things: teach our children, they say,
teach our children how to speak and write and count and think
correctly; and second, help them develop reliable standards of
right and wrong to guide them through life.
   The American people expect our children to leave school as
better people _ better intellectually and better morally. And they
are right to expect this.
   In the past eight years, the vital terms of the education debate
in this country have changed. Now, the national debate and
discussion on education are focused on issues like standards and
accountability. It's focused on discipline, on instilling
self-discipline in children and getting drugs out of schools.
   It's on learning math, history, geography and science; and its
on mastering the English language; its on honoring our good
teachers, like Jaime Escalante. It's on teaching our moral and
political principles. It's on schools forming character. And now,
finally, it's focused on giving parents a choice in deciding where
their children will go to school.
   Bringing these issues front and center has provoked controversy
from time to time. But there are some fights worth fighting,
   In education, as with other issues, we have witnessed a crucial
shift in the very terms of our national discourse. In reaffirming
our beliefs, Republicans have looked to our founders, to the
Declaration of Independence, to the Constitution, and to our
history.
   And following Lincoln, we have sought guidance from our
Judeo-Christian tradition. We have done this, we have been
criticized for doing this, and we shall continue to do this.
   The extent of our success can be measured by the emptiness of
the new Democratic Party platform. Democratic leaders once used to
celebrate their liberalism unabashedly. Today, they're reluctant
even to utter the word. The Democratic leadership won't come clean,
   But make no mistake: they are still liberals. And their liberal
policies will not sustain the traditions, will not sustain the
institutions, will not sustain the moral values that are at the
foundation of our society.
   Consider the family. The Democratic leadership would make
government not the ally of the family, but its replacement. The
sanctity of human life, moral standards, personal and institutional
responsibility _ even the pledge of allegiance _ too often these
are the subject of denigration or embarrassment among leaders of
the Democratic Party.
   Once it could be said that the leadership of the Democratic
Party _ the Democratic party of Truman, Kennedy and Jackson _
that's Scoop Jackson not Jesse Jackson _ was a proud defender of
freedom. But today's Democratic leadership is not.
   Today's Democratic leaders waver. They are not resolute. They
have lost confidence in our principles and they have lost the will
to defend our principles. They have lost that will both at home and
abroad,
   Why? I'll tell you why. Because the Democratic elites regard
much of American history as a mistake to be corrected, not a legacy
to be extended. Those Democratic leaders need to learn that in the
long history of nations and peoples, the American achievement
stands high. It is rare, and that achievement is worth defending.
   Ladies and gentlemen, the Democratic leadership doesn't
understand this. But George Bush does.
   George Bush knows about the importance of standards, discipline,
choice, accountability, and the teaching of right and wrong.
   George Bush has the experience and the guts to lead this
country. He will protect our precious freedoms. He will help to
educate our precious children. Tonight, I am proud _ we are proud _
to stand with our principles and to stand with George Bush.
   Thank you very much.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Bennett Text _ 1 Take</HEAD>
