<HEAD>Quayle Nomination Upsets Game Show Fans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alas, poor Dan Quayle _ some television game show
fans didn't care to hear about him even if he was chosen Tuesday as
George Bush's vice presidential running mate.
   Station WLS-TV, owned and operated by ABC, ran a bulletin
shortly before 4 p.m, CDT announcing that Sen. Dan Quayle of
Indiana was Bush's long-awaited choice. But the announcement came
in the final two minutes of the popular game show, ``Jeopardy,''
which, as aficionados know, is the time for ``Final Jeopardy.''
   So, while Quayle's name may have been the answer to the biggest
question of the Republican National Convention, to ``Jeopardy''
viewers it blocked out the eagerly anticipated final answer and
question.
   ``We probably got about 50 to 60 angry telephone calls,'' said
WLS spokeswoman Fran Preston. ``We had to run the final answer and
question on the 4 o'clock news to keep everyone happy.''
   The answer, which always precedes the question, was: ``Hamlet
called him `a fellow of infinite jest, of most excellent fancy.'''
   The question was: ``Who was Yorick?'' not ``Who is Dan Quayle?''
</TEXT>
