<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-Drought-TheChases-IV ADV22   08-17 1001</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-The Chases-IV, ADV 22,1033</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, Aug. 22 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Part IV: Proud Farm Family Reaches for Washington's Hand</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic logo</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan this month approved the
costliest disaster relief measure ever enacted for farmers. This
report, one of an occasional series on the drought and the Chases
of Barry County, Mich., looks at how one troubled farm family is
reaching for Washington's helping hand.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jean and Gordon Chase have been feeding
their dairy cows an apple pulp-and-cereal mix so that their hay
supply, practically wiped out by the drought of '88, will last the
year.
   But now they question the wisdom of their hard-headed planning.
   Their feed supply means they may not be eligible to buy as much
discount corn as they hoped from the federal government under a
drought-relief plan just signed into law.
   The Chases are disappointed, but they aren't surprised.
   ``All along, what these government programs have done is allow
the poor manager to last longer,'' says Gordon Chase, shaking his
head and wiping his brow in the heat of the family den.
   Farm subsidy programs are a sensitive subject for the Chases, as
they are for other farmers who pride themselves on their
independence. They insist they don't want handouts, but acknowledge
they do need help and are frustrated when they don't qualify.
   ``You hear more and more farmers talking about that now than
ever before _ that a handout is not what we want,'' says Jean
Chase. ``We don't want something that helps temporarily, but will
help us establish solutions for these kinds of problems in the
future.''
   Part of that solution may be federal crop insurance.
   With their son, Kurt, and his wife, Dena, the Chases farm 1,100
acres of wheat, soybeans and corn here in southwest Michigan.
   They took out only enough crop insurance this year to cover 66
acres of string beans they were growing for a canning company. They
plan to expand their coverage next year, although they don't know
by how much. The Chases saw the advantages of insurance after their
beans, though intensely irrigated, died under the hot sun.
   The Chases grow frustrated when they see farmers receiving large
government relief payments after they have been careless in their
business.
   ``We don't like to take it and yet we're greedy and get upset
when we don't qualify when we see other people who do,'' says Mrs.
Chase, 51.
   It also bothers the Chases that the subsidies create some public
resentment toward farmers.
   ``They've caused some hard feelings among other businesses and
that's tough to deal with,'' says Gordon Chase, 51, as he sips iced
tea in the 95-degree heat.
   But the Chases know they cannot afford to ignore the subsidies.
   They have applied for government assistance under the new relief
law, anticipating at least a 35-percent loss in crops because of
the drought, the minimum loss covered by the Washington aid program.
   The government's $3.9 billion drought-relief plan will
compensate farmers for 65 percent of the crop revenues they lose
above that minimum, up to $100,000.
   Although many of the Chases' 350 acres of corn are lost, some
plants were revived by recent rains and are growing small,
underdeveloped ears. Their wheat harvest was healthy, but their 200
acres of soybeans will survive only if more rain falls.
   With the harvest still weeks away, they cannot be sure of their
yield.
   ``You'd rather have the crop that you've worked so hard on,''
Mrs. Chase says. ``But at this point, we don't even know if we'll
be getting any assistance at all.''
   Because of their feed shortage, the Chases hoped to get a
discount on low-cost government corn. But the local Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Service office says the Chases will
be eligible to buy only 90 days' worth of feed at the discounted
price, less than they sought for feeding their 300 head of dairy
and beef cattle.
   One bright spot: The drought-relief law cancels a planned
reduction in dairy price levels under the government's
market-support program. Under the plan, the price farmers get for
their milk would have been cut to $10.10 per hundredweight from
$10.60.
   For the Chases, whose 125 milk cows each produce an average
19,000 pounds of milk per year, that 50-cent cut would have hurt.
   Reducing price supports was to have been one of a series of
moves to cut back on the accumulation of costly surplus stocks of
dairy products. But the Chases believe such methods may actually
add to the financial plight of farmers.
   Under the Dairy Termination Program, part of the 1985 Farm Bill,
the federal government paid dairy farmers to get out of the
business. The program was partly funded by farmers who chose to
stay in dairying.
   The Chases estimate about $1,500 came out of their milk checks
each month to fund the 18-month program.
   ``When they cut your prices to help take care of a surplus, at
least from our standpoint, it doesn't work,'' Chase says.
   ``Because we're in debt, we have to have a certain amount of
money flowing through this business every month. So when they cut
your prices, you have to do something, so we milked more cows,''
Chase says. ``That defeats the whole purpose of what the
government's trying to do, but you have no choice.''
   The Chases are quick to admit they don't have any answers. But
they like the sound of a quota system, like one in Canada, under
which the government pays a relatively high price for a certain
amount of crops or milk from each farmer, then cuts the payment
drastically for anything beyond that set amount. That system keeps
surpluses down.
   A twist of nature, however, like the drought of '88, can undo
any system.
   ``When you have a year like this, I don't think there are any
real answers,'' Chase says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon Aug. 22 or Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
