<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   08-17 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0541</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit widened to $12.5
billion in June as imports hit an all-time high, according to a
government report that analysts said shows how far the country
still has to go to solve its trade problems.
   The gap between what America exports and what the country
imports surged by 28.5 percent in June, a major setback after three
consecutive monthly improvements, the Commerce Department said
Tuesday.
   For the first six months of the year, the deficit was running at
an annual rate of $140 billion, down from the record $170.3 billion
deficit set in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American factories, mines and utilities
operated at 83.5 percent of capacity in July, the highest operating
level in eight years, the government reported.
   The Federal Reserve said Tuesday that the operating rate climbed
a sharp 0.4 percentage point last month and now stands 2.4
percentage points higher than it was a year ago as American
manufacturers continued to benefit from a boom in export sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Insurance Group Inc. agreed to
discuss a $4.9 billion buyout offer from Batus Inc., the first
concession by the insurer in a bitter takeover battle that has
raged for eight months.
   Farmers said Tuesday's offer of negotiations didn't mean it had
dropped a number of objections to being bought by the Louisville,
Ky.-based tobacco and retailing company.
   Batus, a subisidiary of BAT Industries PLC of Britain, is
seeking to gain a foothold in the American financial services
business. Farmers is a leading auto, home and property and casualty
insurer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. rejected a takeover bid
from Roy E. Disney's Shamrock Holdings Inc. valued at roughly $3
billion, saying it planned to remain independent despite persistent
takeover rumors.
   Polaroid's 13-member board voted unanimously to turn down the
unsolicited bid from Shamrock, a Burbank, Calif., investment firm
owned by Disney, a nephew of animator Walt Disney.
   In closing trading Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange,
Polaroid rose 87.5 cents to $43.37{.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cablevision Systems Corp. has agreed to spend
$550 million to buy Viacom Inc.'s cable television properties in
Long Island, N.Y., and suburban Cleveland, which together have more
than 200,000 subscribers.
   Cablevision will also buy a 5 percent stake in Viacom's
Showtime-The Movie Channel for $25 million, the companies said
Tuesday.
   The sales will help Viacom reduce debt incurred last year in the
leveraged buyout under which it became 83 percent owned by National
Amusements Inc., which owns and operates about 425 movie screens.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   DeLaurentiis Entertainment Group
Inc., left floundering by a string of box office flops, filed for
protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of federal
bankruptcy laws.
   Tuesday's move had been expected since Friday, when the company
founded by Italian producer Dino DeLaurentiis revealed it had
failed to negotiate a debt swap with bondholders that it had termed
essential for survival.
   The company hasn't reported financial results for 1987, but has
announced estimates of a $69 million loss.
</TEXT>
