<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   08-17 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0535</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of a new venture involving the weekly
television supplements of 33 newspapers plan to challenge popular
TV Guide in a battle for advertising revenue.
   The venture, called TV Week Network, groups the newspapers in an
effort to attract national entertainment advertising with rates
competitive with TV Guide's. It is a joint venture of Tribune Media
Services, a subsidiary of Chicago-based Tribune Co., and Western
States Associates, an independent agency that represents newspaper
publishers.
   Representatives of TV Guide had no immediate comment on
Tuesday's announcement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. employees, armed with a
federal court order, began removing $1.7 million in military
components from Armtec Inc. in Palatka under the watchful eyes of
three federal marshals.
   While the packing and loading operation took place Tuesday,
about 25 former Armtec employees, who lost their jobs when Unisys
cancelled its contracts with Armtec, picketed outside.
   Both companies have come under scrutiny in a federal probe of
potential fraud and bribery in Pentagon weapons contacts, and
Armtec shut down earlier this month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers met privately to plan strategy on
behalf of farmers in 10 states who accuse Chubb Group of Insurance
Cos. of reneging on its duties to pay drought insurance claims.
   One lawyer involved in the Tuesday talks called the gathering an
``organizational meeting in an effort to have a united front.''
   A federal judge has granted class-action status to lawsuits
against Chubb, allowing eligible farmers nationwide to join a group
legal action against the Warren, N.J.-based company. Farmers still
can pursue independent litigation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. is impressing
customers, if not Wall Street, with new computers and appears on
the way to its goal of $10 billion in annual sales entering its
50th year of business in 1989.
   At a meeting of more than 2,000 customers in Florida last week,
Hewlett-Packard enjoyed a wealth of plaudits for its Spectrum line
of minicomputers.
   That wealth, though, hasn't yet affected Hewlett-Packard's stock
price, which plunged $1.50 a share Tuesday to a new low for the
year, $45.87{.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines expressed confidence that the
Department of Transportation will reverse a recommendation to pull
United's license on the lucarative Seattle-Tokyo route and award it
to rival American Airlines.
   ``Taking the route away from United, which has served it
faithfully for more than five years, is not in the best interests
of the United States and does not make sense,'' Stephen M. Wolf,
chairman of United's parent, UAL Inc., said Tuesday.
   His remarks came after Richard Walsh, director of the
Transportation Department's Office of Economics, recommended the
shift from United to American.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bargain-hunting investors rescued the stock market from another
decline Tuesday, boosting the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
17.24 points to close at 2,021.51.
   Both the dollar and long-term bond prices fell on the trade data
but managed to recover. Gold prices finished lower.
   Oil futures prices declined and grain and soybean futures closed
mostly lower.
</TEXT>
