<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Decline Ahead of Tuesday API Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures were weaker in quiet markets ahead
of an American Petroleum Institute report indicating a decline in
crude oil stocks during the past week.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, fell 12 cents a barrel to close at $15.49 a barrel on
Tuesday.
   Refined products traded on the exchange also rose. Contracts for
September delivery of wholesale heating oil decreased 0.24 cent to
finish at 44.03 cents a gallon, while September gasoline slipped
0.26 cent to 46.11 a gallon.
   Crude oil futures opened the day stronger than expected in thin
dealings, then eased off as traders awaited the American Petroleum
Institute's weekly report on oil inventories, analysts said.
   The report, released after the market closed, showed crude oil
stocks fll by 3.6 million barrels, gasoline inventories rose 1.5
million barrels and distillate stocks rose 1.4 million barrels in
the past week.
   Reports that ministers from the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries were talking of a November meeting did little
to spur Tuesday's energy prices, analysts said.
