<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SchererFight Bjt   08-17 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scherer Fight, Bjt,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Founder's Heirs Battle Scherer Management In Proxy Fight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lede prospects uncertain; meeting begins 2 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family feud over the future of R.P. Scherer
Corp. hinged on a proxy battle waged today at the capsule
manufacturing company's annual meeting.
   The proxy fight, the culmination of months of legal wrangling,
pitted Karla Scherer Fink, daughter of the company's founder, and
her brother against Peter Fink, her husband, who also is Scherer's
president and chief executive officer.
   Fink, who together with brother John S. Scherer controls about
38 percent of the company's stock, is seeking three seats on the
11-member board of directors to help further her push to sell off
the company, the world's biggest producer of gelatin capsules for
the pharmaceutical and vitamin industries.
   As the company's largest shareholder, Fink already is a board
member; her brother is up for re-election.
   Results of the vote were not expected to be known immediately.
   Fink has been pressing for some time to sell the company as a
means of disposing of her stake and maximizing shareholder value.
She reportedly filed for divorce in mid-May, about two weeks after
the board rejected her proposal to sell the company.
   ``The people who own the company should make this decision,''
John Scherer said in a statement last month. ``There are members of
management who obviously believe otherwise, for their own
self-serving reasons. They are wrong to think their harassment can
intimidate Karla into backing off.''
   In a July 28 letter to stockholders, Karla Fink and her brother
noted that Peter Fink and Scherer Chairman Wilbur H. Mack earned
more than $3 million between April 1, 1985, and March 31.
   ``In our opinion it is perfectly clear who are the real
beneficiaries of Scherer management's economic policy: the top
executives,'' the letter said.
   Peter Fink responded in a letter to shareholders that he was
dismayed by criticism over the very compensation his wife had
approved while serving as a Scherer director.
   He linked the company's strong performance to management skills
and urged shareholders to reject his wife's ``handpicked nominees.''
   Scherer reported net income of $12.8 million, up 44 percent in
the fiscal year ended March 31. Sales jumped 27 percent to $290.7
million.
   Karla Fink and her brother said the strong financial performance
made it an opportune time to sell the company, but Peter Fink said
the board was convinced that shareholders would be served best by
remaining independent.
   Still pending Tuesday before the Michigan Court of Appeals was a
ruling on stock carrying a potentially pivotal 9.3 percent of
Scherer's voting power.
   The court action involves a block of 470,000 shares in two
family trusts administered by Manufacturers National Bank. Karla
Fink and her brother, beneficiaries of the trusts, argued that
Manufacturers National Bank had conflicting interests.
   A probate court judge named an independent fiduciary on Monday
to decide how to vote on the stock, but Wayne County Circuit Judge
Kathleen MacDonald vacated that ruling Tuesday, reinstating the
bank as trustee and allowing it to vote the block at the annual
meeting.
   Attorneys for Karla Fink appealed the ruling to the state Court
of Appeals, said Beth Lyons, spokeswoman for the Mrs. Fink and her
brother.
   Troy-based Scherer employs about 2,800 people at 22 facilities
in 13 countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
