<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilWorkers     08-17 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Workers,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shortage of Offshore Oil Workers Could Threaten Gulf Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An upturn in the energy industry could pose a
serious labor problem for some oilfield services companies because
of a lack of experienced oil workers, industry officials say.
   A shortage of offshore oil workers already has developed in
parts of the Gulf of Mexico, officials said, but that problem could
spread industrywide if drilling increases.
   Ocean Oil Weekly Report said Monday that some offshore companies
could double their work load if they could find enough skilled
workers. The shortage of qualified personnel is ``threatening to
hamper the slight surge in drilling activity,'' the newsletter said.
   The decline of oil prices in the early 1980s forced layoffs that
drove oil-field employees into other businesses, and the depressed
wages now offered in the oil industry are not big enough to draw
them back, said Jim Redden, editor of the newsletter.
   Some rig laborer jobs earned $11 per hour on offshore platforms
in the early 1980s, compared with the $7 per hour they now are
paid, according to Ed McGhee of the International Association of
Drilling Contractors. Bargemasters who made $48,000 per year now
are being paid about $30,000.
   Zapata Gulf Marine had to mothball a few of its 98 supply
vessels working in the Gulf because of a lack of sailors and
maritime engineers, Zapata spokesman Barney White said Monday.
   ``We're really having a manpower crunch,'' he said. ``Last
month, we had three boats that we couldn't work because we didn't
have crews.''
   Zapata's recruiters have been working to locate maritime
personnel, White said. The company has maintained enough workers
for its six Gulf rigs by recalling former employees who had worked
on the two dozen rigs it operated in the Gulf several years ago, he
said.
   Most offshore drilling companies have enough roustabouts, tool
pushers, drillers and roughnecks, said McGhee.
   But if drilling were to increase sharply, the need for labor
would be great, he said. Divers, mechanics, electricians, welders,
pipefitters and boat hands are in short supply, Redden said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-High-TechExports     08-17 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-High-Tech Exports,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: Exports Growing Among Young High-Tech Firms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Over the next decade, exports by young
high-technology companies could help reduce the national trade
deficit, according to economists who unveiled a new survey of such
firms.
   ``As we evolve into a technology-driven type manufacturer,
...these companies do start exporting shortly after they are
born,'' James M. Howell, Bank of Boston's chief economist, said
Tuesday. ``In this environment, they can be substantial
contributors to exports.''
   The bank's survey of nearly 400 firms nationwide indicated many
high-tech firms are exporting soon after formation and not
experiencing a significant competitive disadvantage.
   High-tech companies, which are concentrated on the two coasts,
will play a significant role in job growth in the next five years
and could make ``a fairly substantial contribution'' to reducing
the foreign trade deficit by the mid-1990s, Howell said.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that the U.S. trade deficit
for June increased to $12.5 billion, a 28.5 percent increase over
May's $9.8 billion imbalance and the worst monthly figure since
February.
   The bank survey was mailed earlier this year to 6,539 companies
in the fields of biotechnology, advanced materials, photonic and
optics, automation and test and measurement.
   High-tech exporters formed during the 1980s with annual sales of
under $10 million have had about the same _ or in some cases faster
_ sales and employment growth rates as non-exporting firms, the
survey indicated.
   ``Most of the jobs in the country get created by young high-tech
companies growing up,'' Howell said. ``There's a difference between
a Digital (Equipment Corp.) growing up from the '50s to the '80s
and a corner drug store not growing at all.''
   The survey indicated sales increased by 50 percent and
employment by 23 percent among young export firms in the most
recent fiscal year, compared to 44 percent and 26 percent,
respectively, among non-exporting firms.
   Technology concentrations in the form of manufacturing firms and
research facilities are a major source of new development ``because
they serve as the spawning ground for entrepreneurs and as a
significant source of new products and processes,'' the survey said.
   The young exporters perceive Europe and Japan as their primary
sources of comptition, but in only one of the five fields did a
majority of companies think that competition is unfair. Sixty-seven
percent of test and measurement companies thought competition was
too stiff, compared to 22 percent in biotechnology and 18 percent
in photonic and optics.
   ``Gaining market share in a rapidly expanding global market is
viewed as being far more important than the fairness of the
marketplace,'' the survey said.
   `This finding strikes us as significant and suggests that the
current preoccupation with protectionism misses the mark,'' it
said. ``From a policy perspective, it will be more productive to
focus on the issue of creating a hospitable environment for
business starts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0291 </DOCNO>
