<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-17 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies in
moderately active European trading this morning, as bullish
sentiment overcame the effect of disappointing U.S. trade figures
for June.
   Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the market was surprised by the
dollar's quick recovery from the effects of the announcement that
the trade gap widened to $12.5 billion in June from a revised $9.8
billion in May.
   They attributed the recovery to bullish sentiment created by
relatively high U.S. interest rates and the conviction that the
U.S. administration wants a strong dollar at the time of the
November presidential election.
   ``The firmer dollar seems to be politically motivated, as the
Republicans want to use it for their electoral campaign,'' said
Gerhard Sunderdiek, client manager at Bank of America in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.07 yen to a closing 133.15 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 133.52 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8994 West German marks, up from 1.8705; 1.5973
Swiss francs, up from 1.5705; 6.4320 French francs, up from 6.3390;
2.1395 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1065; 1,406.35 Italian lire, up
from 1,384.50; 1.2295 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2275.
   In London, it cost $1.7000 to buy one pound, compared with
$1.7190 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $428.90 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $429. Both were down from Tuesday's late bid
of $431.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $428.85, down from $433 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $431.31, down from
Tuesday's $434.21.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.61 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.77.
</TEXT>
