<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Rally, Dollar Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices firmed on Tokyo's stock exchange
today, while the dollar edged up.
   After opening at 28,041.38, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a main barometer of the market, gained 282.31
points, or 1.01 percent, to close at 28,178.86 points.
   Total volume of both sections was 850 million shares, more than
three times as much as Tuesday's 260 million shares.
   Despite the $12.5 billion June U.S. trade deficit reported
Tuesday, share prices in New York, which stayed relatively high,
led the Tokyo market rebound, according to a stock dealer at a
major securities firm in Tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``Another reason of the dramatic change in Tokyo is that most of
the dealers who had been on Bon holidays returned to business
today,'' he said.
   Bon is an annual holiday when Japanese pay homage to their
ancestors.
   Rising issues were those related to steel, heavy machines and
electricity, while some of the precision machines-related stocks
dipped, the dealer added.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar opened at 133.17 yen,
ranged between 133.00 yen and 133.35 yen before closing at 133.15
yen, up 0.07 yen from the previous day's close.
   Spot trading totaled $5.2560 billion, up from Tuesday's $3.1420
billion.
