<2ND_LINE>British Stocks,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Mixed At Midday In Lackluster Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were mixed in lackluster trading at
midday Wednesday, with the market's near-term outlook clouded by
concerns about Britain's economy.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 2.9
points, or 0.2 percent, at 1,828.2 at about 12:30 p.m.
   Among the top 100 shares, 37 were higher, 34 were lower and 29
were unchanged.
   Volume was thin, with 171.3 million shares changing hands by
midday compared with 168.8 million shares at the same time Tuesday.
   Most shares languished in morning dealings, with activity
concentrated on a few, selected shares.
   Underlying the market's reticence to trade are concerns about
possible overheating in the British economy, highlighted by a
report by the Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development.
The report warned of ``renewed inflationary pressures'' in the
British economy.
   Many players suspect the market isn't going anywhere until these
fears about inflation are eased, dealers said.
   Volumes also were depressed as players remained a bit perplexed
by the market's rally late Tuesday, which came despite
worse-than-expected U.S. trade figures.
   ``Quite a few people were caught out by yesterday afternoon's
move,'' said one equity salesman.
