<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Maxicare     08-17 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maxicare,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maxicare Withdraws From Utah, Leaves 20,000 Subscribers Uninsured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxicare of Utah Inc. has announced it has
withdrawn from Utah, leaving its 20,000 health-care subscribers
uninsured.
   The announcement was made at a news conference Tuesday at which
officials of the health-maintenance organization said they were
ceasing immediately all health-care coverage in Utah.
   Harold C. Yancey, state commissioner of insurance, said he hoped
health care providers would honor Maxicare contracts until the
state can come up with a solution to the vacuum left by Maxicare's
sudden departure.
   Maxicare of Utah, which operated under the national corporate
umbrella of Maxicare Health Plans, opened its Utah operation in
January 1984.
   Yancey characterized Maxicare of Utah Inc. as being in an
``insolvent situation.''
   He said Utah officials will meet with 10 other health
maintenance organizations doing business in the state in the hope
that one or more will be able to cover Maxicare contracts.
   ``We're still holding meetings in the department to try and find
some coverage for all of the enrollees in Maxicare,'' Yancey said.
   ``We hope providers will continue to see their patients and
honor the agreements with Maxicare,'' the commissioner said. ``The
health providers are going to have to make a business decision....
(But) their claims may or may not be paid.''
   Yancey said state officials became aware of Maxicare's problems
last spring when a state financial examination of 1987 records
revealed the health maintenance organization was in trouble.
   He said the parent company had hoped eventually that the company
would be able to turn a profit in Utah.
   Maxicare's losses and the misfortune of other health maintenance
organizations in Utah are part of a nationwide problem, Yancey
said. ``It is not a unique Utah problem. HMOs all over the U.S. are
in dire trouble,'' he said.
   He said factors making it difficult for HMOs to make money
include escalating medical costs, exotic new treatments that are
costly, inadequate premiums and subscribers taking record numbers
of trips to the doctor.
   ``The customers are taking more advantage of their health care
than ever before,'' Yancey said.
</TEXT>
