<2ND_LINE>BC-France-US,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Critical Of U.S. Trade Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The French government, meeting at Cabinet level for
the first time since July 17, noted its ``extreme irritation''
Wednesday at the trade bill passed by the U.S. Congress.
   Government spokesman Claude Evin, speaking after the meeting,
said both President Francois Mitterrand and Premier Michel Rocard
manifested their irritation and accused the United States of
creating a new policy ``without international consultation.''
   ``France will not just limit itself to verbal condemnations,''
Evin said. ``The French ministers concerned (by the trade bill)
will have the occasion to examine the consequences of the decisions
taken in the United States.''
   The spokesman refused to discuss possible retaliatory measures.
He said the minister of agriculture was ``particularly concerned''
by the bill and noted that the Common Market has already termed it
protectionist.
   Among other things, the bill focuses unfair-trade investigations
on countries with consistent patterns of unfair trade practices.
