<1ST_LINE>u f BC-LaserFees 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Laser Fees, 1st Ld-Writethru,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Helps Settle Who Invented Laser</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT that Borman heads Patlex, sted
Spectra-Physics.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coherent Inc. has entered an agreement
that will end its status as one of the last holdouts in a
protracted patent fight over who invented the laser, the company
said.
   The Palo Alto-based company said Tuesday it will pay tiny Patlex
Corp., of Chatsworth, Calif., license fees on the sale of most of
Coherent's lasers.
   The agreement leaves Spectra-Physics Inc., of San Jose, as the
last major laser maker refusing to pay fees to Patlex.
   Patlex is headed by former Apollo astronaut and former Eastern
Airlines Chairman Frank Borman.
   The agreement with Patlex covers gas discharge lasers made by
Coherent, and it protects Coherent's customers from patent
infringement action by Patlex.
   Patlex, which would not disclose the terms of the agreement, has
asked for a 5 percent royalty from most laser makers.
   Coherent and Spectra-Physics are two of the world's leading
manufacturers of lasers.
   Patlex is a small laser company that has a 64 percent interest
in licensing income from patents it has secured over the years for
inventor Gordon Gould. Gould came up with a design for a laser in
the 1950s while he was a graduate student at Columbia University.
But much of the credit for the invention has gone to Charles
Townes, a former physics professor at Columbia who was a consultant
to Bell Laboratories, and Arthur Schawlow, then a Bell Laboratories
scientist.
   In October, the U.S. Patent Office gave Gould a patent for the
invention of the gas discharge laser.
</TEXT>
