<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GTECH-Mexico     08-17 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GTECH-Mexico,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GTECH Signs Contract To Expand In Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GTECH Corp., the world's largest lottery
concern, has signed a five-year contract with Mexico to triple the
size of its lottery operation there.
   The contract calls for the company to add 1,000 sales terminals
to Mexico's 500-terminal network, allowing the operation to expand
beyond Mexico City's borders.
   ``We hope this (recent contract) is just the first expansion
phase,'' said Victor Markowicz, GTECH's senior vice president of
international sales.
   GTECH would not comment on the contract's worth, citing
competitive considerations and a desire ``to protect customers'
proprietary information,'' he said.
   The existing contract generates annual revenues of $2 million to
$3 million, according to Cato Carpenter, an analyst with the
Baltimore-based Alex Brown & Sons.
   GTECH has disclosed the worth of other foreign contracts,
including Spain, $5 million to $10 million a year; Ontario, Canada,
$10 million; Sweden, just under $4 million and Australia, $4
million. GTECH also has contracts in Iceland and Ireland, but has
not disclosed their worth.
   The extra terminals will allow Pronosticos Deportivos para la
Asistencia Publica, which operates the Mexican lottery, to expand
to Guadalajara and other, still undertermined, cities, said
Markowicz.
   When GTECH installed its computer terminals in Mexico in June,
1987, it marked the first time Mexico's Lotto game had been
automated. About 20 percent of Mexican Lotto agents are outfitted
with GTECH terminals, said Markowicz. GTECH's terminals account for
about half of all Lotto sales in Mexico, he said.
   ``The growth of the game is highly attributable to our
terminals,''he said. ``We expect Mexico to absorb many more
terminals.''
   Mexico leases the terminals with the intention of purchasing
them at the end of each contract period. A Mexican subcontractor
operates the terminals.
</TEXT>
