<2ND_LINE>BC-Komatsu-Dresser,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Komatsu To Set Up Joint Venture With Dresser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Komatsu Ltd., the largest construction machinery
manufacturer in Japan, and Dresser Industries Inc., a leading oil
field service company in the United States, have signed a joint
venture agreement, a Komatsu spokesman said Wednesday.
   The contract, signed Monday in Chicago, establishes a joint
company to manufacture and sell construction machinery in the
United States, Canada and Latin America, said the spokesman,
Takashi Matsumura.
   The Komatsu Dresser Co., equally owned by the two parent
companies, will be headquartered in the Chicago suburb of
Libertyville, Ill.
   It plans to hire 5,000 workers at its headquarters and eight
plants in the United States, Canada and Brazil, Matsumura said.
   The company will begin operations on September 1, he said.
   ``It is part of our stragedy of globalization,'' Matsumura said.
``We have been aiming to set up a world-wide sales and production
network.''
   Matsumura also said the joint venture will help Komatsu minimize
the effects of exchange rate fluctuations.
   Total assets of the new company will be about $400 million, and
it hopes to generate sales of $1.5 billion the first year, the
spokesman said.
</TEXT>
