<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GMBoard     08-17 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM Board,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No More Rubber-Stamp Board at GM</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Objections by directors to some proposed changes
on the General Motors Corp. board and a retreat by Chairman Roger
B. Smith may show the auto company's management that board approval
can no longer be taken for granted.
   Smith was startled at a recent board meeting when outside
directors protested changes that would affect the makeup of the
board and stood their ground, The Wall Street Journal reported
today.
   GM's board ``isn't undercutting management,'' the newspaper
quoted a source close to the board as saying. ``But there's a
feeling that perhaps (the board) wasn't as involved in some past
decisions as it should have been.''
   One director was quoted as saying, ``There's no doubt that the
board has a sense of wanting to be less spoken to and more
consulted with. ... We are getting a little more ventilation in a
place where the windows haven't been open.''
   The discussion at the board's June 27 meeting did not involve a
major strategic decision for the company.
   Following a decision by Elmer W. Johnson, an executive vice
president and board member, to resign, Smith proposed a series of
executive changes.
   He wanted to name William E. Hoglund, Robert T. O'Connell and
John F. Smith Jr. as executive vice presidents and place them on
the board, as had been customary for executive vice presidents.
   But outside board members objected to replacing one inside
director with three, which would give management eight of 20 seats,
or 40 percent of the votes, rather than six of 18, or 33 percent.
   A compromise was worked out in which the three will sit at the
board table but without full director status.
   The original proposal never came to a vote. ``Roger's smart. He
can count,'' one director told the newspaper.
   Smith said Tuesday it would be improper to discuss the meeting,
but maintained the outside directors have long been active and
independent.
   ``I don't think they're more questioning or critical now than a
year ago,'' Smith said.
   GM President Robert Stempel, an inside director, acknowledged
plenty of discussion at the meeting, though he said, ``I don't want
to use the word `disagreement.' Our outside board members always
offer us counsel. They certainly in this matter have given us
copious advice.''
   Automatic support for management began to falter in 1984, when
GM acquired Electronic Data Systems Corp. and put its founder, H.
Ross Perot, on the board. Perot voted no the following year when GM
decided to acquire Hughes Aircraft Co.
   One possible area of increasing board involvement is the
question of tying executive pay more closely to results, which some
directors advocate.
   Another looming question is management succession, with Vice
Chairman Donald J. Atwood, who oversees GM's high-tech
subsidiaries, retiring next year and Smith scheduled to step down
in July 1990.
   Some directors said an atmosphere encouraging free discussion
was strengthened by the 1982 appointment of John G. Smale,
innovative chairman of Procter & Gamble Co., to the board, and the
1986 appointment of James D. Robinson III, chairman of American
Express Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-United-Japan     08-17 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-United-Japan,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Recommends DOT Reconsider United Route Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top official of the U.S. Department of
Transportation has ordered a lower level official of the department
to reconsider a recommendation that American Airlines replace
United Airlines on the lucrative Seattle-Tokyo route.
   Chicago-based United, the nation's largest airline, expressed
confidence Tuesday that the department will reverse the
recommendation on the trans-Pacific route which United has flown
since 1983.
   United became a major player in the Far East market in 1985
after acquiring Pan Am Corp.'s Pacific routes for $715 million in
what was then the largest airline route deal in history.
   But in April, DOT officials argued that United had diverted much
of its Tokyo traffic around Seattle to San Francisco and Los
Angeles. The department also said Fort Worth-based American has a
better financial base and its traffic pattern from the Midwest
would better serve the Seattle base.
   United has been flying the route since 1983, but its service is
under review as a condition of government approval of its purchase
of Pan Am's Pacific routes.
   ``Taking the route away from United, which has served it
faithfully for more than five years, is not in the best interests
of the United States and does not make sense,'' said United
Chairman Stephen M. Wolf.
   Wolf's remarks Tuesday came one day after Richard Walsh,
director of DOT's Office of Economics, recommended the route shift
from United to American, the second-largest U.S. carrier.
   Assistant Transportation Secretary Matthew Scocozza instructed
Walsh to review his recommendation in advance of the department's
final decision, expected in mid-September.
   Walsh's recommendation also contradicted a June 10 finding by
Administrative Law Judge Burton Kolko that United should retain the
route.
   American welcomed Walsh's recommendation.
   ``Obviously we're excited and delighted at the recommendation,''
said Al Becker, a spokesman for American. ``We think that we have
made the strongest case for the route.''
   Becker said American would spend ``many millions of dollars''
expanding its operation at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport to
1,700 employees, and would pump $400 million into the Seattle
economy annually if it won the route.
   The Seattle-Tokyo route is viewed by the airline industry as one
of the most prized in the expanding Pacific travel market.
   Northwest Airlines is the only other U.S. carrier allowed by
Japan to fly the route in competition with Japan Air Lines.
   The Japanese Ministry of Transport last year set a goal of
doubling the number of outbound Japanese travelers to 10 million by
1991. Many are expected to choose Seattle as their first U.S.
destination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
