<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Hewlett-Packard,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Giant Reports Earnings Rise 30 Percent In Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computer giant Hewlett-Packard Co. said
today its profits rose 30 percent in the third quarter, aided by
record orders for its electronics instruments.
   For the period ended July 31, the company reported after-tax
profits of $192 million, or 80 cents a share, up from $148 million,
or 57 cents a share, in the same period last year.
   Hewlett-Packard, the largest producer of electronic instruments
in the world, said its net revenue during the period rose 19
percent to $2.434 billion.
   Company president John A. Young noted the effort needed to match
the record high level of orders taken in the third quarter last
year.
   ``We met that challenge,'' he said. ``In fact, we set new
quarterly records for U.S. orders and for total orders.''
   For the nine months ending July 31, the company's net revenue
was up 23 percent to $7.122 billion, or $2.33 cents a share,
compared with $5.811 billion, or $1.65 a share, for the same period
in 1987.
   Orders for the nine-month period were $7.454 billion, up 19
percent from the $6.246 billion of a year ago.
</TEXT>
