<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UTC-Fraud     08-17 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UTC-Fraud,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Technologies Warns Shareholders on Defense Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigation of alleged fraud in
government defense contracts could harm the business United
Technologies Corp. does with the military, the company has told its
shareholders.
   United Technologies, which does about $4 billion worth of
business each year with the Defense Department, made the suggestion
in an Aug. 12 filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The company, based in Hartford, is one of about three dozen U.S.
defense contractors searched by federal agents investigating the
fraud allegations.
   ``If the corporation were charged with wrongdoing as a result of
the investigation, the corporation or its units could be suspended
as a government contractor,'' United Technologies said in its SEC
filing.
   The filing was made after the SEC warned companies under
investigation of their obligation to inform shareholders of
developments that might affect the companies' finances.
   United Technologies said in its filing that some of its
operating units were searched and received grand jury subpoenas in
the case. No one has been charged with wrongdoing.
   Also noted in the filing is that the investigation into
procurement practices has prompted the Defense Department to
require two United Technologies subsidiaries, Pratt & Whitney and
Norden Systems, to sign ``certification of business integrity''
when bidding on future government contracts.
   United Technologies and other defense contractors are seeking a
modification of the directive, which asks them to affirm they have
not obtained confidential bidding information.
   According to the SEC filing, the investigation and certification
requirement and the uncertainty they are creating in the defense
industry ``may adversely affect the corporation's ability to obtain
government business.''
   United Technologies spokeswoman Peg Hashem said Tuesday the
company thought the filing was ``appropriate'' because of the SEC's
advisory and the Defense Department's certification requirement.
   Charles Larson, a spokesman for the SEC in Washington, said the
commission didn't specifically request United Technologies to make
its filing in its standard financial document, called a Form 10-Q.
   ``I think some of the contractors are responding to our
statement that publicly traded companies have the responsibility to
put out full and timely information about the investigation,''
Larson said.
   Northrop Corp. of Los Angeles, another target of the Pentagon
investigation, also has made two public disclosures to its
shareholders through SEC filings. Larson said the SEC is not
keeping track of which other defense contractors have made similar
filings.
</TEXT>
