<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Lower On Slack Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop futures opened mostly lower today on the
Chicago Board of Trade as the market registered disappointment in
the slack global demand for U.S. grains and soybean products.
   With the end of the growing season approaching, the focus of
grain and soybean traders is gradually shifting from weather to
demand concerns, especially in exports, analysts said.
   In the corn market, which has recently been the leader among the
crop futures, ``there is very little near-term demand and nothing
to hold it in the short run,'' said Cathy Leow, a grain trader for
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   The approaching corn harvest traditionally brings lower corn
prices, she said, adding, ``I just look for the softness to
continue.''
   Cooler temperatures and showers were expected to reach the
drought-stricken Corn Belt on Thursday, which should give the
struggling soybean crop a break from record-setting heat.
   Wheat futures weakened on news the Agriculture Department had
rejected Egypt's bid for 250,000 metric tons of subsidized wheat.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 3 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.87{ a bushel; corn was 3{
cents to 5 cents lower with September at $2.82 a bushel; oats were
3 cents to 5{ cents lower with September at $2.74{ a bushel;
soybeans were 10 cents to 13 cents lower with August at $8.53 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent to .40 cent higher with August at
70.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .20 cent
higher with August at 81.85 cents a pound; hogs were .27 cent lower
to .28 cent higher with August at 46.90 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .70 cent higher with August at 34.40
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Tuesday while pork futures were
mostly lower.
</TEXT>
