<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DetroitNewspapers 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0018,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Challenges Detroit Newspaper JOA</HEAD>
<HEAD>EdsL Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE with start of hearing. Picks up
11th graf pvs, The lawsuit contends ... A version moving on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge was urged today to block the
partial merger of Detroit's daily newspapers by a lawyer who
contended that former Attorney General Edwin Meese III ignored the
law in approving the deal.
   William Schultz, representing Michigan Citizens for an
Independent Press, argued that neither the Detroit Free Press nor
the Detroit News could qualify as ``failing newspapers'' under the
law that allows joint operating agreements of dailies in the same
city.
   ``You have a situation where the two competing newspapers are in
a struggle for control and it's not at all clear who is going to
win,'' Schultz told U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green at a
hearing on his group's bid for a temporary restraining order.
   The two newspapers are scheduled to combine their commercial and
production facilities Thursday under a joint operating agreement
approved last week by Meese before he left office.
   The News, which is owned by Gannett Co., Inc., and the Free
Press, owned by Knight-Ridder, Inc., will maintain separate
editorial staffs but publish joint editions on weekends.
   The News, now a 24-hour paper, will publish evening editions
during the week.
   Schultz said Meese ignored an administrative law judge's finding
that neither paper was in danger of financial collapse. The
administrative law judge recommended against approval of the joint
operating agreement under an anti-trust exemption provided by the
Newspaper Preservation Act.
   Philip Lacovara, representing Knight-Ridder, said the partial
merger ``is the only solution to a bad situation.''
   Although the merger will result in 500 layoffs, 1,500 jobs would
be lost in Detroit if the Free Press closed its doors, Lacovara
said. Knight-Ridder had threatened to close the paper, which has
lost $56.2 million since 1980, if the joint operating agreement
were not approved.
   ``The Free Press cannot survive, cannot become profitable so
long as it is in commercial competition with the News,'' Lacovara
told the judge, who reserved decision on the injunction.
   ``The Free Press has no unilateral way out, the competitive
situation is such that it can't get in the black by unilaterally
raising its prices,'' Lacovara said.
   The plaintiffs, who include advertisers, a state senator, and
one part-time printer who was told he would no longer have a job
under the joint operating agreement, have also filed suit for a
permanent injunction against the merger.
   The suit filed Tuesday charged that Meese's order allowing the
joint operating agreement ``is arbitrary and capricious, contrary
to law, and not supported by substantial evidence'' that either
daily qualified as a ``failing newspaper'' under the Newspaper
Preservation Act.
   The merger ``will remove the beneficial effects of competition
on the quality (in terms of editorial coverage, diversity, and news
reporting) and is likely to cause a rise in the prices of
newspapers in the Detroit areas,'' the complaint said.
   The suit also said the combined operation will result in
increased advertising rates.
   The plaintiffs say Meese violated Justice Department regulations
by meeting with members of Michigan's congressional delegation in
June to discuss the newspaper merger.
   The lawsuit contends that Meese ignored recommendations by
Morton Needelman, the administrative law judge, that the losses by
both newspapers were the result of a marketing strategy designed to
drive the competition out of business or force creation of a joint
operating agreement.
   Needelman also found that the Free Press was not in a ``downward
spiral'' financially nor was it dominated by the News.
   The plaintiffs include Democratic State Sen. John F. Kelly and
Public Citizen, a consumer lobby organization founded by Ralph
Nader. Also joining the suit were W. Edward Wendover, a journalism
professor and publisher of the weekly Plymouth-Canton Community
Crier, and David A. Kersh, president of Metro Publications, Inc.,
which sells coupon books and advertises in the News.
</TEXT>
