<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   08-17 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Markets Respond Calmly To Jump In Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs on housing starts, stock market; picks up
2nd graf pvs, Tuesday's report ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction climbed 2.4 percent in July, the government
said today, but a companion report indicated that higher mortgage
rates may stifle the construction business in coming months.
   Building permits for future construction fell 5.4 percent, the
biggest decline since a 9 percent fall in January, the Commerce
Department said. Analysts said higher borrowing costs could be
discouraging the market.
   The Commerce Department said new homes and apartments were being
built at an annual rate of 1.49 million units in July. It was the
second consecutive monthly increase following a 4.4 percent rise in
June.
   Stocks weakened today after a higher opening, but brokers said
the market signaled no clear direction. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrial stocks, which partly recovered Tuesday from a
three-month low, was higher during much of the morning before
retreating and was down 5.68 points to 2,015.83 by noon EDT.
   On Tuesday, stocks, bonds and the dollar rose in spite of a
government report that the nation's merchandise trade deficit
widened to $12.5 billion in June.
   Tuesday's report caught the market off guard and hurt prices at
first, but investors eventually found reasons to be content with
the biggest trade gap since February.
   Investors also failed to be unnerved by a Federal Reserve report
that American industry operated at 83.5 percent of capacity in
July. That was the highest operating level in eight years, and
could be an indicator of rising inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 17.24 to
2,021.51 on Tuesday, recovering about half the loss it sustained
Monday in falling to a three-month low.
   The dollar, which lost more than 1 percent of its value right
after the trade report, finished the day with half-percentage point
gains against the British pound, West German mark and Japanese yen.
   Bond prices strengthened after morning losses, with the yield on
the bellwether 30-year Treasury bond dipping to 9.40 percent from
9.43 percent late Monday.
   The market's reaction was far more positive than in April, when
the Commerce Department's report of a $14.4 billion February
deficit contributed to a 101.46-point drop in the Dow Jones
industrial average.
   ``Basically, the trade number wasn't bad. It may not have been
spectacular, but it was quite all right,'' said Arnold Moskowitz,
senior vice president and economist for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Moskowitz said the deficit was not far above expectations
considering the wide fluctuations that are typical. And he said
some of the record imports that swelled the June deficit probably
should have been recorded in May, when the deficit was unexpectedly
low.
   Investors also were impressed with an upward revision in May
exports, which led to a reduction in the May deficit to $9.8
billion from $10.9 billion.
   The factory use report added to concerns that the economy is
overheating. But Moskowitz said recent Fed moves to raise interest
rates are beginning to cool off consumer spending, leaving slack
for export-driven industries to continue their expansion.
   ``This one-month jump in the trade deficit is not cause for
alarm,'' U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said in a
statement. ``Monthly numbers will always be erratic and it is more
instructive to focus on the long-term outlook.''
   Exports fell by 2.4 percent in June to a seasonally adjusted
$26.8 billion while imports surged to an all-time high of $39.4
billion.
   Even with the deterioration, the U.S. trade deficit for the
first six months of the year was running at an annual rate of $140
billion, down sharply from the record deficit of $170.3 billion set
in 1987.
  
</TEXT>
