<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GM-DefenseProbe     08-17 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GM-Defense Probe,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Filing: Government Probes GM Subsidiaries' Defense Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Justice Department is investigating
defense contracts awarded two General Motors Corp. subsidiaries, GM
has told the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   GM said in reports filed this week with the SEC that contracts
with its Electronic Data Systems Corp. and Hughes Aircraft Co. are
under investigation, according to GM spokesman Terry Sullivan.
   Publicly traded corporations are required to make such reports
to the SEC if they face potential liability.
   Roger Still, an EDS spokesman, said federal investigators are
probing allegations that some companies may have used secret
information supplied by consultants to win key contracts.
   But Still said federal attorneys have told EDS neither it nor
any of its employees are suspected of criminal activity.
   Hal Watkins, a Hughes Aircraft spokesman, said a federal grand
jury in Birmingham, Ala., is investigating charges that Hughes
employees did not furnish the Defense Department with all of the
information required by the federal government's truth in
contracting law in connection with a 1983 contract.
   Hughes' position is that neither it nor any of its employees
violated any law, Watkins said.
</TEXT>
