<2ND_LINE>BC-Ferrari-Fiat,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fiat To Raise Stake In Ferrari Following Founder's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fiat SpA said Wednesday it plans to raise its stake
in automaker Ferrari SpA following the recent death of founder Enzo
Ferrari.
   Fiat, which acquired a 50 percent stake in Ferrari in 1969,
holds an option to buy the 40 percent owned by Enzo Ferrari, who
died in Modena Sunday at the age of 90.
   Ferrari was ``by contract obligated'' to offer Enzo Ferrari's
shares to Fiat in the event Enzo had decided to sell his share or
in case of his death, a Fiat spokeswoman said.
   The remaining 10 percent would be left in the hands of Enzo
Ferrari's son, Lardi Ferrari.
   The Fiat spokeswoman said procedural details and financial terms
would be discussed at a meeting early next month between the
Ferrari family and Fiat officials.
   Ferrari, which produces nearly 4,000 luxury and sport cars a
year, posted a profit of 14.8 billion lire, or around $10.5
million, in 1987 on sales of 360 billion lire, or $257 million.
</TEXT>
