<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Construction,0426</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Housing Construction Down In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Housing Starts Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer housing units were built during the second
quarter of 1988 than a year ago, reflecting continued softness in
the rental housing market, a research group reported Wednesday.
   For the April-June period, new housing construction slipped 9
percent to 406,882 units, compared with 446,955 units built during
the second quarter of 1987, said the F.W. Dodge Group of
McGraw-Hill Information Services Co.
   The report followed the release of Commerce Department
statistics saying housing construction climbed 2.4 percent in July,
to an annual rate of 1.49 million units. That was the second
consecutive monthly increase, following a 4.4 percent rise in June.
   ``Latest data reveal that housing activity has receded to only
three-quarters of its peak volume reached in 1986 when apartment
construction was being subsidized by tax incentives,'' said George
A. Christie, chief economist for F.W. Dodge, which reports
regularly on construction activity.
   Christie said most of the decline has been in rental housing,
where high vacancy rates have hindered new apartment construction.
   Construction of one-family homes has remained steady, Christie
said.
   Only six of the nation's 25 most active housing markets posted
gains in the quarter, the report said.
   Here are the 25 most active housing areas, the number of new
residential units and the percentage change from the second
quarters of 1987:
   _Riverside-San Bernardino, Calif., 15,615, up 57 percent.
   _Washington, D.C., 12,733, down 22 percent.
   _Los Angeles, 12,527, down 16 percent.
   _Atlanta, 12,381, up 13 percent.
   _Detroit, 8,117, up 29 percent.
   _Las Vegas, Nev., 6,973, up 91 percent.
   _Chicago, 6,510, down 31 percent.
   _San Diego, 6,462, down 25 percent.
   _Philadelphia, 6,105, up 2 percent.
   _Minneapolis-St. Paul, 6,087, down 14 percent.
   _Phoenix, Ariz., 5,974, down 17 percent.
   _Tampa-St. Petersburg-Clearwater, Fla., 5,369, down 16 percent.
   _Anaheim-Santa Ana, Calif., 5,151, down 11 percent.
   _Orlando, Fla., 5,130, up 4 percent.
   _West Palm Beach-Boca Raton-Delray Beach, Fla., 4,833, down 22
percent.
   _Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood-Pompano Beach, Fla., 4,721, down 1
percent.
   _Sacramento, Calif., 4,661, down 21 percent.
   _Miami, 4,494, down 21 percent.
   _Boston, 4,334, down 6 percent.
   _Seattle, 4,045, down 5 percent.
   _Baltimore, 3,840, down 3 percent.
   _Norfolk-Virginia Beach-Newport News, Va., 3,832, down 4 percent.
   _Oakland, Calif., 3,644, down 34 percent.
   _Columbus, Ohio, 3,436, down 3 percent.
   _St. Louis, 3,394, down 25 percent.
