<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KodakUnit     08-17 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kodak Unit,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Decides to Keep Business That Sells Lysol, D-Con And Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. has decided to keep the
household products group it acquired in the $5.1 billion
acquisition of Sterling Drug Co., company officials said Wednesday.
   Kodak concluded the Lehn & Fink unit of Sterling, which sells
Lysol disinfectant, D-Con rat poison and other well-known products
``is too important to lose,'' said Kay Whitmore, Kodak's president
and executive officer.
   In recent weeks, published reports and rumors on Wall Street
indicated that Kodak planned to sell the Montvale, N.J.-based unit,
which had sales of $594 million last year.
   ``I'm not surprised they're keeping it,'' said Mark Obenzinger,
an analyst with Wood, Gundy & Co. in New York. ``They couldn't get
the price they wanted. They paid top dollar for it, so they have to
get top, top dollar for it.''
   Eugene Glazer, an analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New
York, agreed, noting that one reason Kodak needed to hang a higher
pricetag on the unit was to cover a hefty tax that would have been
levied on the deal.
   Tax law changes in 1986 make it more expensive for companies to
buy another firm and sell off the unwanted parts of it, Glazer said.
   Because of the new law, Kodak would have to pay ``hundreds of
millions'' of dollars in taxes if it sold Lehn & Fink, he said.
   While Lehn & Fink still does not fit into Kodak's strategic
plans, analysts said it's a successful and well-run company that
won't hurt Kodak's bottom line.
   Whitmore told Lehn & Fink employees Wednesday he envisioned Lehn
& Fink marketing products developed by Kodak's chemical division;
Kodak using its strength in convenience store outlets to get Lehn &
Fink products onto more store shelves; and Kodak helping market
Lehn & Fink's products overseas.
   Kodak bought Sterling Drug Co. for $5.1 billion earlier this
year as a ``white knight'' for Sterling, which was trying to avoid
a hostile takeover attempt by Swiss multinational pharmaceutical
giant F. Hoffman-LaRoche & Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
