<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-17 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Close Lower; Soybeans Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT soybean price range</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures closed mostly lower Wednesday while
most soybean contracts advanced in a fourth day of volatile trading
on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   ``There's no rhyme or reason to it, necessarily,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``It's just the
same choppy pattern we've seen last several days and I think we're
going to continue in this vein.''
   With the end of the growing season approaching, grain and
soybean traders are paying more attention to global demand factors
than the weather's effects on supplies, analysts said.
   In the corn market, which has recently been the leader among the
crop futures, ``there is very little near-term demand and nothing
to hold it in the short run,'' said Cathy Leow, assistant
vice-president in charge of grain futures trading for Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc.
   Export demand for wheat and soybean products also has been
slack, possibly because of high prices linked to the summer-long
drought, Lespinasse said.
   ``High prices discourage demand, so that's been a drag on the
market,'' he said. ``Lower prices will enhance demand. Maybe that's
what the market's trying to tell us.''
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 3{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.90 a bushel; corn was 2
cents lower to 3\ cents higher with September at $2.85 a bushel;
oats were 4 cents to 7{ cents lower with September at $2.70{ a
bushel; soybeans were 7 cents lower to 16 cents higher with August
at $8.77 a bushel.
</TEXT>
