<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BizWeekProbe     08-17 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biz Week Probe,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Connecticut Stockbroker Pleads Guilty to Wire Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Merrill Lynch & Co. stockbroker
pleaded guilty Wednesday to engaging in a scheme in which he
illicitly obtained advance copies of Business Week, then reaped
profits from trading stocks mentioned in the magazine.
   William Dillon, 33, who was dismissed last month from Merrill
Lynch's New London, is the first person to be criminally charged in
the widening insider-trading scandal involving leaked copies of
Business Week.
   In a 25-minute hearing before U.S. District Judge Ellen Burns,
Dillon pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud. As part of a plea
agreement, he is cooperating fully with investigators.
   The government said Dillon paid $10 to $30 for advance copies of
the business magazine to various emoloyees of R.R. Donnelley & Sons
Co., which prints the weekly publication at two plants, including
one in nearby Old Saybrook.
   Dillon, of Old Lyme, acknowledged that he bought non-public
copies of the magazine on Thursday mornings between late 1986 and
July 1988. The publication is released to the public after the
markets close on Thursdays.
   According to prosecutors, he bought stock in about 129 companies
mentioned favorably in the ``Inside Wall Street'' column, then sold
the securities after the magazine was made public and prices rose.
   Dillon did not make any statements during his brief court
appearance and would not discuss the case outside the courtroom.
   He was freed on a $5,000 bond and was scheduled to be sentenced
Oct. 12.
   The government contends that Dillon made about $94,000 through
the illegal activity.
   Some of the profits were made through a trading account in the
name of a yet unidentified person who engaged in the activity with
Dillon, prosecutors said.
   Dillon's mother, Elizabeth Baird, maintained an account through
which some trades were made based on the information from Business
Week, the government said.
   Neither Baird nor Dillon's wife, Diana Dillon, who worked
briefly at Donnelley, will face any charges as a result of his plea
bargain.
   Both Dillon and his mother will be required to turn over all
profits realized through the scheme to the government, prosecutors
said.
   The U.S. attorney's office last week announced that Dillon would
plead guilty and cooperate with investigators in the probe that has
extended to a number of brokerage houses.
   R.R. Donnelley has fired five employees from its Old Saybrook
plant and one from its Torrance, Calif., facility. Another
Donnelley employee resigned.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Peter Jongbloed said Dillon usually held
his shares less than one week before cashing them in for profit.
Dillon also admitted tipping off others to information he illicitly
obtained, the government said.
   In the complaint to which Dillon pleaded guilty Wedneday, he was
charged with using wire communications on Sept. 24, 1987, to
purchase 8,000 shares of the common stock of Valhi Inc.
   Jongbloed said Dillon sold the shares four days later for a
profit of more than $10,000.
   Dillon also has agreed to plead guilty Sept. 6 to another wire
fraud count, stemming from the same scheme, in U.S. District Court
in New York.
   Prosecutors said they would recommend that Dillon serve
sentences for the Connecticut and New York charges concurrently.
The wire fraud charge carries a maximum penalty of five years in
prison and a $250,000 fine.
   Dillon's attorney, Henry Putzel, said Wednesday ``there may be
some small facts we quibble with,'' but he said his client
acknowledged that the government's evidence was strong enough to
lead to a conviction if he were tried.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0329 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Texaco Bjt   08-17 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texaco, Bjt,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Institutions Pushing for Stronger Role in Texaco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two big institutional shareholders in Texaco
Inc. want a voice in nominating directors to Texaco's board, and
some analysts said Wednesday the move could run into stiff
resistance from Texaco management.
   Officials of the California Public Employee Retirement System
and the New York State Employees Retirement Fund will ask for a
formal, long-term role in choosing Texaco directors. They plan to
make the request at a meeting on Aug. 24 with Texaco President
James W. Kinnear, said Richard Koppes, general counsel of the
California fund.
   The New York pension holds 3 million Texaco shares and the
California fund has 783,000 of the company's 244.3 million shares
outstanding. The California system is the largest public employee
pension fund in the country with more than $46 billion in assets,
while the New York fund controls $39 billion.
   Two seats on the Texaco board are expected to open within the
next year. The two pension funds want institutional shareholders in
Texaco to be permanently represented on the board's nominating
committee by ``independent'' delegates who are neither executives
nor shareholders.
   The two funds are not seeking to place direct representatives on
the board's nominating committee, Koppes said, since they would get
access to confidential information about Texaco that could conflict
with their fiduciary responsibilities as money managers.
   The pension officials could be tempted to buy or sell Texaco
stock on the basis of that information _ and probably would have to
give up the right to trade the stock before joining the board.
   ``This could very well be an important development for all of
corporate America,'' said Rosario Ilacqua, vice president of equity
research at the investment firm Nikko Securities Co. International
Inc.
   Texaco declined comment on the issue. Anita Larsen, a
spokeswoman at the company's headquarters in White Plains, N.Y.,
would only reiterate Kinnear's recent public promise to meet with
representatives of the institutional investors.
   Texaco emerged from bankruptcy court reorganization in April
after filing the largest Chapter 11 petition in U.S. corporate
history.
   In its successful proxy battle in June with Texaco's largest
shareholder, financier Carl C. Icahn, management won the support of
the California and New York pension funds by promising to consider
their request for a voice in nominating directors.
   The shareholders' proposal ``probably makes some sense ... but
it does present a lot of problems,'' said Bruce Lazier, an analyst
at the investment firm Prescott, Ball & Turben Inc.
   The pension funds _ and Texaco management _ might be more likely
to accept a special advisory role for the big shareholders that was
below the level of board representation.
   But even that may be difficult, some observers said.
   ``Texaco's record has not been very good'' regarding its
treatment of shareholders, Ilacqua said, although he conceded
management had turned something of a new leaf since the bankruptcy
and had been forced to become more responsive under pressure from
Icahn.
   If the pension funds succeed, it would mark a major,
ground-breaking victory for institutional shareholders seeking a
bigger say in how corporations are run.
   Institutional shareholders have scored similar _ but less
ambitious _ successes this year at Aluminum Company of America,
General Mills Inc., Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing Co., Sara Lee
Corp. and Loral Corp.
   Koppes, the California fund's general counsel, acknowledged that
there was pessimism about the two big shareholders' prospects for
success in their initiative. He said he remained optimistic,
however.
   ``We're confident. Mr. Kinnear has publicly promised to engage
in meaningful dialogue on this and we expect that will happen,''
Koppes said in a phone interview from his office in Sacramento,
Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880817-0330 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OilDemand     08-17 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Demand,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Demand Slips In July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demand for petroleum products declined in July
along with a falloff in domestic crude oil production, but imports
reached their highest level in about a year, the American Petroleum
Institute reported Wednesday.
   According to the Institute's Monthly Statistical Report,
deliveries of petroleum products, a key measure of demand, fell 2.3
percent to an average 16.7 million barrels a day when compared with
year-ago figures.
   ``Despite continued growth in both the economy and in highway
travel, July's limp gasoline deliveries ... continued the no-growth
patternof the second quarter,'' the Washington-based institute said.
   But API noted that deliveries strengthened consistently as the
month progressed, ``indicating fairly healthy deliveries by
month-end.''
   Domestic crude oil production fell 1.2 percent from the year-ago
period to an average 8.2 million barrels a day.
   Despite the drop in crude production, the institute noted that
the production of natural gas liquids averaged 1.6 million barrels
a day. Natural gas liquids account for about 10 percent of the
nation's petroleum supplies.
   The institute noted that the average 7.3 million barrels a day
in imported petroleum goods during July ``came close to last July's
recent-year record.'' The United States is dependent upon imports
for nearly 44 percent of its oil needs.
   In other highlights, the institute reported:
   _Total inventories were up 1.3 percent from June and were 6.3
percent higher than in the year-ago period.
   _The nation's refineries continued to operate at high levels,
reaching 86.9 percent of capacity in July.
   For the first seven months of the year, imports were up a hefty
11.3 percent while demand was up 1.7 percent over the 1987 period.
Crude production was down during the period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
