<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-17 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Despite Central Bank Intervention; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged against major foreign
currencies Wednesday as the U.S. and West German central banks
tried with partial success to limit its climb against the West
German mark.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   The dollar's strength continued to confound market players who
had expected the currency to fall after Tuesday's report that the
U.S. trade deficit had expanded more than expected in June.
   The Federal Reserve and the West German central bank knocked the
dollar below 1.9 marks by concerted dollar selling in morning New
York trading, but investors carried it back up, forcing the Fed to
intervene again in the afternoon, said Angelo Mazzeo, an assistant
vice president at European American Bank in New York.
   The dollar's jerky movements were costly to some traders, Mazzeo
said. ``It was ugly yesterday and it was ugly again today,'' he
said.
   Relatively high interest rates in the United States continued to
attract investors to dollars, said Shani Shamah, a corporate trader
at Nomura Bank International.
   Although the trade deficit widened to $12.5 billion in June,
traders were impressed that the gap for May was revised downward to
$9.8 billion from an originally reported $10.9 billion.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar rose 0.07 yen to a closing 133.15 yen. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 134.05 yen. At the end of the day in New York, the
dollar rose to 134.01 yen from 133.73 late Tuesday.
   In London, the dollar soared against the British pound. It cost
$1.6905 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7190 late Tuesday. Later
in New York, it cost $1.6913 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7038
late Tuesday.
   The dollar peaked briefly at 1.9165 West German marks in New
York before settling at 1.9098 marks, up from 1.8894 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's rates, included: 1.6040 Swiss francs, up from 1.5872;
1.2313 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2276; 6.4660 French francs, up
from 6.4035; and 1,412.50 Italian lire, up from 1,399.45.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.9123 West German marks, up from 1.8705; 1.6025
Swiss francs, up from 1.5705; 6.4750 French francs, up from 6.3390;
2.1550 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1065; 1,401.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,384.50; and 1.2323 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2275.
   In Hong Kong, gold dropped to $431.31 an ounce from $434.21.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $428.50 a troy ounce,
compared with Tuesday's bid of $431.25. In Zurich, gold closed at a
bid $428.50 an ounce, down from $433 Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $431 a troy ounce from $428.90 Tuesday. Republic
National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $430.40 a troy ounce
as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $428.80 an ounce late Tuesday.
   Silver bullion prices fell in London to a late bid price of
$6.62 a troy ounce, compared with Tuesday's $6.77. On New York's
Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose to $6.647 an ounce
from $6.610.
</TEXT>
