<HEAD>Armtek Rejects Unsolicited Tender Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armtek Corp.'s board of directors
Wednesday rejected as inadequate an unsolicited $490 million
takeover offer from Mark IV Industries Inc. and urged shareholders
not to tender their shares.
   ``The board beleives that the company's remaining independent
would be a superior alternative ...,'' Armtek said in a prepared
statement.
   Mark IV recently offered $40 a share in cash for all of Armtek's
outstanding shares and associated preferred stock purchase rights.
   Armtek, formerly known as Armstrong Rubber Co., is a supplier of
engineered drive and heat exchange systems, modules and components.
It had $1.2 billion in sales last year.
   Two month ago, Armtek sold its largest unit, Armstrong Tire Co.,
to Pirelli Group, an Italian tire maker, for $197 million, capping
a corporate restructuring.
   Mark IV, based in Amherst, N.Y., produces technical,
professional audio equipment and aerospace products. The company
had 1987 sales of $292 million.
</TEXT>
