<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices finished mostly lower
Wednesday in dull trading.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, edged down 2 cents a barrel to close at $15.47. Other
contract months also posted marginal losses.
   A barrel is equivalent to 42 gallons.
   Futures prices of oil products traded on the exchange also fell.
Contracts for September delivery of wholesale heating oil slipped
0.10 cent to finish at 43.93 cents a gallon. September gasoline
rose 0.51 cent to 46.62 cents a gallon, but most other gasoline
contract months declined.
   Analysts said the declines were caused mainly by technical
market factors rather than any fresh news developments.
   ``The oil market is in the complete doldrums right now,'' said
Chris McCormack, an energy futures broker for Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   He said oil prices were unaffected by a report late Tuesday that
U.S. crude stocks fell by 3.6 million barrels, gasoline inventories
rose 1.5 million barrels and distillate stocks rose 1.4 million
barrels in the past week. The weekly data were compiled by the
American Petroleum Institute, an industry group based in Washington.
   The API data ``were really kind of a non-event,'' McCormack said.
   The market was similarly unimpressed by the API's monthly report
published Wednesday showing that demand for petroleum products
declined in July but imports reached their highest level in about a
year.
</TEXT>
