<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Hewlett-Packard     08-17 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Hewlett-Packard,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard Earnings Rise 30 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. said Wednesday its
profit rose 30 percent in its third fiscal quarter, but its stock
continued to fall.
   Analysts expressed concern about the quality of the computer
maker's earnings, noting the company benefited significantly from a
reduction in its tax rate from earlier this year that exaggerated
its results.
   ``On first blush their earnings look very nice to investors, but
people are looking at the quality,'' said Adam Cuhney of Kidder,
Peabody, Inc. ``The higher the quality, the more they're willing to
pay for the stock.''
   Hewlett-Packard's stock, which reached new lows for the year
Monday and again Tuesday, fell again, dropping $1.12{ a share to
$44.25 a share in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Earnings rose to $192 million, or 80 cents a share, from $148
million, or 57 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose about 19
percent to $2.43 billion from $2.05 billion.
   Analysts have been looking closely at whether Hewlett-Packard is
moving ahead in U.S. orders as it rolls out its new Spectrum line
of computers based on RISC _ reduced instruction-set computing _
technology.
   U.S. orders totaled $1.20 billion in this year's third quarter,
an increase of less than 1 percent. International orders, which are
more profitable because of the dollar conversion, rose 27 percent
to $1.33 billion. Overall, the $2.53 billion in orders amounted to
a 13 percent increase from the $2.24 billion in the corresponding
quarter last year.
   ``We are particularly pleased with the growth in international
orders,'' John A. Young, the president and chief executive, said in
a statement. ``Europe and the Asia Pacific region both are
generating high order levels as the major economies in these areas
continue to show solid growth.
   ``Though our U.S. order growth rate has moderated, there
continues to be strength in the domestic economy, particularly in
capital spending,'' he said. ``This offers us opportunities in the
months ahead.''
   Hewlett-Packard has been trying to reach $10 billion in annual
sales as it enters its 50th year in 1989, but it would have to have
a spectacular fourth quarter to reach that mark. In 1987,
Hewlett-Packard posted $8.1 billion in revenue.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, profits rose 35
percent to $573 million, or $2.33 a share, from $426 million, or
$1.65 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 23 percent to $7.12
billion from $5.81 billion.
</TEXT>
