<HEAD>Reports Fourth Quarter Loss of $5.1 Million But Gain for Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playboy Enterprises Inc. reported a
fourth-quarter loss Wednesday but managed a modest profit for the
fiscal year.
   For the three months ended June 30, Playboy said it lost $5.1
million, compared with a gain of $7.04 million or 75 cents a share
in the year-earlier period. Sales totaled $37.78 million vs. $43.40
million, a 12.9 percent drop.
   For the year, Playboy said it made $2.6 million or 28 cents a
share, a 77 percent drop from the year-earlier profit of $11.1
million or $1.18 a share. Sales totaled $159.84 million vs. $161.76
million, a 1 percent decline.
   In a statement, the company blamed the lower profits on
continued losses by its Video Group. It also said the year-earlier
figure was inflated by the sale of ``Games'' magazine and two
paintings from the company's art collection.
   The Video Group has been restructured in a strategy to make the
company profitable by the end of the next fiscal year. Its new
service, called ``Night Life,'' will feature R-rated films and
exclusive programming, said Christie Hefner, president and chief
operating officer of Playboy Enterprises.
</TEXT>
