<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 1812EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-17 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugar Futures Sink To 2-Month Low On Rising Supplies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar futures prices sank below 10 cents a pound for the first
time in two months Wednesday on New York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa
Exchange amid signs of rising world supplies.
   On other markets, crop futures were mixed; livestock and meat
were mostly higher; precious metals gained; energy futures were
narrowly mixed; and stock-index futures were unchanged.
   Sugar for October delivery plunged 0.63 cent to 9.86 cents a
pound, the lowest closing price for near-term delivery since June
16, when the July contract finished at 9.69 cents a pound.
   The price for October sugar has fallen nearly 37 percent in the
past month after reaching a seven-year high of 15.30 cents a pound
on July 19.
   Sugar futures had rallied on increased Asian buying after China
moved to increase the availabilty of the sweetener to its citizens,
analysts said. But Far Eastern buying stalled in mid-July, and
futures prices have slipped steadily lower as the near-term supply
picture improved.
   Analysts said Wednesday's selloff was rooted in a French
agency's estimate that the current European sugar-beet crop would
produce 13.51 million metric tons of sugar, compared with last
year's 12.8 million metric tons. The same agency had previously
estimated a 200,000-metric-ton decline in European sugar production.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. Department of Agriculture reported Wednesday
that mainland U.S. sugar production for the first half of 1988
totaled 2.4 million tons, a 2 percent increase from the same period
a year ago. Hawaiian sugar production for the same period rose 6
percent to 419,000 tons, the USDA said.
   Grain futures closed mostly lower while most soybean contracts
advanced in a fourth day of see-saw trading on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   ``There's no rhyme or reason to it, necessarily,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``It's just the
same choppy pattern we've seen last several days and I think we're
going to continue in this vein.''
   With the end of the growing season approaching, grain and
soybean traders are paying more attention to global demand factors
and less attention to the weather's impact on supplies, analysts
said.
   Export demand for corn, wheat and soybean products has been
slack, possibly because of high prices linked to the summer-long
drought, Lespinasse said.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents lower to \ cent higher with September at
$3.90\ a bushel; corn was 2\ cents lower to 3 cents higher with
September at $2.84} a bushel; oats were 4} cents to 7 cents lower
with September at $2.70{ a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents lower to
15 cents higher with August at $8.77 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in reaction to unexpectedly strong cash cattle
and beef markets, said Charles Richardson, a livestock market
analyst with Lind-Waldock & Co. in Denver.
   Live cattle settled .50 cent to 1.30 cents higher with August at
70.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .57 cent higher
with August at 82.25 cents a pound; hogs were .22 cent lower to .63
cent higher with August at 46.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent to .83 cent higher with August at 34.70 cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures rose slightly in a late rally fueled by
technical factors in a thin market, analysts said.
   Gold settled $2.10 higher across the board with October at
$435.10 a troy ounce; silver was 3 cents to 3.7 cents higher with
September at $6.665 a troy ounce.
   Crude-oil futures fell slightly while oil products were mixed in
very light trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to 8 cents
lower with September at $15.47 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent
to .30 cent lower with September at 43.93 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .25 cent lower to .51 cent higher with September at
46.62 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures were virtually unchanged on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of
the Standard & Poor's 500 index settled at 261.25 points.
