<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mexico-Japan     08-17 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Japan,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Says It Wants To Help Mexico Solve Debt Crunch</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Seiichi in 10th graf is correct</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan will increase investment in Mexico,
import more Mexican goods and ``seriously consider'' Mexican
proposals for reducing its massive foreign debt, Japanese officials
said Wednesday.
   They praised Mexico's attempt to restructure its economy and
said Japan, one of the world's mightiest creditors and exporters,
looks forward to increasing imports of Mexican goods.
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno singled out Mexico's
inflation-fighting plan, the Economic Solidarity Pact, for special
praise, saying it ``impressed me considerably.''
   The pact between government, business and labor to restrain
prices and wages is credited with reducing sharply the record 159.2
percent inflation Mexico suffered last year.
   Uno spoke in Japanese through a Spanish translator at a news
conference the day after meeting with President Miguel de la Madrid
and his successor, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, winner from the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party of the July 6 presidential
election.
   Uno arrived Monday for a four-day visit.
   He said Japan plans to increase its imports from all Pacific
Basin countries and places a high priority on the debt crisis in
Latin America.
   The foreign minister said Japan will seriously consider various
Mexican proposals for reducing its $104-billion foreign debt, the
largest in the developing world after Brazil's. Japan and Japanese
banks hold about 17 percent of Mexico's debt.
   When asked if Japan would forgive Mexico of interest on any of
its debt, Uno said it would be difficult to make an exception for
Mexico. But he also said Japan hadn't ruled out the idea.
   Later, Seiichi Kondo, a Japanese Foreign Ministry spokesman
traveling with Uno, told The Associated Press that Japan will
likely increase investment in assembly plants along the
U.S.-Mexican border. He said more than 40 Japanese firms already
have such plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
