<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-IBMPCs     08-17 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM PCs,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM To Bring Back Version Of Old Personal Computer, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. may be
planning to bring back a version of its old personal computer in a
move reminiscent of Coca-Cola Co.'s introduction of Coke Classic.
   The new computer would be based on the PC AT, which IBM
abandoned as it shifted production over to its new Personal
System-2 line of computers, according to the trade journal PC Week.
   As with Coca-Cola, IBM would be bringing back the older product
because of customer demand. IBM would continue to sell its new
Personal System-2 line, just as Coca-Cola sells New Coke.
   IBM has refused to comment on the report, and some analysts are
skeptical IBM would go back to an older model of PC. Stewart Alsop,
editor of P.C. Letter, said: ``It would kind of give the lie to
everything they've been saying.''
   Companies such as Compaq Computer Corp. and Tandy Corp. that
continued to make computers based on the old IBM standard have
enjoyed booming sales.
   Meanwhile, IBM's share of the personal computer market has
slipped since the April 1987 announcement of the Personal System-2
line. Its old PC AT computer continued to be popular even as the
company was phasing it out.
   PC Week said the new machine would be called the Model 35. It
would reportedly use the old design but have some of the features
of the new machine, such as better graphics. The price would be
between $2,000 and $3,000.
</TEXT>
