<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Maxicare-HMOs     08-17 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maxicare-HMOs,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Other HMOs Step In To Take Over Maxicare Clients In Utah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially sound health maintenance
organizations will step in to provide medical coverage to 20,000
people served by Maxicare Utah Inc., which is shutting down its
operations here.
   State Insurance Commissioner Harold C. Yancey said Wednesday
that all of the existing HMOs in Utah plan to contact and try to
enroll Maxicare accounts. He said Maxicare clients should
experience no lapse in coverage.
   On Tuesday, Maxicare's board of directors, citing losses of $5
million in the past five years, announced the closure of the health
plan's operations in Utah.
   Maxicare accounts that are not enrolled in other programs by
month's end will be apportioned on a pro rata basis to active HMOs,
Yancey said.
   ``They (HMOs) have agreed to take over a very serious problem,
and frankly I salute them for the action they have taken because
they have been good citizens and recognized this is the best thing
for everyone concerned,'' the commissioner said.
   Yancey said some of Maxicare's outstanding bills ultimately will
end up in the liquidation process and be apportioned.
   It is unknown if the department will dip into the state's
insurance guarantee fund, of which HMOs are members. The purpose of
the fund is to cover claims of insolvent member insurance agencies
that are no longer able to pay those claims.
   State officials say that while 11 HMOs are licensed in Utah,
only eight are active.
   Maxicare operates in Salt Lake, Utah, Davis, Weber and Summit
counties. The closure affects only Utah and not any of the other 35
states where the HMO does business.
</TEXT>
