<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Peru-MineStrike     08-17 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Mine Strike,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peru Miners Approve Pact To Settle Month-Long Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking miners ratified a government
agreement Wednesday to end a crippling month-long walkout and
return to work, a labor official said.
   More than 150 delegates from miners unions across Peru approved
a back-to-work agreement hammered out late Tuesday between top
government and strike officials, said Saul Cantoral, secretary
general of the leftist-led Federation of Mine, Metal and Steel
Workers.
   Cantoral, whose group claims to represent 75 percent of the
nation's 90,000 miners, said the workers would begin returning to
work Thursday.
   Strike official Eliseo Macha told The Associated Press the
settlement was contingent on the government publishing a decree
agreeing to miners' collective bargaining demands.
   The strike, organized by the Federation of Mine, Metal and Steel
Workers, began July 18. Since then, it has cost Peru more than $100
million in lost production, according to President Alan Garcia.
   Prime Minister Armando Villanueva and Cantoral, with more than a
dozen other top government and union officials, signed the
agreement late Tuesday night, according to the official gazette El
Peruano.
   The pact calls for the nation's miners to return to work and
gives tentative approval to a major strike demand that all labor
contracts be negotiated jointly, El Peruano said.
   The government and the National Society of Mining and Petroleum,
a private mine owners trade group, earlier had rejected strikers'
main demand for joint negotiations, arguing that each company faced
unique problems.
   Analysts said mine unions were seeking to enhance their
bargaining power position by unifying contract negotiations.
   An official decree recognizing the demand for joint negotiations
was to be issued Thursday, officials said.
   Garcia on Sunday accused communists of manipulating strikers to
destabilize the nation, and threatened to declare the vital mineral
industry in a state of emergency.
   Peru is a leading world producer of silver and copper and major
source of gold, lead and zinc. The country traditionally receives
more than 50 percent of its revenue from mineral exports, which
last year totalled $1.2 billion.
   The miners federation said the strike had paralyzed 90 percent
of the mineral activity.
   Industry analysts said the strike had reduced silver output by
75 percent and copper by 70 percent. State-run Centromin, the
nation's largest mine company, halted exports of copper, lead and
zinc on July 29.
   Peru's mineral industry has been battered with labor strikes
this year due to a declining national economy. Centromin alone has
undergone 36 strikes prior to the nationwide strike, company
officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
