<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ThriftPlan     08-17 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thrift Plan,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Thrift Acquisition Plan Could Be Revealed Thursday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group led by Chicago banker William
Gibson reportedly will acquire up to 13 troubled Texas thrift
institutions, as part of federal plan expected to result in
transactions involving 35 thrifts by the end of August.
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram in Wednesday's editions quoted
sources as saying the Federal Home Loan Bank Board was about to
announce a transaction with the Gibson group, which also includes
Fritts Seslar Investments, a specialist in corporate pension funds
and real estate investments.
   An announcement planned for Wednesday was postponed because of
delays in hammering out final details of the transactions, and
could be made as early as Thursday, the newspaper quoted sources as
saying.
   Gibson, a senior vice president of RepublicBank Corp. from 1981
to 1986, is an executive vice president of Chicago-based
Continental Illinois Bank & Trust Co.
   ``It's a deal we can be proud of,'' said bank board member Roger
Martin. ``It's a good consolidation. It's got cash, and six of the
institutions are high cost-of-funds (thrifts).''
   Such a transaction would achieve the bank board's goals of
injecting new capital into the institutions, reducing the number of
branch offices and eliminating thrifts offering depositors
above-market rates.
   The FHLB says high cost-of-funds thrifts are insolvent savings
and loans that offer offer higher interest rates to lure enough
depositors to stay afloat.
   Martin declined to say how many institutions are involved in the
Gibson group's transaction, but a bank board aide put the number at
eight.
   Other sources told the newspaper the number could be as high as
13 and that most of the thrifts would be small- to medium-sized.
   As of April, the bank board wanted to deal with 123 insolvent
institutions resolved under its so-called Southwest Plan, which is
attempting to revive the troubled Texas savings and loan business
by closing or consolidating a number of institutions.
   On Tuesday, Martin said that by the end of August, 35 insolvent
thrifts would be dealt with.
   Martin repeatedly has said four transactions involving 20
institutions would take place by this Saturday.
   ``We'll come pretty close to meeting that target,'' Martin said
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
