<FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 2358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AutoProfits     08-17 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Auto Profits,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Group: Import Dealers Lost Edge, Overall Profits Declined
Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imported car dealers lost a one-time profit edge
and new car dealers overall saw profits decline as prices went up
in 1987, according to the National Automobile Dealers Association.
   Pretax profits for the average U.S. dealership fell 12.1 percent
in 1987, after declining nearly 2 percent decline in 1986, NADA
said Tuesday.
   The declines followed steadily rising dealer profits from 1981
through 1985.
   The NADA said consumers paid an average of $13,450 for a new
1987 car or truck, up 3.8 percent from an average of $12,950 in
1986.
   Profits dropped partly because fewer vehicles were sold, NADA
said. Also, a decline in the U.S. dollar forced makers of imported
cars to raise prices more than did U.S. companies, the trade group
stated.
   Figures compiled by NADA indicated import dealers accepted lower
profits rather than pass the full amount of their price increases
on to customers, in an effort to remain competitive.
   Import dealerships generally were more profitable than domestic
dealerships in the early 1980s and sometimes were able to sell cars
above list prices, increasing their profit margin, the association
said.
   That brought a scramble among dealers to add foreign brands, but
imports now apparently are no more profitable than domestic cars,
NADA said.
   Average pretax profits at dealerships in 1987 were 1.88 percent
of sales, down from 2.16 percent in 1986 and 2.2 percent in 1985,
the association said.
   The average U.S. dealer had $10.7 million in sales last year, up
from $10.6 million in 1986.
   The number of new cars sold was 10,277,900, down 10 percent from
11,459,300 in 1986.
   NADA is the major trade association for the nation's 25,000 new
car dealerships.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
