<1ST_LINE>u f BC-May-ShoppingCenters     08-17 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-May-Shopping Centers,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>May Co. Enters Partnership To Operate Shopping Centers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   May Department Stores Co. announced Wednesday
it had agreed to operate its shopping center development business
in equal partnership with Prudential Insurance Co. of America and
developer Melvin Simon & Associates Inc.
   A joint venture between Prudential and Melvin Simon, called
PruSimon, will pay about $550 million cash into the May venture,
according to a news release.
   May will contribute the capital stock of May Centers Inc., the
release said. PruSimon will be the managing general partner.
   While certain conditions remain to be satisfied, May said it
anticipated that PruSimon formally would enter into the partnership
within the next 30 days.
   ``The combination of May Centers' strong organization and
excellent shopping centers with the national scope of Simon's
development capabilities and management experience and the
investment expertise of Prudential will significantly enhance May
Centers' value,'' said David C. Farrell, chairman and chief
executive of May.
   May announced July 17 it was discussing the possible sale of a
50 percent interest in the shopping center business in order to
focus more on its retail operations.
   St. Louis-based May is one of the nation's largest retailers,
with operations that included Lord & Taylor, Hecht's, Filene's,
Foley's and Famous Barr department stores and the Caldor and
Venture discount store chains. May also said that under the new
venture, it had the option to have the partnership buy May common
shares up to the approximate $550 million contribution of PruSimon.
   The company also said that any May common stock owned by the
partnership would be treated identically with other May common
stock, including the right to receive dividends, but would not be
voted nor be considered outstanding for voting purposes.
   In addition, half of any shares owned by the partnership would
not be treated as outstanding in computing May's earnings per
share. May's option to sell stock to the partnership can be
exercised by May for up to 60 months after the closing.
   The new partnership will operate May Centers Inc. under the name
May Centers Associates, May said.
</TEXT>
