<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0281,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Sharply Higher In Tokyo; Stocks Up Slightly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning closing, adds quotes.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose sharply against the Japanese
yen Thursday morning, while share prices edged higher on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange.
   The dollar opened at 134.00 yen, up from 133.15 yen at
Wednesday's close, and by late morning was quoted at 133.85 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues rose 21.95 points to finish morning trading at
28,200.81.
   Exchange dealers said the dollar's sharp gain followed its
overnight rise in New York and London trading.
   ``The dollar is basically firm, but profit-taking pushes it down
when it surpasses the 134.00 (yen) mark,'' said a dealer at a U.S.
bank's Tokyo office. ``As a result, the dollar is unlikely to move
out of the range of 132.00-134.00 for a while,'' said the dealer,
who requested anonymity.
   In the stock market, securities dealers said large-capital and
export-related shares were strong, reflecting the dollar's strength
and a market rise overnight on Wall Street.
   ``The Tokyo market's bullishness continues,'' said Ichitaro
Watanabe, a broker at Nikko Securities Co. ``High-tech shares are
being bought to recover yesterday's loss, while most other shares
are also rising.''
</TEXT>
